<BLOCK1><TI>CLAIM OF THE PLAINTIFF</TI>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Parties</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The plaintiff, Rong Wei (&ldquo;<BOLD>Wei</BOLD>&rdquo;), is an individual having an address for service for the Purpose of this proceeding at XXXXXXXXXX.</P>
<P>2. The defendant, Allan Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Chiu</BOLD>&rdquo;), is a businessperson with a residential address at XXXXXXXXXX</P>
<P>3. The defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu, Quuenie Lau and Queenie Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Lau</BOLD>&rdquo;) is a businessperson with a residential address at XXXXXXXXXX.</P>
<P>4. At all material times, Chin and Lau were husband and wife.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Defendants' Representations</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. Starting in or about 2015, Wei was induced to provide funds to Chiu and Lau for the purpose of Chiu purchasing investments on behalf of and for Wei. Wei was induced to provide the funds to Chiu and Lau based on representations made to Wei by Chiu and Lau, including among others:
<P1>(a) Chiu had a Bachelor of Commerce from the Sauder School of Business at the University of British Columbia and a Masters of Business Administration from Brown University;</P1>
<P1>(b) Chiu had considerable experience in investing as a result of high level management positions with the Institutional Buying Department of Goldman Sachs' offices in Hong Kong, Korea, Japan and Singapore;</P1>
<P1>(c) Based on his education and expertise, Chiu could provide sound investment advice to Wei;</P1>
<P1>(d) Chiu, through his &ldquo;retirement&rdquo; account with Goldman Sachs in Hong Kong, was able to purchase IPOs that were not accessible to the public;</P1>
<P1>(e) Chiu would invest funds he received from Wei on her behalf;</P1>
<P1>(f) Chiu would hold on Wei's behalf and for her sole benefit any investments purchased by Chiu using Wei's funds;</P1>
<P1>(g) Lau would assist in managing Wei's investments;</P1>
<P1>(h) Wei would receive a return on her investment of over 20% per annum as a result of having invested through Chiu and Lau; and</P1>
<P1>(i) Wei's investments would be safe.</P1>
(the &ldquo;<BOLD>Representations</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>6. The Representations were intentionally made to Wei by Chiu and Lau.</P>
<P>7. The Representations were false and were made by Chiu and Lau knowing that they were false, without belief in their truth, or reckless as to whether they were true or false.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Piaintiff's Investments with Chiu and Lau</UNDER></TI>
<P>8. In reliance on the Representations or similar statements, Wei provided a total of $1,106,219.26 million in US dollars to Chiu and Lau to be held in trust by them for Wei and to be used for the purchase of certain investments, which would in turn be held in trust by Chiu and/or Lau for the benefit of Wei. In particular, Wei delivered to Chiu and Lau the following amounts for the purpose of purchasing the following investments:
