<P>9. At all material times, Wei provided the above investment funds to Chiu and Lau solely and for the specific purpose of having Chiu use the funds to purchase shares in the above noted companies and markets for and on behalf of Wei.</P>
<P>10. At all materials times, Chiu and Lau were to hold the above funds received from Wei and any investments purchased using those funds in trust and for the sole benefit of Wei.</P>
<P>11. Between July 2015 and August 2016, Wei, Chiu and Lau also entered into various investment agreements with respect to the funds provided by Wei to Chiu and Lau (collectively, the &ldquo;<BOLD>Investment Agreements</BOLD>&rdquo;). Pursuant to certain of the Investment Agreements, dated May 16, 2016 and August 10, 2016, Chiu acknowledged and agreed that the funds provided by Wei would be held in trust by Chiu until October 31, 2016.</P>
<P>12. At all material times, in breach of trust, and contrary to the Representations and the terms of the Investment Agreements, Chiu and Lau did not invest the funds they received from Wei and did not provide Wei a return on her investment, but rather converted Wei's funds to their own uses by putting the investment funds to such uses as they saw fit, the particulars of which are best known to Chiu and Lau.</P>
<P>13. Despite demand from Wei for the return of the full amount provided by her to Chiu and Lau, and in breach of their trust obligations to Wei and the Investment Agreements, as of the current date, Chiu and Lau have only returned to Wei USD$34,000 of the principal amounts she provided to them. Chiu and Lau have failed to return to Wei the remainder of the principal amounts she provided to them or pay her any return on those amounts.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Plaintiff's Payment of Commissions and Management Fees</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. Between 2015 and 2016, Wei further provided to Chiu and Lau funds on account of certain management fees and commissions that were purported to be owed under the Investment Agreements by Wei to Chiu and Lau for their assistance in managing the investments purportedly purchased with Wei's funds.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Promissory Note</UNDER></TI>
<P>15. In November 2016, Wei directed Chiu to sell Wei's investments and transfer the funds back to Wei.</P>
<P>16. At that time, Chiu advised Wei that he was unable to sell her investments until April 1, 2017, which was the start of the next tax year.</P>
<P>17. On November 29, 2016, Chiu and Wei executed an agreement wherein Chiu acknowledged that he owed Wei USD$1.25 million, which consisted of the principal amount Wei had provided to Chiu and Lau for investment purposes and some interest (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Promissory Note</BOLD>&rdquo;). It was a term of the Promissory Note that Chiu would repay Wei USD$1.25 million on April 1, 2017.</P>
<P>18. The Promissory Note further provided that Chiu would use as security for the amount he owed to Wei a property he owned at XXXXXXXXXX</P>
<P>19. From April 1, 2017, with the exception of the USD$34,000 received by Wei, Chiu has failed to pay the principal amount of the Promissory Note, as well as interest on the principal, despite demand.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Defendants' Conspiracy</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. At all material times, Chiu and Lau conspired and/or agreed with each other to induce Wei, and others, to make investments with Chiu and Lau in a fraudulent investment operation run by them.</P>
<P>21. The Representations, the receipt of investment funds in exchange therefor, and the concealment by Chiu and Lau of their fraudulent investment operation were acts committed by Chiu and Lau in furtherance of a conspiracy to defraud investors, including Wei.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Damages suffered by the Plaintiff</UNDER></TI>
<P>22. As a result of the Representations that induced Wei to provide funds to Chiu and Lau for the purchase of certain investments, Chiu's and Lau's breach of trust and/or the conversion of Wei's investment, Wei has suffered losses and damages, the particulars of which include, but are not limited to, the following:
<P1>(a) The loss of USD$1,098,767.00 provided to Chiu and Lau for the sole and specific purpose of Chiu using the funds to purchase certain investments on behalf of Wei, less the US$34,000 received by Wei;</P1>
<P1>(b) Lost opportunity cost in not having the funds provided available for other, legitimate investment opportunities;</P1>
<P1>(c) The loss of funds paid by Wei to Chiu and Lau on the mistaken belief that these amount were due by Wei on account of management fees and commissions that were said to be owed under the Investment Agreements;</P1>
<P1>(d) Such further and additional losses and damages as will be proven at the trial of this action.</P1></P>
<P>23. Further, and in the alternative, as a result of Chiu's default under the Promissory Note, Chiu owes Wei the principal, less the US$34,000 received by Wei, plus interest on the Promissory Note, which remains due and payable.</P>
<P>24. The rate for converting US dollars into Canadian dollars on May 11, 2017 was 1.3707. Applying this conversion rate, as of May 11, 2017:
<ITEM><P>USD$1,098,767.00 would be converted into CAD$1,506,079.93; and</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>USD$1,250,000.00 would be converted into CAD$1,713,375.00.</P></ITEM></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Acquisition of Assets by the Defendants using Wei's Funds</UNDER></TI>
<P>25. The use of Wei's funds by the defendants is best known to them and they have fraudulently failed to disclose those uses to Wei.</P>
<P>26. Unbeknownst to Wei, the defendants, in furtherance of a conspiracy, fraudulently converted some or all of Wei's funds by using them to acquire certain assets, the particulars of which are best known to the defendants.</P>
<P>27. Some or all of the funds provided by Wei to Chiu and Lau or the assets traceable therefrom remain in the possession or control of Chiu, Lau, or corporate entities under their control.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>28. The plaintiff claims the sum of CAD$1,506,079.93 on account of the principal amounts provided by Wei to Chiu and Lau;</P>
<P>29. The plaintiff further claims against the defendants, and each of them, for:
<P1>(a) restitution;</P1>
<P1>(b) general damages;</P1>
<P1>(c) special damages;</P1>
<P1>(d) aggravated damages; and</P1>
<P1>(e) punitive damages;</P1></P>
<P>30. The plaintiff claims that the defendants hold funds invested by the plaintiff and any real or personal property or any other assets purchased with such funds obtained from the fraud perpetrated on the plaintiff as constructive trustees or pursuant to a quistclose trust for the benefit of the plaintiff;</P>
<P>31. The plaintiff claims tracing orders against the defendants and third parties compelling them to deliver records relating to the funds invested by the plaintiff and assets acquired by the defendants or in respect to the fraud perpetrated on the plaintiff;</P>
<P>32. The plaintiff claims interlocutory and permanent injunctions, among other things, restraining the defendants, by themselves their servants, agents or otherwise, from disposing of any of their assets, real or personal, pre-judgment attachment orders, pre-judgment garnishment and for orders compelling third parties to provide information with respect to the funds invested by the plaintiff or assets acquired through such funds;</P>
<P>33. The plaintiff claims an order or judgment of this Honourable Court seeking the assistance of those Courts or tribunals in other jurisdictions which the plaintiff learns or discovers is a jurisdiction where the defendant, or one or more of them, have moved the funds invested by the plaintiff, or has assets which can be traced to such funds;</P>
<P>34. The plaintiff claims interest pursuant to the <EM>Court Order Interest Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 79;</P>
<P>35. The plaintiff claims special costs, or in the alternative, costs; and</P>
<P>36. The plaintiff claims such further and other relief as the nature of the case may require and this Honourable Court may permit.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>37. The plaintiff claims against the defendants, and each of them, on the basis of breach of trust, unjust enrichment, conversion, non-disclosure, breach of contract and fraud, and relies on the common law related thereto.</P>
<P>38. The funds were provided by the plaintiff to the defendants for the sole and specific purpose of the defendants investing the funds on behalf of the plaintiff. The plaintiff is entitled to a declaration of a quistclose trust and associated remedies, because, contrary to the specific purpose for which the plaintiff's funds were advanced, the defendants failed to invest the funds on behalf of the plaintiff.</P>
<P>39. The defendants have without lawful excuse retained, converted or used for their own benefit funds belonging to the plaintiff and monies owed to the plaintiff.</P>
<P>40. Each and all of the defendants conspired as aforesaid to defraud the plaintiff of her investments and to convert the plaintiff's investment funds to their own use.</P>
<P>41. The defendants have been unjustly enriched by the receipt, retention and use of the plaintiff's funds, by achieving a benefit which corresponded to a detriment to the plaintiff, for no juristic reason.</P>
<P>42. The Representations made by the defendants to the plaintiff were false and were made knowing that they were false without belief in their truth, or reckless as to whether they were true or false. The Representations were relied on by the plaintiff and induced the plaintiff to invest with the defendants in their fraudulent investment operation thereby causing loss or damage.</P>
<P>43. The defendants, or one of them, received the proceeds of the fraud perpetrated on the plaintiff or acquired assets with such funds with knowledge, actual or constructive, of such fraud. The defendants had knowledge, actual or constructive, of all material facts set out above including, without limitation, the fact that the defendants were running a fraudulent investment operation as set out above.</P>
<P>44. The plaintiff is entitled to a declaration of constructive trust and associated remedies because the defendants obtained funds from the plaintiff through wrongful means, namely, the Representations and their fraudulent investment operation, and those funds can be traced to the acquisition or improvement of assets by the defendants, the particulars of which are known to the defendants.</P>
<P>45. Further, and in the alternative, Chiu has defaulted on the Promissory Note and the plaintiff is entitled to the amount due under the Promissory Note, which remains un paid.</P>
