<BLOCK1><TI>RESPONSE TO CIVIL CLAIM</TI>
<P>Filed by: ALLAN CHIU (&ldquo;Mr. Chiu&rdquo;) and MUIKWAN QUEENIE LAU also known as MUI KWAN QUEENIE CHIU (&ldquo;Mrs. Chiu&rdquo;), collectively, &ldquo;The Defendants&rdquo;</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>RESPONSE TO NOTICE OF CIVIL CLAIM FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Division"><N>1</N><TI>Defendant's Response to Facts</TI>
<P><P1>1. The facts alleged in paragraphs <UNDER>1 and 4</UNDER> of Part 1 of the Notice of Civil Claim are admitted with the exception that Mr. Chiu's surname is incorrectly spelled in paragraph 4.</P1>
<P1>2. The facts alleged in paragraphs <UNDER>2-3, 5-23 and 25-27</UNDER> of Part 1 of the Notice of Civil Claim are denied.</P1>
<P1>3. The facts alleged in paragraphs <UNDER>24</UNDER> of Part 1 of the Notice of Civil Claim are outside the knowledge of the Defendants.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Division"><N>2</N><TI>Defendants' Version of Facts</TI>
<P><P1>1. Mr. Chiu is retired. Mrs. Chiu is a homemaker. Together, they have resided in rental premise at XXXXXXXXXX since 2013. They been residents of Canada since 2010 and are both Canadian citizens.</P1>
<P1>2. The Plaintiff has a residential address at XXXXXXXXXX as well as a residential address at XXXXXXXXXX, Yi Yuan Ju Xiao Qu, XXXXXXXXXX XXXXXXXXXX</P1>
<P1>3. The Plaintiff is a citizen of both Canada and the Peoples' Republic of China.</P1>
<P1>4. The Defendants deny that either of them made to the Plaintiff any of the representations as alleged by the Plaintiff in paragraph 5 of the Notice of Civil Claim herein (the &ldquo;NOCC&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>5. The Plaintiff first met the Defendants in or about January 2015 through a tennis club at which their respective children played tennis.</P1>
<P1>6. From their first meeting, the Plaintiff wished to talk to the Defendants almost entirely about her interest in stock trading and other investments and the poor returns she was receiving on her investments. The Defendants had no interest in discussing these subjects with the Plaintiff but the Plaintiff persisted and, at times, the Defendant, Mr. Chiu, listen ed to the Plaintiff only out of politeness. Later, in or about April and May 2015, the Plaintiff sought to develop a friendship with Mrs. Chiu and to use that friendship with Mrs. Chiu to influence and persuade Mr. Chiu to give the Plaintiff some friendly advice as to which stocks or other investments the Plaintiff should consider purchasing.</P1>
<P1>7. At all relevant times between early 2016 and early April 2017, Mr. Chiu and the Plaintiff were willing partners and participants in an intimate romantic and sexual relationship unknown to Mrs. Chiu and the Plaintiff told Mr. Chiu that the relationship was also unknown to the Plaintiff's husband. Mrs. Chiu learned of the relationship between Mr. Chiu and the Plaintiff in late 2016. It is unknown to the Defendants when or if the Plaintiff's husband became aware of the relationship between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu.</P1>
<P1>8. Once the relationship began between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu, the Plaintiff avoided contact with Mrs. Chiu.</P1>
<P1>9. The relationship between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu was more than an extramarital affair. Mr. Chiu was involved in nearly every facet of the Plaintiff's life, including accompanying the Plaintiff on visits to her doctor; meeting with the Plaintiff's son's school principal; meeting with the Plaintiff's daughter's university counsellors; dealing with the Plaintiff's real estate agents with respect to the Plaintiff's properties in Las Vegas, Nevada, USA; meeting with the Plaintiff's tax accountants regarding tax planning; as well as discussing and helping the Plaintiff with her stock trading activities, successfully helping her earn over USD$300,000 in profits in the year 2016 as well as other significant trading profits in the period January to April 2017.</P1>
<P1>10. Mr. Chiu did whatever he could to assist the Plaintiff in her life because he and the Plaintiff were in love and Mr. Chiu and the Plaintiff considered each other to be part of each other's families.</P1>
<P1>11. During the relevant time period, the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu were together almost every day and they travelled together to, amongst other places, Singapore where the Plaintiff requested Mr. Chiu to assist the Plaintiff in meeting with lawyers to acquire a British Virgin Islands shelf company, Century Lane Investments Ltd., to shelter assets from Canadian taxation and to Europe for vacation and to investigate potential investment opportunities for the Plaintiff.</P1>
<P1>12. Following a trip which the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu took together to Singapo re in June 2016, the Plaintiff raised the subject of their living together and she discussed with Mr. Chiu on many occasions their eventually living together. The Plaintiff informed Mr. Chiu that, while she wished to live together with Mr. Chiu, her divorce/separation agreement with her husband prohibited the Plaintiff from cohabiting until the Plaintiff's son had reached the age of 18 and was enrolled in university and Plaintiff did not wish to risk her husband's ceasing to make support payments for her children. In the Autumn of 2016, the Plaintiff discussed with Mr. Chiu and considered purchasing an additional home in Vancouver, close to their respective homes so that the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu would have a private place to meet away from the Plaintiff's home.</P1>
<P1>13. The Plaintiff asked Mr. Chiu to assist her in corresponding and negotiating with one of her investment consultants, RBC Dominion Securities, the matter of compensation for losses on investments which she denied having authorized. Mr. Chiu did assist the Plaintiff in that regard in or about December 2015 and January 2016 and succeeded in obtaining for the Plaintiff compensation payments from RBC Dominion Securities in excess of CAD$25,000.</P1>
<P1>14. At all relevant times, the Plaintiff trusted and sought out the advice of Mr. Chiu with respect to potential investments. Out of love and affection for the Plaintiff, Mr. Chiu provided to the Plaintiff, to the best of his abilities, investment advice and counsel based on his understanding of the markets and his own investment experience and not on the basis of any professional qualifications or for any compensation.</P1>
<P1>15. In or about June 2015, the Plaintiff, dissatisfied with the investment results obtained for her by her account manager at CIBC Wood Gundy, chose to manage her own investments and moved most or all of her holdings from Wood Gundy into investment accounts in Hong Kong held in the name of the Plaintiff's mother, Wang Xian. The Plaintiff suffered losses in those accounts exceeding USD$1 Million within a few weeks.</P1>
<P1>16. In or about June 2015, in an effort to stop her losses, the Plaintiff requested that Mr, Chiu assist the Plaintiff in managing the Hong Kong investment accounts and Mr. Chiu helped the Plaintiff manage those accounts until April 2017. As well, from in or about August 2015, Mr, Chiu helped the Plaintiff manage a CIBC Investor's Edge account until April 2017.</P1>
<P1>17. The Plaintiff's Hong Kong investment accounts in her mother's name were self-directed investment accounts held by the firm, Essence International (also known as Anxin). Prior to Mr, Chiu being asked by the Plaintiff to help her manage those accounts, the Plaintiff had personally managed those accounts poorly and accused Essence International of misappropriating HKD$1.6 Million. Later, the Plaintiff requested that Mr. Chiu help her negotiate compensation from Essence International and Mr. Chiu did his best to assist the Plaintiff until it became clear that the Plaintiff's claims were inaccura te and that her losses had resulted from her own miscalculations.</P1>
<P1>18. On some occasions, the Plaintiff would purchase directly those investments recommended to her by Mr. Chiu. On other occasions, the Plaintiff would supply funds to Mr. Chiu on the understanding and agreement that he would purchase for the Plaintiff in either the Plaintiff's name or, as directed by the Plaintiff, in the name of the Plaintiff's mother those investments which Mr. Chiu had recommended.</P1>
<P1>19. On some occasions, funds provided to Mr. Chiu by the Plaintiff for investment purchases remained in Mr. Chiu's control after the Plaintiff changed her mind about the investments or the investments were no longer available to her. On those occasions, Mr. Chiu held the funds for the Plaintiff and, with the Plaintiff's full knowledge and agreement, Mr. Chiu used some of those funds to settle some of his own debts.</P1>
<P1>20. In allowing Mr. Chiu to use some of the funds for his own purposes under the terms of a conditional loan, the Plaintiff agreed to modify and did modify the terms of the two account management agreements dated July 4, 2015 which the Plaintiff has incorrectly described as investment agreements in paragraph 11 of the NOCC and the Plaintiff also agreed to modify and did modify the terms of the two investment agreements dated respectively May 16, 2016 and August 10, 2016 described in paragraph 11 of the NOCC. The Defendant, Mrs. Chiu, was not a party to any investment agreements with the Plaintiff dated May 16, 2016, August 10, 2016 or any other investment agreement with the Plaintiff. The Defendant, Mrs. Chiu, executed the two account management agreements dated July 4, 2015 on behalf of Mr. Chiu and not in her personal capacity and Mrs. Chiu neither h ad the skills to provide services nor did she provide services to the Plaintiff under the account management agreements.</P1>
<P1>21. The Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu were planning their future together and the Plaintiff was in complete agreement with Mr. Chiu using some of her funds for his own purposes on the basis and understanding that the Plaintiff's funds used for Mr. Chiu's own purposes were loaned by the Plaintiff to Mr. Chiu on the condition that he would repay those fun ds when he was able to do so. The Plaintiff expressed to Mr. Chiu that he was free to use the Plaintiff's funds for his own purposes and that she was grateful to Mr. Chiu for guiding her in her investments and helping her make sizeable returns on those investments.</P1>
<P1>22. In that regard, one part of the relationship between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu was and remains one of creditor and debtor and the loan or loans made by the Plaintiff to Mr. Chiu were conditional loans. The Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu agreed again in or about October 2016 that Mr. Chiu would repay any indebtedness owed to the Plaintiff only when he was able to do so but, also, that Mr. Chiu could repay the indebtedness by continuing to help the Plaintiff trade stocks in her trading accounts without compensation but that trading profits earned in those trading accounts as a result of Mr. Chiu's advice and guidance would be treated by the Plaintiff as payment by him to reduce the said indebtedness. The Plaintiff told Mr. Chiu that she trusted him and his proven ability to generate a good return on the Plaintiff's investments on a consistent basis. The Plaintiff treated her assets as joint assets of herself and Mr. Chiu and often told Mr. Chiu that they were going to be together and share everything.</P1>
<P1>23. With the exception of the sum of USD$31,892.00 on October 16, 2015 and the sum of USD$7,000 on October 21, 2015, Mr. Chiu admits the receipt of funds from the Plaintiff as described in paragraph 8 of the NOCC but does not admit that the funds were provided to him for the purpose of purchasing for the Plaintiff the investments listed in paragraph 8 of the NOCC.</P1>
<P1>24. Mrs. Chiu denies the receipt of any funds from the Plaintiff.</P1>
<P1>25. In or about mid-November 2016, when the Plaintiff learned that Mr. Chiu had travelled to Hong Kong with Mrs. Chiu, the Plaintiff became very jealous and her attitude toward Mr. Chiu and the loans changed. The Plaintiff sent text and email messages to Mr. Chiu demanding that he sell for her various stocks when she knew that Mr. Chiu had not purchased those stocks for the Plaintiff and when she knew that the related funds had been loaned to Mr. Chiu by the Plaintiff.</P1>
<P1>26. When Mr. Chiu returned from Hong Kong in or about late November 2016, the romantic and sexual relationship between him and the Plaintiff resumed and the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu were together almost every day for lunch, dinner and other outings as a couple.</P1>
<P1>27. Mr. Chiu denies signing any promissory note in favour of the Plaintiff.</P1>
<P1>28. From in or about the Autumn of 2015, Mr. Chiu assisted the Plaintiff with many aspects of her personal life. For example, during late 2016 and early 2017, Mr. Chiu accompanied the Plaintiff to meet her son's school principal, accompanied the Plaintiff to a fund-raising event for her son's school, helped the Plaintiff plan her family vacation to Hawaii and provided numerous other aids to the Plaintiff as might be expected of a spouse, including helping the Plaintiff trade stock in the Hong Kong investment trading account with Essence International and in the US investment trading account with CIBC Investor's Edge without receiving any compensation from the Plaintiff.</P1>
<P1>29. During the period 2015&ndash;2017, much correspondence was conducted between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu by way of &ldquo;WeChat&rdquo;, an online messaging service which facilitates text messaging in Cantonese or Mandarin languages as well as other languages. The Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu exchanged thousands of messages via WeChat using the Plaintiff's WeChat ID, Eliza7117.</P1>
<P1>30. In early April 2017, the Plaintiff again became jealous that Mr. Chiu was spending more time with Mrs. Chiu and that they were attempting to reconcile. The Plaintiff began reminding Mr. Chiu often of his indebtedness to her and Mr. Chiu told the Plaintiff that he would make payments to her as and when he was able to do so. In keeping with tha t arrangement, Mr. Chiu made payments of USD$14,000 and USD$20,000 respectively to the Plaintiff in the month of April 2017. Mr. Chiu told the Plaintiff in mid -May 2017 that he would make a further payment of USD$70,000 in May but the Plaintiff commenced t his action and sought an order freezing Mr. Chiu's assets before he could make the proposed payment.</P1>
<P1>31. At the Plaintiff's request, Mr. Chiu conversed with the Plaintiff's tax accountant, Mr. Tony Yu, in April 2017 regarding the Plaintiff's loan to Mr. Chiu and whether or not that loan could be accounted for as a doubtful account because the Plaintiff wanted to write off the loan as a bad debt for tax purposes.</P1>
<P1>32. To date, Mr. Chiu has been able to make partial payments on his indebtedness to the Plaintiff but has not been able to pay that indebtedness in full. Mr. Chiu remains ready to enter into a payment schedule with the Plaintiff provided that he has access to his assets to make payments to the Plaintiff and provided that there be a full accounting of the indebtedness.</P1>
<P1>33. Mrs. Chiu played no part at all in the meetings, text messaging or discussions between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu concerning prospective or actual stock trading or investments by the Plaintiff. Mrs. Chiu gave no investment advice to the Plaintiff and received no compensation from the Plaintiff. Mrs. Chiu did not conspire in any way with Mr. Chiu and was not aware of any details of investments suggested to the Plaintiff by Mr. Chiu.</P1>
<P1>34. The Plaintiff's allegations as against the Defendants in fraud are entirely without merit and are based on the jealousy of a disgruntled lover and on the Plaintiff's seeking vengeance for the Defendants' marital reconciliation.</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>RESPONSE TO RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P><P1>1. The Defendant Mr. Chiu consents to the granting of the relief sought in paragraphs <BOLD>NIL</BOLD> of Part 2 of the Notice of Civil Claim.</P1>
<P1>2. The Defendant Mrs. Chiu consents to the granting of the relief sought in paragraphs <BOLD>NIL</BOLD> of Part 2 of the Notice of Civil Claim.</P1>
<P1>3. The Defendants oppose the granting of the relief sought in paragraphs 28 through 36 of Part 2 of the Notice of Civil Claim.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P><P1>1. The Defendant Mrs. Chiu did not enter into a relationship in trust or contract with the Plaintiff, received no funds from the Plaintiff and had no participation in or knowledge of the dealings between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu.</P1>
<P1>2. Funds which were supplied to the Defendant Mr. Chiu by the Plaintiff and which may have been impressed with a trust in favour of the Plaintiff were released by the Plaintiff to Mr. Chiu by amending any trust relationship and specifically providing the subject funds to Mr. Chiu pursuant to a conditional loan contract.</P1>
<P1>3. The relationship between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu was an intimate and familial one and it is in the context of the nature of that relationship that a conditional loan was made by the Plaintiff in favour of Mr. Chiu.</P1>
<P1>4. The contractual relationship between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu is that of debtor and creditor pursuant to a conditional loan agreement</P1>
<P1>5. The Plaintiff alleges a fraud and the Defendants deny any fraud and put the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P1>
<P1>6. The Plaintiff alleges an unjust enrichment and the Defendant Mrs. Chiu claims no enrichment at all and the Defendant Mr. Chiu claims a juridical reason for his enrichment, specifically, a contract in debt.</P1>
<P1>7. The Plaintiff alleges a breach of trust and the Defendant Mrs. Chiu claims no trust relationship existed between her and the Plaintiff and the Defendant Mr. Chiu claims that any trust relationship which did exist between him and the Plaintiff was modified and or extinguished by the loan agreements made between the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu.</P1></P>
