<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application without notice will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge or master at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia on May 16, 2017 at 9:45 am for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiff be at liberty to serve a copy of the Notice of Civil Claim upon the Defendant, Allan Chiu, by leaving a copy of the Notice of Civil Claim and a copy of the attached Order at the door of his residence located at XXXXXXXXXX XXXXXXXXXX by emailing them to the Defendant, Allan Chiu, at allan@allanchiuconsulting.asia, and sending a WeChat message to the Defendant, Allan Chiu, advising that the Notice of Civil Claim had been sent to him by email, and such service shall be good and sufficient service on the Defendant, Allan Chiu.</P>
<P>2. The Plaintiff be at liberty to serve a copy of the Notice of Civil Claim upon the Defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu, by sending by email a copy of the Notice of Civil Claim and a copy of the attached Order to the Defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu, at XXXXXXXXXX and sending a WeChat message to the Defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu, advising that the Notice of Civil Claim had been sent to her by email, and such service shall be good and sufficient service on the Defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. On May 12, 2017, the Plaintiff, Rong Wei (&ldquo;<BOLD>Wei</BOLD>&rdquo;), filed the Notice of Civil Claim seeking, among other things, a judgment against the Defendants in the approximate amount of $1.5 million pius interest, on account of funds provided to the Defendants for the purchase of shares to be held on behalf of and in trust for Wei.</P>
<P>2. The Defendant, Allan Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Chiu</BOLD>&rdquo;), is an individual who to the best of Wei's information, ordinarily resides at XXXXXXXXXX (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Birney Property</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. The Defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Lau</BOLD>&rdquo;), is an individual who at all materials times was married to Chiu.</P>
<P>4. Wei intends to file an application in the within proceedings seeking a Mareva injunction freezing Chiu's and Lau's assets.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Defendants' Residence</EM></TI>
<P>1. Wei has known Chiu and Lau since 2014.</P>
<P>2. During that time, Wei was advised by Chiu that he and Lau lived at the Birney Property and visited them both there.</P>
<P>5. Subsequently, Chiu advised Wei that Lau was no longer living at the Birney Property and that he did not know where Lau was or how to contact her.</P>
<P>6. At this time, Wei has no information regarding the whereabouts of Lau.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Attempted Service of Chiu at the Birney Property</EM></TI>
<P>3. Prior to Wei commencing this action, Chiu had arranged to meet with Wei on May 14, 2017. Chiu had promised that at that meeting he would return to Wei some of the funds she had provided to him.</P>
<P>4. On May 12, 2017, Chiu called Wei and cancelled the May 14, 2017 meeting. Chiu told Wei that he was not able to meet with her, because he was very sick and not able to go out. Chiu also told Wei that he was ill and staying with relatives in Richmond, British Columbia, but he did not tell her where in Richmond he was staying.</P>
<P>5. Wei does not believe that Chiu was telling her the truth when he said he was staying in Richmond, because he has told her so many lies during the course of their relationship.</P>
<P>7. On the evening of May 12, 2017, Wei attended at the Birney Property in an effort to try to serve Chiu with the Notice of Civil Claim. There was no indication that anyone was home at the Birney Property and the Defendants' car was not in their parking spot.</P>
<P>8. Over the course of the next two days, Wei attended at the Birney Property three times at various times of the day. On each of Wei's visits, there was no indication that anyone was home at the Birney Property and the Defendants' car was not in their parking spot.</P>
<P>9. Thereafter, on the morning of May 15, 2017, Wei attended again at the Birney Property to try to serve Chiu with the Notice of Civil Claim. On that visit, Wei knocked on the front door to the Birney Property, but no one answered. There was no indication that anyone was home and the Defendants' car was not in their parking spot. Wei also looked around the Defendants' neighborhood and was unable to locate their car.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Defendants' Contact Information</EM></TI>
<P>10. Throughout Wei's involvement with Chiu, Chiu and Wei communicated using email and WeChat. During that time, Chiu used the following email address: <UNDER>allan@allanchiuconsulting.asia.</UNDER> Chiu's WeChat username is: AllanC1001.</P>
<P>11. Wei and Lau also communicate by WeChat. Lau's WeChat username is: QueenieC1001. In addition, Chiu also provided Wei with the following email address by Lau, as well as himself: XXXXXXXXXX.</P>
<P>12. Previously, Lau also provided Wei with her cellphone number. Wei has tried calling Lau's cellphone number to arrange a meeting to serve her with the Notice of Civil Claim, but Lau did not pick up Wei's call and the call did not go to voicemail.</P>
<P>13. If a copy of the Notice of Civil Claim is emailed to Chiu and Lau and a WeChat message is sent to them advising that the Notice of Civil Claim has been emailed, it is likely that they will receive the Notice of Civil Claim.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. Under Rule 4-3(1) of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, unless the Court otherwise orders, a Notice of Civil must be served by personal service.</P>
<P>2. Pursuant to Rule 4-4(1) of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, the Court may, on application without notice, make an order for substituted service granting permission to use an alternative method of service.</P>
<P>3. The Court may grant an order for substituted service if it is impracticable to serve a document by personal service or if the person to be served by personal service
<P1>(a) cannot be found after a diligent search, or</P1>
<P1>(b) is evading service of the documents.</P1></P>
<P>4. The Plaintiff has made diligent efforts to serve Mr. Chiu. Mr. Chiu either cannot be found, or is likely already aware of this claim and evading service.</P>
<P>5. To the best of the Plaintiff's information Lau no longer lives at the Birney Property and the Plaintiff has no other information regarding Lau's whereabouts. Due to the urgency and nature of this matter, it would be impractical for the Plaintiff to be required to serve Lau personally.</P>
<P>6. In the event the Court grants the order sought, there is no reason to believe that the Notice of Civil Claim will not come to the attention of the Defendants.</P>
<P>7. In the circumstances, it would be just for the Court to exercise its discretion to grant the order sought.</P></BLOCK2>
