<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>AFFIDAVIT</UNDER></TI>
<P>I, <BOLD>RONG (ELIZA) WEI</BOLD>, of Vancouver, British Columbia, housewife, SWEAR (OR AFFIRM) THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am the plaintiff in this action and as such have knowledge of the matters hereinafter referred to save and except where stated to be based on information and belief and where so stated, I verily believe same to be true.</P>
<P>2. I moved to Vancouver from China seven years ago. I am currently a housewife. I have a Master's degree in finance from the Dongbei University of Finance and Economics in China. Previously, I worked for the credit card department of the China Construction Bank in China.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Introduction</EM></TI>
<P>3. I first met Allan Chiu and his wife Queenie Lau in 2014 at the River Club in Richmond, B.C. where our respective children were taking tennis lessons. Over the course of watching our children's lessons, we got to know each other socially.</P>
<P>4. In the course of our discussions, I told Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau that I had some money that I wanted to invest in Hong Kong equities and that I was looking for investment advice.</P>
<P>5. Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau told me that Mr. Chiu was an experienced investor and could assist me with investments in Hong Kong and elsewhere. They told me, in particular, that Mr. Chiu:
<P1>a. had a Bachelor of Commerce from the Sauder School of Business at the University of British Columbia and a Masters of Business Administration from Brown University;</P1>
<P1>b. had considerable experience in investing as a result of high level positions with Goldman Sachs' offices in Hong Kong, Korea, Japan and Singapore, including most recently before he retired working as the Department Head of the Asia Pacific (Including Japan) Institutional Buying Side of Goldman Sachs' Hong Kong office;</P1>
<P1>c. when he had worked at Goldman Sachs, he had been responsible for managing a portfolio of USD$20 billion for institutional clients;</P1>
<P1>d. had worked as a consultant for companies after his retirement from Goldman Sachs, like a Singapore state-owned holding company named Temasek, where he had made approximately USD$2 million per year, Progress Energy and other large companies in Dubai; and</P1>
<P1>e. had worked for Petronas Petroliam Nasional Berhad.</P1></P>
<P>6. At first Mr. Chiu identified a couple of stocks, which I observed. These stocks performed relatively well, which further led me to believe Mr. Chiu had significant investment experience.</P>
<P>7. In or about August 2015 I gave Mr. Chiu the password to one of my small investment accounts, so he could manage that account on my behalf (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Wei CIBC Account</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>8. I later gave him the password to a larger investment account registered in my mother's name, so he could manage that account also.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Goldman Sachs Account</EM></TI>
<P>9. In the spring of 2015 Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau recommended that I invest in the U.S. stock market. In particular, they recommended that I purchase U.S. IPOs.</P>
<P>10. To do so, they told me I needed to transfer money to Mr. Chiu so that he could make investments on my behalf using his &ldquo;retirement&rdquo; trust account with Goldman Sachs in Hong Kong (the &ldquo;GS Account&rdquo;). Mr. Chiu told me that he had received the GS Account, because of his former employment with Goldman Sachs. Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau told me that, through the GS Account, Mr. Chiu could purchase good IPOs that were not accessible to the public and that, as a result, I would make a better return on my investments, which they estimated at over 20% per year.</P>
<P>11. Mr. Chiu also told me that he had USD$26.3 million of his own money in the GS Account.</P>
<P>12. Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau told me that I would only be able to benefit from this preferential access if the investments were purchased for me by Mr. Chiu through the GS Account and in Mr. Chiu's name. To facilitate this, they told me that I would need to transfer funds into Mr. Chiu's name through Ms. Lau's bank account with the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, account number XXXXXXXXXX (the &ldquo;<BOLD>CIBC Account</BOLD>&rdquo;). While at times I provided Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau with cash, the majority of the funds I provided to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau between 2015 and 2016 were transferred from my account to the CIBC Account.</P>
<P>13. I understood that Mr. Chiu would hold any shares he purchased for me on my behalf and in trust for me.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Investment in TRU</EM></TI>
<P>14. In June 2015 Mr. Chiu recommended that I invest in an IPO being issued by TransUnion (stock symbol TRU). He described this as a very good investment that would likely yield a return of 20% in 6 months.</P>
<P>15. To enable him to purchase the TRU shares on my behalf, Mr. Chiu instructed me to provide Ms. Lau USD$200,000, which she would in turn provide to him to deposit in the GS Account.</P>
<P>16. I agreed to do so and, on June 23, 2015, provided USD$162,000 to Ms. Lau and subsequently, on June 26, 2015, provided the remaining balance of USD$38,000 to Ms. Lau. These funds were provided to Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in TRU on my behalf.</P>
<P>17. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibits &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> and <BOLD>&ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> are copies of the bank drafts evidencing these payments to Ms. Lau. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of one of the bank drafts that was signed by Ms. Lau when I provided it to her.</P>
<P>18. Mr. Chiu told me that he purchased on my behalf 8888 shares of the TRU IPO at a share price of USD$22.50/per share.</P>
<P>19. About the time I made these payments, I asked Mr. Chiu if he could execute a share pledge to show that he held the TRU shares on my behalf. Mr. Chiu told me that it was most important that I trust him and that he was not prepared to invest on my behalf if I did not do so.</P>
<P>20. I also asked Mr. Chiu to provide me with evidence, like a screen shot, that he had purchased the TRU shares, but he told me that because my purchase was part of a much larger institutional transaction made through Goldman Sachs he was unable to provide evidence of the transaction he had made for me.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The 2015 Investment Agreements</EM></TI>
<P>21. About this time I suggested to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau that we enter into some form of agreement to evidence that they were managing, and holding on my behalf, my investments.</P>
<P>22. Because he was still managing my mother's Hong Kong account, Mr. Chiu suggested we enter into two agreements, which he prepared:
<P1>a. an agreement in respect of my mother's Hong Kong account, a copy of which is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD>; and</P1>
<P1>b. a second agreement in respect of U.S. shares he would purchase through the GS Account, as well as the shares I held in the Wei CIBC Account (the &ldquo;US Agreement of Undertaking&rdquo;), a copy of which is attached hereto as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P>23. Mr. Chiu told me that, because he was not certified in Canada, he could not sign these investment agreements and it is for this reason that Ms. Lau signed them instead.</P>
<P>24. At the time I signed the US Agreement of Undertaking, I provided Ms. Lau with USD$3,967 in cash, representing the US equivalent of the CAD$5,000 management fee under that agreement.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Investment in RACE</EM></TI>
<P>25. In October 2015 Mr. Chiu recommended that I invest in an IPO being issued by Ferrari NV (stock symbol RACE). He again described this as a very good investment opportunity.</P>
<P>26. Mr. Chiu advised me that he would sell approximately 3,494 of the TRU shares he had purchased on my behalf and use the proceeds, approximately USD$89,383, from that sale to buy RACE shares for me.</P>
<P>27. To enable him to purchase further RACE shares on my behalf, Mr. Chiu instructed me to provide to Ms. Lau an additional USD$86,892, which she would in turn provide to him.</P>
<P>28. I agreed to do so and, on October 15, 2015, provided USD$55,000 to Ms. Lau and subsequently, on October 16, 2015, provided the remaining balance of USD$31,892 to Ms. Lau. These funds were provided to Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in RACE on my behalf.</P>
<P>29. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibits &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> and <BOLD>&ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD> are copies of the transaction records evidencing these payments to the CIBC Account.</P>
<P>30. On October 17, 2015, Mr. Chiu provided me with a summary of the investments he had made on my behalf. A copy of this report is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD>, along with print outs showing the value in my investment accounts as of August 25, 2015 and October 17, 2015.</P>
<P>31. On October 17, 2015, Mr. Chiu also provided me with a summary of the commissions and management fees he had incurred to date. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of this summary.</P>
<P>32. After providing this summary, Mr, Chiu advised me that the price for the RACE shares was higher than he had expected and that he required an additional USD$7,000.00 to complete the purchase. Mr. Chiu told me that this additional amount was required because the share price for the RACE shares had increased from USD$50 per share to USD$52 per share.</P>
<P>33. On October 21, 2015 I provided this amount to Ms. Lau. This amount was provided to Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu again for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in RACE on my behalf.</P>
<P>34. On December 8, 2015 I paid to Ms. Lau the management fees indicated on Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;.</P>
<P>35. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</BOLD> are copies of my bank records evidencing these payments, as well as an additional payment for their management fee.</P>
<P>36. On December 6, 2015, Mr. Chiu provided me with a summary of the investments he had made on my behalf. A copy of this report is attached hereto as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo;</BOLD>, along With print outs showing the value in my investment accounts as of December 6, 2015.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Investment in Airbnb</EM></TI>
<P>37. In January 2016 Mr. Chiu recommended that I invest USD$960,000 in an IPO being issued by Airbnb. He again indicated to me that this would be a good investment that would yield significant returns. He further indicated to me that he expected that the investment would double in a year.</P>
<P>38. I was not prepared, nor was I able, to invest USD$960,000 in the Airbnb IPO, but I agreed to provide Mr. Chiu with USD$64,000 to enable him to purchase Airbnb shares on my behalf. Mr. Chiu instructed me to provide to Ms. Lau USD$64,000, which she would in turn provide to him.</P>
<P>39. I agreed to do so and, on January 5, 2016, provided USD$69,899.91 to Ms. Lau. This payment represented the USD$64,000 investment amount and an amount owing for management fees. The USD$64,000 was provided to Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in Airbnb on my behalf.</P>
<P>40. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;L&rdquo;</BOLD> are copies of my bank records evidencing these payments, as well as an additional payment for their management fee.</P>
<P>41. Although I had advised Mr. Chiu that I did not have USD$960,000 to invest in Airbnb, he suggested that I pay what I could at that time and he would cover the rest of the investment until I had more cash. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;M&rdquo;</BOLD> is an email dated January 20, 2016 to this effect, enclosing an agreement he prepared.</P>
<P>42. The email address Mr. Chiu uses to communicate with me is: <UNDER>allan@allanchiuconsulting.asia</UNDER> This led me to believe that Mr. Chiu had set up a consulting company.</P>
<P>43. After I had provided Mr. Chiu with the USD$64,000 to purchase shares in Airbnb on my behalf, Mr. Chiu advised me that Airbnb had not gone through with the IPO and so he had not purchased any shares in Airbnb.</P>
<P>44. Mr. Chiu did not return to me the USD$64,000 I had provided in January 2016. This caused me some concern and I asked Mr. Chiu over WeChat to provide me with proof that he was holding the investments he had made to date for me, and also provide proof of the assets he said he owned. In response to my message, we exchanged emails, copies of which are attached and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;N&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>45. I subsequently met with Mr. Chiu and he assured me he was acting in my best interests, cared about my well-being and was holding my investment in trust for me. Given these reassurances, I did not persist in asking him for additional information concerning the investments he was holding on my behalf.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Involvement of Ms. Lau</EM></TI>
<P>46. The investments described to above were discussed in the presence of Ms. Lau. In these conversations Ms. Lau often reinforced and agreed with what Mr. Chiu suggested I do.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Investment in UK</EM></TI>
<P>47. In May 2016 Mr. Chiu recommended that I invest in the United Kingdom.</P>
<P>48. Mr. Chiu advised me that the UK market was undervalued as a result of the uncertainty posed by the UK's upcoming referendum on the European Union. He told me that he had learned that Goldman Sachs advisors were predicting a &ldquo;no&rdquo; vote on the referendum and when that occurred, the UK stock market would rise approximately 20%.</P>
<P>49. I was reluctant to invest any more money but Mr. Chiu persisted and repeated to me that this was a very good investment.</P>
<P>50. Mr. Chiu told me that he would use the USD$64,000, which I had provided him in January 2016 for investing in Airbnb, to buy shares in the UK market for me.</P>
<P>51. Mr. Chiu recommended that I invest a further USD$500,000, but I indicated that I was unable to invest this amount of money. Mr. Chiu then told me that if I could invest USD$300,000 he would invest the balance using his own funds.</P>
<P>52. On May 16, 2016, Mr. Chiu presented me with another investment agreement concerning the UK investments. Around this time, Mr. Chiu had separated from Ms. Lau. Mr. Chiu therefore signed the agreement himself. He told me that, because we knew each other better, it was now okay for him to sign investment agreements himself. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;O&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of this agreement.</P>
<P>53. I agreed to invest a further USD$300,000 and, on May 17, 2016, provided USD$300,000 to Mr. Chiu through the CIBC Account, which was the same account that I had used to provide funds to Ms. Lau in the past. These funds were provided to Mr. Chiu for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in the UK market on my behalf.</P>
<P>54. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;P&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of my bank records evidencing this payment.</P>
<P>55. In August 2016 I sold a property in Las Vegas for net proceeds of USD$248,891.20. When Mr. Chiu learned of this he pressured me to invest an additional USD$200,000, to cover the investment he had made with me in May 2016.</P>
<P>56. On August 10, 2016, Mr. Chiu presented me with another investment agreement concerning this further UK investment. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;Q&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of this agreement.</P>
<P>57. I agreed to invest a further USD$200,000 in the UK market and, on August 5, 2016, provided USD$200,000 to Mr. Chiu through the CIBC Account. These funds were provided to Mr. Chiu for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in the UK market on my behalf.</P>
<P>58. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;R&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of my bank records evidencing this payment.</P>
<P>59. On August 10, 2016, Mr. Chiu provided me with another summary of the investments he had made on my behalf. A copy of this report is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;S&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>60. In October 2016 Mr. Chiu recommended that I invest in an IPO being issued by a bank with a stock symbol of NTB. Mr. Chiu told me that he had learned that Goldman Sachs would be acquiring this bank, causing its share price to increase significantly.</P>
<P>61. Initially, I told Mr. Chiu that I did not want to purchase any stock in NTB at that time, but Mr. Chiu continued to recommend to me that I invest in NTB. Mr. Chiu advised me that he had bought some shares in NTB and that they had already increased in value. He offered to sell me some of those shares at the price he had purchased them at, because of our good relationship and because he needed some money for his daughter's schooling.</P>
<P>62. I agreed to invest a further USD$240,875 and, on October 12, 2016, provided USD$240,875 to Mr. Chiu through the same account that I had paid Ms. Lau in the past. These funds were provided to Mr. Chiu for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in a bank with a stock symbol of NTB on my behalf, and in selling to me shares he had already purchased in NTB.</P>
<P>63. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;T&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of my bank records evidencing this payment.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Summary of my Involvement with Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau</EM></TI>
<P>64. Between June 2015 and October 2016, I provided over USD$1,100,000 to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau for the sole and specific purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing investments on my behalf. I relied upon the representations made to me by Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau, as set out in paragraph 4 above, in deciding to provide this money to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau.</P>
<P>65. At all times, it was my understanding and intention that any shares purchased using the funds I provided to Ms. Lau and through her Mr. Chiu would be held on my behalf and in trust for me.</P>
<P>66. Mr. Chiu also told me a number of times that he held properties around the world, including a house and apartment in Singapore and a property in San Francisco. He also told me that Ms. Lau owned a townhouse in London's W8 district. I further relied upon Mr. Chiu's representations to me that he owned a lot of valuable property in deciding to provide my money to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau.</P>
<P>67. Between June 2015 and October 2016, I also provided Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau with payments for commissions and management fees that they told me were owed as a result of them managing my investments. During this time, I gave Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau approximately USD$44,000 on account of commissions and management fees.</P>
<P>68. In 2016 I became more friendly with Mr. Chiu and he asked me to accompany him on trips to Europe and Singapore. Mr. Chiu would spend lavishly on these trips. He would pay for us to fly business class, dine in Michelin star restaurants and stay in luxury hotels, like the Four Seasons.</P>
<P>69. After Ms. Lau left Mr. Chiu I sensed that Mr. Chiu was interested in me in a romantic sense. He told me on more than one occasion that he was attracted to me and wanted us to be together. We were at times involved in a romantic way.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Return of Funds</EM></TI>
<P>70. Under the UK investment agreements, Mr. Chiu was to return my investments, plus any net return, on or before October 31, 2016.</P>
<P>71. In November I asked Mr. Chiu to return my investments in TRU, RACE, NTB and the UK market. On November 17, 2016, I sent an email to Mr. Chiu asking him to sell my investments in TRU, RACE, NTB and the UK market, and transfer the funds into my mother's US account. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;U&rdquo;</BOLD> is my email to Mr. Chiu, dated November 17, 2016 requesting that he sell my investments.</P>
<P>72. At that time he told me that he had been required to loan Ms. Lau money for her fashion business and also to pay tuition and other amounts for his daughter's private school in the United Kingdom. To make these payments he had sold off millions of dollars of the investments in the GS account. He told me that if he sold any more investments in the current tax year he would pay a significant penalty. He told me that, to avoid paying this penalty, he would need to wait until April 1, 2017, the start of the next tax year, to sell my investments and repay my money.</P>
<P>73. I became concerned and asked Mr. Chiu to execute a promissory note which I prepared, in part to confirm the total amount of my investments. When we discussed this promissory note, Mr. Chiu agreed to offer, as security for the amount owed, property he held at XXXXXXXXXX XXXXXXXXXX (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Ocean Drive Property</BOLD>&rdquo;). A copy of this document is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;V&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>74. On March 28, 2017, I met again with Mr. Chiu. At that time Mr. Chiu told me that he could not return my money because he and Ms. Lau were undergoing a divorce. He asked me to sign a loan agreement he wrote up agreeing to extend any repayment to me until his divorce was finalized. I refused to the sign the loan agreement. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;W&rdquo;</BOLD> are one of the drafts of the loan agreement Mr. Chiu provided to me.</P>
<P>75. During the March 28, 2017 meeting, I recorded my conversations with Mr. Chiu using my iPhone. I believe that Mr. Chiu became suspicious that I was recording the meeting, because he asked if I was recording us. I did not answer Mr. Chiu's question.</P>
<P>76. A couple of days later, Mr. Chiu and I arranged to meet again. Mr. Chiu told me that, at the meeting, he would repay me some of my money. He also asked me to bring originals of the investment agreements we had signed and the transfers I had made to Ms. Lau's account.</P>
<P>77. On or about April 6, 2017, I met with Mr. Chiu and he returned to me USD$14,000 of the money I had provided to him. I believe at this meeting that Mr. Chiu stole my iPhone, as it was not among my belongings after we parted company. I believe Mr. Chiu stole my iPhone while I was counting the money he gave me. Mr. Chiu and I corresponded to a large extent using an instant messaging program called WeChat. I believe Mr. Chiu stole my phone so that he could delete those messages and the recordings I had made of our previous conversations.</P>
<P>78. A couple of days later, on or about April 9, 2017, Mr. Chiu gave me USD$20,000 and again asked me to sign the loan agreement I had refused to sign. I again refused to sign the loan agreement.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Dissipation of Assets</EM></TI>
<P>79. I am concerned that Mr. Chiu will take steps to hide and or dissipate his assets.</P>
<P>80. At one point Mr. Chiu recommended that I open an account in the British Virgin Islands to hold all of my investments. I believe he may also have accounts there, or in other offshore locations.</P>
<P>81. Recently, Mr. Chiu advised me that he will be traveling to Hong Kong to sign his divorce agreement with Ms. Lau and that he has also booked a surgery in Hong Kong on May 19, 2017. Mr. Chiu told me that he will meet with me on May 14, 2017 to return USD$70,000 of the funds I have provided to him and that he will then travel to Hong Kong for May 19.</P>
<P>82. On May 11, 2017, I sent a WeChat to Mr. Chiu asking if he could give me the USD$70,000 on May 13, 2017 instead of May 14. I did not receive a response to my message.</P>
<P>83. On May 12, 2017, at approximately 6:40 am, I went to Mr. Chiu's townhouse at XXXXXXXXXX XXXXXXXXXX There were no on house and I could not find his car in the townhouse's garage.</P>
<P>84. Later on May 12, 2017, I received a call from Mr. Chiu. Mr. Chiu told me that he was ill and staying with relatives in Richmond, British Columbia, but he did not tell me where in Richmond he was staying. Mr. Chiu also told me that he would not be able to meet with me this weekend, because he was very sick and not able to go out. Mr. Chiu said that he might wire transfer me the USD$70,000 on Monday, May 15, 2017.</P>
<P>85. During our telephone conversation on May 12, 2017, Mr. Chiu also stated that because he is very sick, he can no longer go to Hong Kong. He said that he will now have the surgery in Vancouver in a few weeks' time.</P>
<P>86. I believe that Mr. Chiu was not being truthful with me during our May 12 call and that he has gone into hiding. I am concerned that if Mr. Chiu has not already left British Columbia, he may leave soon. I am also concerned that if Mr. Chiu leaves British Columbia, he will not return and that he will take assets with him from British Columbia.</P>
<P>87. In November 2016, Mr. Chiu told me he had worked for Stoneset Equities and gave me his business card. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;X&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of the Stoneset Equities Asia Pte. Ltd. business card for Allan Chiu. At that time, Mr. Chiu also showed me his residency card for Singapore.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Investigation into Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau</EM></TI>
<P>88. In or about the fall of 2016, I retained John Hilpert, a private investigator in Vancouver, to look into Mr. Chiu to try to verify Mr. Chiu's identity and some of the claims he had made to me about his past.</P>
<P>89. During that time period, I also retained I-OnAsia Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>OnAsia</BOLD>&rdquo;) to undertake a background search of Mr. Chiu in Hong Kong. I provided OnAsia with various information that Mr. Chiu had told me about his education and work experience and requested that OnAsia take steps to try to verify that information.</P>
<P>90. OnAsia advised me that based upon its inquiries it had determined that:
<P1>a. Mr. Chiu did not attend the University of British Columbia Sauder School of Business during the period he advised me he had attend that school;</P1>
<P1>b. Mr. Chiu did not attend Brown University;</P1>
<P1>c. Mr. Chiu is not a member of the CFA Institute, although the CFA Institute does have a record of an Alan Chiu of Pokfulam, Hong Kong;</P1>
<P1>d. Mr. Chiu was not employed with Petronas Petroliam Nasional Berhad;</P1>
<P1>e. Mr. Chiu was not employed with Temasek Holdings Private Limited; and</P1>
<P1>f. Mr. Chiu was not employed at Goldman Sachs (Asia) LLC or Goldman Sachs (Singapore) Pte. Ltd.</P1></P>
<P>91. OnAsia also advised me that it conducted searches of property transactions in Hong Kong using Mr. Chiu's name in English and Chinese, but that it was unable to locate any property transactions in Hong Kong involving Mr. Chiu.</P>
<P>92. During that time period, I also retained David Kang, a private investigator in Singapore, to undertake searches into Mr. Chiu in Singapore.</P>
<P>93. Mr. Kang advised me that based upon his inquiries he had determined that:
<P1>a. the Ocean Drive Property is owed by a company called Interlocal Exim Pte. Ltd.;</P1>
<P1>b. Mr. Chiu does not appear to own property in Singapore;</P1>
<P1>c. the Singapore Registrar of Companies and Business Names listed a &ldquo;Chiu Sung Fai&rdquo; as a director of Stoneset Equities Asia Pte. Ltd.;</P1>
<P1>d. Stoneset Equities Asia Pte. Ltd. listed a business address in Hong Kong;</P1>
<P1>e. Stoneset Equities Asia Pte. Ltd. was stuck off the Singapore Registrar of Companies and Business Names in 2010; and</P1>
<P1>f. Mr. Chiu was sued for bankruptcy in 2001.</P1></P>
<P>94. After I received the above information from Mr. Kang, I asked Mr, Chiu about the Ocean Drive Property and he told me that for tax purposes he had used a number of companies to put a lot of layers between himself and properties he owned. Mr. Chiu told me that some of the companies he used were companies in the British Virgin Islands.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Undertaking as to Damages</EM></TI>
<P>95. I have made an undertaking as to damages, which is attached to this affidavit as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;Y&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
