<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>Name of applicant: Rong Wei</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>On notice to: Allan Chiu and Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwun Queenie Chiu</BOLD></P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge or master at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia on 18/May/2017 at 9:45 am for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. A Mareva injunction, substantially in the form attached hereto as <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD>; and</P>
<P>2. An Norwich Pharmacal Order, substantially in the form attached hereto as <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Overview</UNDER></TI>
<P>3. Between 2015 and 2016, the plaintiff, Rong Wei (&ldquo;<BOLD>Wei</BOLD>&rdquo;), provided over USD$1.1 million to the defendants, Allan Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Chiu</BOLD>&rdquo;) and Mui Kwan Queenie Lau (&ldquo;<BOLD>Lau</BOLD>&rdquo;) to make certain investments on her behalf.</P>
<P>4. Chiu and Lau induced Wei to provide these funds based on representations that, among other things, such funds would be used by Chiu to purchase shares for Wei, Chiu had considerable experience in investing as a result of high level positions with Goldman Sachs, and that Chiu owned properties around the world.</P>
<P>5. At all material times, it was Wei's understanding that any shares purchased using the funds she provided to Chiu and Lau would be held on her behalf and in trust for her.</P>
<P>6. Wei has recently learned, through investigative efforts, that the representations made to her by Chiu and Lau were false. Despite repeated demands, with the exception of USD$34,000, Chiu and Lau have failed to return to Wei the funds she provided to them.</P>
<P>7. Wei's recent inquiries of Chui have been ignored. Wei believes Chui has gone into hiding and may soon leave British Columbia, if he has not already.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Wei's Investment with Chiu and Lau</UNDER></TI>
<P>8. Chin and Lau are husband and wife.</P>
<P>9. In 2014, Wei met Chiu and Lau. Through the course of various discussions, Wei told Chiu and Lau that she had some money that she wanted to invest and was looking for investment advice.</P>
<P>10. Wei was advised by Chiu and Lau that Chiu was an experienced investor and could assist Wei with investments. Among other things, Chiu and Lau told Wei that Chiu:
<P1>(a) had a Bachelor of Commerce from the Sauder School of Business at the University of British Columbia and a Masters of Business Administration from Brown University;</P1>
<P1>(b) had considerable experience in investing as a result of high level positions with Goldman Sachs' offices in Hong Kong, Korea, Japan and Singapore;</P1>
<P1>(c) had been responsible for managing a portfolio of USD$20 billion for institutional clients;</P1>
<P1>(d) had worked as a consultant for companies, like a Singapore state-owned holding company named Temasek, where he had made approximately USD$2 million per year;</P1>
<P1>(e) Chiu owned a number of properties in different countries; and</P1>
<P1>(f) Lau owned a property in London, United Kingdom.</P1></P>
<P>11. Wei was persuaded by Chiu and Lau to allow them to assist Wei with making investments. Thereafter, from time to time, Chiu would make recommendations to Wei regarding what companies and markets she should invest in. In particular, Chiu recommended that Wei invest in:
<P1>(a) an IPO being issued by TransUnion;</P1>
<P1>(b) an IPO being issued by Ferrari NV;</P1>
<P1>(c) an IPO being issued by Airbnb; and</P1>
<P1>(d) the UK stock market.</P1></P>
<P>12. In order to facilitate investing in these companies and the UK market, Wei transferred funds to Chiu and Lau, primarily through a Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce account held in the name of Lau. The funds were provided by Wei on the understanding that they would be used by Chiu to purchase shares, on Wei's behalf, using his retirement account with Goldman Sachs.</P>
<P>13. From 2015 to 2016, in reliance upon the above representations made by Chiu and Lau, Wei provided over USDS1.1 million to Chiu and Lau for the purpose of Chiu purchasing investments on Wei's behalf and to be held in trust for her.</P>
<P>14. On November 26, 2016, Wei requested that Chiu sell the investments he was holding in trust for her and return the sale proceeds to her. Chiu told Wei that for tax reasons he was unable to sell her shares in his Goldman Sachs account until the following tax year, starting on April 1, 2017.</P>
<P>15. At that time, Chiu executed a promissory note confirming that he owed Wei USD$1.25 million on account of her investments (and the return thereon) and promising to repay that amount on April 1, 2017. Chiu agreed to offer, as security for the amount owed, property he held at XXXXXXXXXX (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Ocean Drive Property</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>16. On March 28, 2017, Chiu told Wei that he was not able to return her money on April 1, 2017, because he and Lau were in the process of divorcing. Chiu requested that Wei execute a loan agreement with respect to the funds Wei had provided to Chiu and Lau. Wei refused to execute the loan agreement.</P>
<P>17. Thereafter, Chiu and Wei met on April 6 and 9, 2017. At those meetings, Chiu provided Wei with USD$14,000 and USD$20,000, respectively. At the April 9 meeting, Chiu again asked Wei to execute a loan agreement and Wei refused.</P>
<P>18. Chiu and Wei also arranged to meet on Sunday, May 14, 2017, at which time Chiu had promised to return USD$70,000 to Wei, but on May 12 Chiu called Wei and cancelled the May 14 meeting. Chiu told Wei that he might wire transfer the promised funds to her on Monday, May 15. As of the date of this Notice of Application, Chiu has not wired or otherwise provided to Wei the USD$70,000 he promised to return to her.</P>
<P>19. As of the date of this Notice of Application, Chiu has only repaid USD$34,000 of the more than USD$1.1 million Wei provided to Chiu and Lau for the sole purpose of Chiu purchasing shares on behalf of and in trust for Wei.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Investigative Efforts to Date</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. Starting in the fall of 2016, Wei retained three private investigators&mdash;one each in British Columbia, Hong Kong and Singapore&mdash;to look into Chiu to try to verify Chiu's identity and the representations he and Lau had made to Wei.</P>
<P>21. The private investigators determined, among other things, that:
<P1>a. Chiu did not attend the University of British Columbia Sauder School of Business during the period he advised Wei he had attended that school;</P1>
<P1>b. Chiu did not attend Brown University;</P1>
<P1>c. Chiu was not employed with Goldman Sachs (Asia) LLC or Goldman Sachs (Singapore) Pte. Ltd, Petronas Petroliam Nasional Berhad or Temasek Holdings Private Limited;</P1>
<P1>d. Chiu had previously worked in Calgary, Albert for Stoneset Asia Equities (&ldquo;<BOLD>Stoneset Equities</BOLD>&rdquo;), part of the Stoneset group of companies, and been involved in a major equities scandal around 2011;</P1>
<P1>e. Stoneset Equities is listed on Alberta Investors Protection's website under the heading &ldquo;Alberta EMD Failed/Failing Investments&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>f. there were no properties registered in the United Kingdom in the name of Mui Kwan Queenie Lau; and</P1>
<P1>g. Chiu had an outstanding debt of $34,000 owed to the Royal Bank.</P1></P>
<P>22. In addition, one of the private investigators determined that the Ocean Drive Property was owed by a company called Interlocal Exim Pte. Ltd. and that Chiu did not appear to own property in Singapore.</P>
<P>23. After being advised by the private investigator of that information, Wei asked Chiu about the Ocean Drive Property and he told her that for tax purposes he had used a number of companies to put a lot of layers between himself and properties he owned. Chiu also told Wei that some of the companies he used were companies in the British Virgin Islands.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Use of Funds by Chiu and Lau</UNDER></TI>
<P>24. The uses of the funds provided by Wei are best known to Chiu and Lau, who have knowingly failed to disclose those uses to Wei. At this time, and despite requests being made from time to time, Wei does not have any documents, save for investment summaries prepared by Chiu and Lau, showing what shares or assets were acquired using her funds, and she does not know how the funds provided by her were used beyond what was represented by Chiu and Lau.</P>
<P>25. Notwithstanding the above, Chiu has recently advised Wei that he is unable, at this time, to return her funds to her because he and Lau are in the process of divorcing.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Dissipation of Assets</UNDER></TI>
<P>26. In addition to Chiu advising Wei that he is unable to return her funds to her, in part, because of his personal circumstances, at different times, Chiu has told Wei that he uses various companies to put ownership layers between himself and property he owns.</P>
<P>27. Chiu has also recommended to Wei that she open a bank account in the British Virgin Islands to hold her investments.</P>
<P>28. Further, Chiu has recently refused to meet with Wei and indicated that he may travel to Hong Kong.</P>
<P>29. Wei has a real concern that Chiu and Lau may transfer or hide assets, and may leave British Columbia taking assets with them.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Defendants' CIBC Bank Accounts</UNDER></TI>
<P>30. Between 2015 and 2016, Chiu and Lau both used a bank account in Lau's name with the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce branch located at 2904 Granville Street, Vancouver (the &ldquo;<BOLD>CIBC Account</BOLD>&rdquo;), in order receive funds from Wei.</P>
<P>31. During that period of time, and under the direction of Chiu and Lau, Wei transferred over USD$1 million into the CIBC Account on the understanding that those funds would be used by Chiu and Lau solely to purchase shares on behalf of and to be held in trust for Wei.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Defendants' Other Bank Accounts</UNDER></TI>
<P>32. in or around February 2017, Chiu showed Wei a summary of what he indicated were her investments. On the back of the summary was banking information for Chiu or Lau from TD Bank.</P>
<P>33. In early 2017, Wei also went to see a movie with Chiu at Cineplex. At that time, Chiu used a SCENE card, which is a rewards program linked to Scotiabank.</P>
<P>34. As a result, Wei has reason to believe that Chiu, Lau or both of them have bank accounts with TD Canada Trust and Scotiabank.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Undertaking as to Damages</UNDER></TI>
<P>35. Wei has executed an undertaking to abide by any order the court may make as to damages if the injunction sought is granted.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>36. The court has the discretion to grant a Mareva injunction enjoining a defendant from dissipating or removing assets from the court's jurisdiction before trial.</P>
<P>37. The test for the granting of a Mareva injunction is whether the plaintiff has established the following:
<P1>(a) a strong <EM>prima facie</EM> or good arguable case;</P1>
<P1>(b) the defendant has assets and that there is a real risk of their disposal or dissipation, so as to render nugatory any judgment; and</P1>
<P1>(c) that, having regard to all relevant factors, the balance of justice and convenience favours the plaintiff's application.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Insurance Corp. of British Columbia v. Patko</SOC><CITE>2008 BCCA 65</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Patko</EM>]; and</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Tracy v. Instaloans Financial Solutions Centres (B.C.) Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2007 BCCA 481</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Tracy</EM>].</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. The consideration of whether to grant a Mareva injunction requires a flexible approach and the fundamental question will be whether the granting of the injunction is just and equitable in all of the circumstances of the case.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Patko</EM> at para. 25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>39. While a Mareva injunction is an exceptional remedy and is an exception to the practice of the court not requiring security before judgment, such an order may be justified where there is a genuine risk of dissipation of assets. The root underlying Mareva injunctions is the risk of harm either through the dissipation or removal of assets. Further, fraud is an exception to the general hostility to prejudgment execution.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Insurance Corp. of British Columbia v. Leland</SOC><CITE>[1999] B.C.J. No. 2073</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>; <EM>Tracy</EM> at para. 45; and</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Musson Cattell Mackey Partnership Architects Designers Planners v. Maki</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 2439</CITE><PARANUM>14 and 16</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Musson</EM>].</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Strong Prima Facie Case</EM></TI>
<P>40. A strict formulation should not be applied to determine whether the plaintiff has put forward a strong <EM>prima facie</EM> or good arguable case. The standard is higher than &ldquo;arguable case&rdquo;, but less than the &ldquo;bound to succeed&rdquo; threshold.
<P1><EM>Tracy</EM> at para. 54.</P1></P>
<P>41. The Plaintiff has provided evidence demonstrating that she provided significant funds to the Defendants based on the misrepresentations provided by them in respect to Chiu's education and investment experience, and that these funds or any investments purchased by them were to be held in trust for the Plaintiff. With the exception of USD$34,000, the Defendants have failed to re-pay the principal amounts held in trust by them for the Plaintiff or, in the alternative, the Defendants have failed to transfer to the Plaintiff any investments held by them in trust for the Plaintiff.</P>
<P>42. Further, Chiu has admitted that he owes Wei USD$1.25 million on account of the funds provided by Wei to Chiu and Lau, along with interest, and promised to repay this amount by April 1, 2017. Contrary to Chiu's promises and representations, at the current date, Chiu has only repaid USD$34,000 of this amount.</P>
<P>43. The evidence presented by the Plaintiff on this application clearly establishes that the Plaintiff has a strong <EM>prima facie</EM> case.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Real Risk of Dissipation of Assets</EM></TI>
<P>44. A risk of dissipation of assets may be inferred from the evidence related to the plaintiff's strong <EM>prima facie</EM> case. Such an inference may be justified in circumstances involving fraud.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Musson</EM> at para. 16;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Netolitzky v. Barclay</SOC><CITE>2002 BCSC 1098</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>; and</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Insurance Corp. of British Columbia v. Leland</SOC><CITE>1999 CarswellBC 1998</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. The Plaintiff has presented clear evidence that she has a strong <EM>prima facie</EM> case involving a breach of trust and fraud.</P>
<P>46. Further, the Plaintiff has presented evidence that there is a real risk that the Defendants will hide assets or leave the jurisdiction taking assets with them.</P>
<P>47. The circumstances of this case justify the court making an inference that there is a risk that the Defendants will dissipate their assets.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Balance of Justice and Convenience</EM></TI>
<P>48. In <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Broadcasting Corp. v. CKPG Television Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>64 B.C.L.R. (2d) 96</CITE></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal set out factors to be considered under balance of convenience. It noted this list is not exhaustive and the relevant factors will vary from case to case:
<P1>(a) the adequacy of damages as a remedy for the applicant if the injunction is not granted and for the respondent if an injunction is granted;</P1>
<P1>(b) the likelihood that if damages are finally awarded they will be paid;</P1>
<P1>(c) the preservation of contested property;</P1>
<P1>(d) other factors affecting whether harm from the granting or refusal of the injunction would be irreparable;</P1>
<P1>(e) which of the parties has acted to alter the balance of their relationship and so affect the status quo;</P1>
<P1>(f) the strength of the applicant's case;</P1>
<P1>(g) any factors affecting the public interest; and</P1>
<P1>(h) any other factors affecting the balance of justice and convenience.</P1></P>
<P>49. With respect to (b) and (d), the Plaintiff will likely have difficulty collecting an award of damages if the Mareva order sought herein is not granted due to the real risk that the Defendants will dissipate or dispose of their assets. There is therefore a substantial risk that damages will not be paid.</P>
<P>50. With respect to (f), the strength of the Plaintiff's case also supports the relief sought herein. Chiu has admitted to owing a significant sum of money to the Plaintiff.</P>
<P>51. In sum, if a protection order is not granted and the Plaintiff's claim succeeds, she will in all likelihood be left without a remedy. In contrast, if a protection order is issued and the plaintiff's claim fails, then the Defendants' assets will have been preserved and all that will have been lost is the ability of the Defendants to sell or otherwise deal with their property for a period of time. To mitigate any such prejudice, the Plaintiff has executed an undertaking as to damages.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Norwich Pharmacal Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>52. A defrauded plaintiff has an equitable right to trace his or her money. For the purpose of giving effect to that right, the court has the discretion to order a third party to disclose information or documents relating to the assets of the alleged fraudster. Such orders are commonly referred to as a &ldquo;Norwich Pharmacal Order&rdquo;.</P>
<P>53. The granting of a Norwich Pharmacal Order is an exceptional remedy, but it may be justified to trace funds and to give effect to a Mareva injunction to prevent the dissipation of assets.</P>
<P>54. When determining whether to grant a Norwich Pharmacal Order, the court will consider the following factors:
<P1>(a) whether the applicant has provided evidence sufficient to raise a valid, bona fide or reasonable claim;</P1>
<P1>(b) whether the application has established a relationship with the third party from whom the information is sought such that it establishes that the third party is somehow involved in the acts complained of;</P1>
<P1>(c) whether the third party is the only practical source of information available;</P1>
<P1>(d) whether the third party can be indemnified for costs to which the third party may be exposed because of the disclosure; and</P1>
<P1>(e) whether the interest of justice favour the obtaining of disclosure.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Musson</EM> at para. 17; and</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Gold Bullion Development Corp. v. Stockhouse Publishing Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 784</CITE><PARANUM>4</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>55. With respect to (a) and (d), as discussed above, the Plaintiff has presented sufficient evidence to establish that it has a bona fide or reasonable claim and has undertaken to pay any costs awarded by the court.</P>
<P>56. With respect to (b), Lau holds a bank account with CIBC, which was used by both Defendants and directly involved in the operation of the Defendants' purported investment scheme. In particular, it was into this account that the Plaintiff transferred funds at the request of the Defendants.</P>
<P>57. In addition, the Plaintiff has presented evidence that Chiu, Lau or both of them likely hold bank accounts with TD Canada Trust and Scotiabank.</P>
<P>58. Further, CIBC, TD Canada Trust and Scotiabank provide the only practical source of information regarding the Defendants' bank accounts, as it is unlikely that the Defendants will disclose accurate and complete information about their financial affairs.</P>
<P>59. In the circumstances of this case, the balance of justice favours the granting of an order that CIBC, TD Canada Trust and Scotiabank provide the Plaintiff with information about the Defendants' bank accounts to allow the Plaintiff to trace its funds.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
