<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>Name of applicant: Rong Wei</BOLD></P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an EX PARTE application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia on 16/Aug/2017 at 9:45 am for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. Leave of this Court to:
<P1>a) apply for, in aid of the within proceeding, an injunction or preservation order pursuant to s. 21M of the High Court Ordinance and ancillary disclosure orders before the High Court of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (the &ldquo;Hong Kong Proceeding&rdquo;); and</P1>
<P1>b) rely on the Defendants' Asset Lists as defined under the Order of Madam Justice Humphries dated May 18, 2017 in the Hong Kong Proceeding.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Background to Canadian Action</EM></TI>
<P>2. The background to this action is summarized in the plaintiff's first affidavit, relied on in support of the mareva order made by Madam Justice Humphries dated May 18, 2017 (the &ldquo;Mareva Order&rdquo;) in this proceeding:
<P1>a) Wei provided over USD $1.1 million to Chiu and Lau, for them to make certain investments on her behalf (paragraph 64);</P1>
<P1>b) Chiu and Lau induced Wei to provide these funds based on representations that, among other things, such funds would be used by Chiu to purchase shares for Wei, Chiu had considerable experience in investing as a result of a high level position with Goldman Sachs, and that Chiu owned properties around the world (paragraphs 64, 66 and 5);</P1>
<P1>c) Wei understood that any shares purchased using the funds she provided to Chiu and Lau would be held on her behalf and in trust for her (paragraph 65);</P1>
<P1>d) Wei subsequently learned, through investigative efforts, that the representations made to her by Chiu and Lau were false (paragraphs 90 to 93); and</P1>
<P1>e) Despite repeated demands, with the exceptions of USD $34,000, Chiu and Lau have failed to return to Wei the funds she provided to them (paragraphs 70 to 78).</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Mareva Order of May 18, 2017</EM></TI>
<P>3. The terms of the Mareva Order, and related disclcosure order, include among others:
<P1>a) Chiu and Lau must provide the plaintiff's solicitor with a list (the &ldquo;Defendants' Asset Lists&rdquo;) verified by affidavit setting out all of their assets as of the date of the Mareva Order (paragraph 17);</P1>
<P1>b) the plaintiff's solicitor shall not disclose the Defendants' Asset Lists or the information contained in them to any person (including the plaintiff) except for the purposes of this proceeding and before making such disclosure, counsel shall obtain a written undertaking in form attached as Schedule 2 to the Mareva Order (paragraph 19);</P1>
<P1>c) The Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce (&ldquo;CIBC&rdquo;) must provide a list of all accounts held by Chiu and Lau, and all supporting records in respect thereof (paragraph 21).</P1></P>
<P>4. CIBC was implicated in the Mareva Order because it was through a CIBC account, maintained by Lau, that Wei transferred funds to Chiu and Lau.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Defendants' Asset Lists</EM></TI>
<P>5. On or around June 21, 2017, Chiu and Lau, through counsel who was since been retained by them, provided the Defendants' Asset Lists to the plaintiff's solicitor.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>CIBC Records</EM></TI>
<P>6. In May and June 2017, the plaintiff's solicitor also received banking records from CIBC in respect of accounts maintained by Lau (the &ldquo;CIBC Records&rdquo;).</P>
<P>7. The CIBC Records, among other things, indicate that in May 2017 Ms. Lau transferred approximately USD $275,000 in funds to an account in Hong Kong. Of that amount, USD $100,000 was transferred after the application for the Mareva Order was substitutionally served on Lau.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Hong Kong Proceeding</EM></TI>
<P>8. In light of the foregoing transfers evident in the CIBC records, and information contained in the Defendants' Asset Lists, Wei intends to apply in Hong Kong for an <EM>ex parte</EM> injunction or preservation order pursuant to s. 21M of the High Court Ordinance and ancillary disclosure orders respecting the Hong Kong based banks used by Chiu and Lau (the &ldquo;Hong Kong Proceeding&rdquo;).</P>
<P>9. In light of the extant Mareva Order, Wei seeks leave to:
<P1>a) commence the Hong Kong Proceeding, given paragraph 9 of the Mareva Order (which provides that any application arising out of the enforcement of the Mareva Order be heard by the Judge who issued the Order); and</P1>
<P1>b) rely on the Defendants' Assets Lists in the Hong Kong Proceeding, given paragraph 19 of the Mareva Order (which prevents the plaintiff's solicitor from disclosing the Defendants Asset Lists unless a written undertaking is first obtained).</P1></P>
<P>10. The disclosure of the Defendants' Assets Lists is required to ensure full and frank disclosure is made in the Hong Kong Proceeding.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Other Relevant Information</EM></TI>
<P>11. In paragraph 9 of the Mareva Order, applications arising out of the enforcement of the Mareva Order are to be heard by Madam Justice Humphries, the Judge who issued the Mareva Order. We have sought to reappear before Madam Justice Humphries but have been advised that she is unavailable to hear this application.</P>
<P>12. Although the defendants have not yet filed a Response to Civil Claim, they have retained Poulsen &amp; Company to act for them in this matter. Counsel for the defendants has advised that there was a close personal relationship between Wei and Chiu and that they were essentially conducting themselves as spouses, sharing various expenses, making and forgiving loans and treating one another's assets as joint property in contemplation of formalizing their spousal relationship, as well as that Chiu was told he did not need to worry about any sums Wei had given him and that he could consider those amounts to be gifts.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>13. This Court has already granted the Mareva Order and in doing so been satisfied that the plaintiff has a strong <EM>prima facie</EM> case and that the worldwide order is just and equitable in all of the circumstances of the case.</P>
<P>14. What the plaintiff is now seeking from the Hong Kong court is an order extending the Mareva Order to Hong Kong, and disclosure orders to assist in its enforcement.</P>
<P>15. Wei's request for an order that she be permitted to use the Defendants' Assets Lists in the Hong Kong Proceeding is, it is submitted, analogous to a request by a party for the court to waive the implied undertaking that attaches to discovery evidence and documents produced in an action.</P>
<P>16. The test for granting an order waiving the implied undertaking is whether the interests of justice outweigh any prejudice that would result to the party that disclosed the evidence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Tekavec</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 1348</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>17. In cases where discovery evidence in one action is sought to be used in another action with the same or similar parties and issues, the prejudice to the examinee is virtually non-existent and leave will generally be granted.
<P1><EM>Tekavec</EM> at para. 15.</P1></P>
<P>18. The parties to the Hong Kong Proceeding are the same as the parties to the within proceedings, and the purpose for which Wei is seeking to use the Defendants' Assets Lists is directly related to the purpose for which the Defendants' Assets Lists were produced in these proceedings.</P>
<P>19. In the circumstances, the balance of justice favours the granting of an order permitting Wei to use the Defendants' Assets Lists in the Hong Kong Proceeding.</P></BLOCK2>
