<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P>Name of applicant: Rong Wei (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Applicant</BOLD>&rdquo;)</P>
<P>TO: Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu and Allan Chiu</P>
<P>AND TO: Their Solicitors</P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge or master at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia on December 4, 2018 at 9:45 a.m. for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. A declaration that Ms. Lau is in contempt of court for refusing or neglecting to attend at the time and place appointed for her examination for discovery and breaching paragraph 4 of the order of Madam Justice Humphries dated May 18, 2017 by (i) acquiring a BMW vehicle registered in her name with serial number XXXXXXXXXX and (ii) in respect of that transaction and all others, failing since in or about December 2017 to advise the plaintiff of her sources of spending.</P>
<P>2. An order that the response to civil claim of Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Ms. Lau</BOLD>&rdquo;) be struck out and the proceeding continue as if no appearance had been entered or no defence filed.</P>
<P>3. In the alternative, an order that Ms. Lau attend at the office of McEwan Cooper Dennis LLP located at XXXXXXXXXX, or such other location as agreed upon by the parties, on December 5, 2018 at 10:00 a.m. for an examination for discovery pertaining to matters in question in this action.</P>
<P>4. An order that Ms. Lau deliver an Amended List of Documents that lists all of the documents that are or have been in her possession or control that could, if available, be used to prove or disprove a material fact, as well as all other documents Ms. Lau intends to refer to at trial (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Amended List of Documents</BOLD>&rdquo;) within 14 days of the order of this Court.</P>
<P>5. An order that Ms. Lau shall include in the Amended List of Documents the documents and classes of documents set out at Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; to this Notice of Application.</P>
<P>6. An order that Ms. Lau swear an affidavit verifying the Amended List of Documents and deliver that affidavit to the Applicant within 14 days of the order of this Court.</P>
<P>7. An order that Ms. Lau post the amount of $30,000 in Court as security for her good behaviour, which amount is to be posted within two weeks of today's date from funds outside of Canada.</P>
<P>8. An order that paragraph 4 of the order of Madam Justice Humphries dated May 18, 2017 be varied by striking out the reference to $3,500.00 and replacing it with $1,000.00 with respect to Ms. Lau, until such time as Ms. Lau: (a) provides the plaintiff with a full accounting, satisfactory to the plaintiff, of her monthly living expenses from December 2017 to the present date and identifies the source of the funds for those living expenses; and (b) produces to the plaintiff all documents within her possession, custody or control related to the purchase or lease of the BMW vehicle registered in her name with serial number XXXXXXXXXX.</P>
<P>9. An order that Ms. Wei be granted her costs thrown away of the failed examination for discovery on September 27, 2018 in the amount of $900 payable forthwith from funds outside of Canada.</P>
<P>10. An order that special costs of this application be payable by Ms. Lau forthwith in any event of the cause.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Overview of Application</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. This case concerns the actions of Allan Chiu and his wife Queenie Lau, who between 2015 and 2016 induced the plaintiff, Rong (Eliza) Wei, to pay them approximately USD$1.1 million to invest on her behalf.</P>
<P>12. Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau did not invest the funds they received from Ms. Wei and did not provide Ms. Wei a return on her investment. Instead, Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau defrauded Ms. Wei and converted Ms. Wei's funds to their own uses. Despite repeated demands, with the exception of USD$34,000, Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau have failed to return to Ms. Wei the funds that she provided to them.</P>
<P>13. On May 18, 2017 Humphries J. granted a Mareva injunction against the defendants which, among other terms, restrained use of their assets.</P>
<P>14. The defendants' misconduct and deceit that gave rise to the need for the plaintiff to bring this claim has carried over into the defendants' defence of the claim.</P>
<P>15. On September 27, 2018, Ms. Lau failed to attend a scheduled examination for discovery in Vancouver. Ms. Lau's counsel advised both before and after the examination that Ms. Lau could not attend the examination because she was in China and unable to travel due to a medical condition. That was false. On the days leading up to and on September 27, Ms. Lau was observed by a private investigator at several locations in Vancouver with her husband, including playing tennis, shopping at an outlet mall and driving a new BMW registered in her name that was acquired after the commencement of this proceeding.</P>
<P>16. Ms. Lau's wilful failure to attend her examination for discovery is a continuation of a course of conduct that can only be described as obstructive. Ms. Lau has been dilatory in providing document disclosure, only producing a list of documents after required by court order. In addition, Ms. Lau is in breach of the terms of a Mareva injunction requiring that she provide Ms. Wei's solicitors with notice of the intended source of funds before she spends any money on her allotted $3,500 a month for living and business expenses. Neither Ms. Lau nor her husband have provided the required information since December 2017.</P>
<P>17. Ms. Wei brings this application seeking an order striking Ms. Lau's response to civil claim for her wilful refusal to attend her examination for discovery. Ms. Wei also seeks an order that Ms. Lau be found in contempt for her non-attendance, as well as for her breach of the terms of the Mareva order.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Procedural History</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ms. Wei Obtains Mareva Injunction</EM></TI>
<P>18. Ms. Wei filed her notice of civil claim on May 12, 2017 claiming the sum of approximately $1.5 million on account of the principal amounts provided by Ms. Wei to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau. Ms. Wei also sought interim and permanent injunctive relief restraining the defendants from disposing of their assets, as well as equitable relief, including tracing orders and orders that the defendants hold any real and personal property as constructive trustees.</P>
<P>19. On May 16, 2017, Ms. Wei filed an application for a Mareva injunction and a Norwich Pharmaceutical Order.</P>
<P>20. On May 18, 2017, Humphries J. granted the orders sought by Ms. Wei (the &ldquo;<BOLD>May 2017 Order</BOLD>&rdquo;), including a Mareva injunction prohibiting the defendants from disposing of their assets.</P>
<P>21. The May 2017 Order was emailed to each of the defendants on May 19, 2017.</P>
<P>22. Based on the defendants' bank records subsequently obtained by Ms. Wei, from May 20, 2017 onward Mr. Chiu withdrew the following amounts from his Bank of China account in Hong Kong: $1,663,221.18 in HKD, $2,900.00 in CAD, and $123,545.73 in USD, for a total amount of $459,630.83 (CAD) based on the Bank of Canada foreign exchange rate posted on May 19, 2017. These withdrawals are in addition to, and not explained by, the exemptions allowed for the defendants under the May 2017 Order.</P>
<P>23. The May 2017 Order required the defendants to provide Ms. Wei's solicitor with an Asset List within seven days setting out all of the defendants' assets as of the date of the May 2017 Order.</P>
<P>24. The Asset Lists were provided by the defendants on June 21, 2017.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Defendants' Delay in Providing Document Discovery</EM></TI>
<P>25. Ms. Wei served her list of documents on October 23, 2017. Ms. Wei served an amended list of documents on November 9, 2017 listing additional documents.</P>
<P>26. Ms. Wei scheduled examinations for discovery of Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau in November 2017. Those examinations could not proceed, as the defendants' had yet to deliver their list of documents, despite several requests. They were adjourned by agreement.</P>
<P>27. On May 29, 2018, Ms. Wei filed an application seeking an order that the defendants deliver a list of documents.</P>
<P>28. On June 6, 2018, Master Vos ordered that the defendants deliver a list of documents within 21 days.</P>
<P>29. On July 3, 2018, the defendants served a list of documents. Despite Ms. Wei requesting copies of the documents on July 5, 2018, the documents were not delivered until August.</P>
<P>30. The defendants' list of documents is sparse and omits many classes of documents. For example, the defendants' list of documents omits banking records necessary for a proper tracing analysis.</P>
<P>31. By letter dated October 10, 2018, Ms. Wei made demand of the defendants pursuant to sub-rules 7-1(10) to (12) of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> that the defendants' list of documents be amended to include the documents set out at Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; to this notice of application. To date, the defendants have not provided a response to the letter.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ms. Lau Fails to Attend Scheduled Examination for Discovery on September 27, 2018</EM></TI>
<P>32. Throughout August 2018, Ms. Wei's counsel communicated with counsel for the defendants to attempt to schedule an examination for discovery of both defendants in the month of September, beginning with Ms. Lau.</P>
<P>33. Ms. Lau did not provide any available dates for a discovery in September. On September 6, 2018, counsel for the defendants advised that he was instructed that Ms. Lau was abroad dealing with a medical issue, and that he was seeking more information to assist in scheduling her examination.</P>
<P>34. On September 18, 2018, counsel for Ms. Wei followed-up with counsel for the defendants seeking further information on when Ms. Lau was expected to be back in the country.</P>
<P>35. On September 19, 2018, Ms. Wei served an appointment to examine for discovery Ms. Lau on September 27, 2018 at the offices of her counsel and attached conduct money.</P>
<P>36. On September 24, 2018, counsel for the defendants advised that he was instructed that Ms. Lau was in China and unable to travel for medical reasons. Counsel for the defendants explained that he understood that Ms. Lau had a blood disorder, and it was hoped it would resolve sufficiently by December so that she was in a position to travel then. Counsel for the defendants requested that the examination of Ms. Lau be rescheduled to December, as Ms. Lau was unable to attend the scheduled discovery on September 27, 2018.</P>
<P>37. On September 25, 2018, counsel for Ms. Wei advised counsel for the defendants that he would be attending the scheduled examination on September 27, 2018 to have the appointment stamped. Counsel for Ms. Wei offered to conduct a discovery of Mr. Chiu on that date, if he was available.</P>
<P>38. On September 26, 2018, counsel for the defendants sent an email to counsel for Ms. Wei reiterating that Ms. Lau was not available for the reasons previously expressed.</P>
<P>39. Ms. Lau did not attend at her scheduled examination for discovery on September 27. An endorsement of non-appearance was issued.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ms. Lau was not in China on the Date of her Examination</EM></TI>
<P>40. The reason proffered by Ms. Lau's counsel on her behalf for her inability to attend her scheduled examination for discovery on September 27 was that she was in China and unable to travel to Vancouver for medical conditions. That was not true.</P>
<P>41. On September 24, the day Ms. Lau's counsel advised Ms. Wei's counsel that Ms. Lau was in China and unable to travel for medical reasons, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were observed by John Hilpert, a private investigator retained by Ms. Wei, at the McArthurGlen outlet mail in Richmond, British Columbia in a dark BMW vehicle.</P>
<P>42. During the afternoon of September 26, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were observed again by Mr. Hilpert at numerous locations in Vancouver, including playing tennis on the UBC campus, driving their BMW, walking a dog at a park and picking up their daughter at the Lansdowne Skytrain station. Mr. Hilpert observed that the BMW had an expired insurance sticker.</P>
<P>43. On September 27, the day of her scheduled examination, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were observed again by Mr. Hilpert at several locations in Vancouver.</P>
<P>44. On September 28, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were again observed by Mr. Hilpert at several locations in Vancouver, including attending the C!BC branch located at 4489 West 10<SUP>th</SUP> Avenue, playing tennis on the UBC campus and going to the McArthurGlen outlet mall in Richmond.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Further Attempts to Schedule Discoveries of the Defendants</EM></TI>
<P>45. On October 4, 2018, counsel for Ms. Wei sent a letter to counsel for the defendants following up on Mr. Chiu's availability for an examination for discovery. Counsel for Ms. Wei also requested that Ms. Lau provide better information about her medical condition, including a doctor's note.</P>
<P>46. During the evening of October 9, 2018, counsel for the defendants sent a letter to counsel for Ms. Wei advising that Ms. Lau hoped that she would be well enough to travel for the purposes of an examination for discovery by December.</P>
<P>47. Counsel for the defendants further advised that Mr. Chiu no longer resides in Vancouver, and was also in China. However, on October 10 Mr. Hilpert once again observed Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau shopping at the Costco wholesale store in Richmond. Mr. Hilpert observed that Mr. Chiu was wearing a Cartier watch. Mr. Hilpert also observed that the defendants' BMW displayed a new 2019 insurance sticker.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Striking Ms. Chiu's Response to Civil Claim for Failure to Attend Examination</UNDER></TI>
<P>48. A party of record has an obligation to make him or herself available for an examination for discovery.
<P1>Rule 7-2(1)</P1></P>
<P>49. A person to be examined for discovery must attend and submit to an examination for discovery if the party wishing to conduct that examination has properly served an appointment and tendered witness fees.
<P1>Rule 7-2(14)</P1></P>
<P>50. Where a defendant, contrary to the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> and without lawful excuse, neglects to attend at the time and place appointed for his or her examination for discovery, the court may strike out the response to civil claim and order the proceeding to continue against that person as if no response to civil claim had been filed.
<P1>Rule 22-7(2) and (5)</P1></P>
<P>51. The court may also make any other order it thinks fit, including an order requiring the party to attend a rescheduled examination for discovery.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Tsoukas v. Ruocco</SOC><CITE>2004 BCSC 1384</CITE><PARANUM>7 and 10</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>52. While courts often allow for a two-step process on an application to strike for nonattendance at an examination for discovery, there is no fixed rule. An order to strike pleadings is usually only made after the second non-attendance at discovery. However, each case will depend on its facts. For example, where the evidence is clear that a defendant has engaged in obstructive conduct, the court will be more willing to apply the sanction of striking the defence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Han v. Cho</SOC><CITE>2008 BCSC 1621</CITE><PARANUM>19&ndash;21</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Kalcsa v. Read Media Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 248</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>636023 B.C. Ltd. v. A-Millenia Construction Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2005 BCSC 1563</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>53. The facts of this case merit an order that Ms. Lau's response to civil claim be struck.</P>
<P>54. The reason offered by Ms. Lau, through counsel, in the days leading up to the date of her scheduled examination for her inability to attend was that she was in China and unable to travel to Vancouver due to medical reasons. That was not true. Ms. Lau was in Vancouver with her husband in the days leading up to the examination and on the date of the examination. She was seen playing tennis, walking her dog and going shopping.</P>
<P>55. The defendants' deceit continued after Ms. Lau's missed examination for discovery, when the defendants (again through their counsel) advised Ms. Wei approximately two weeks later that both of them were residing in China and that Ms. Lau remained unable to travel to Vancouver. Once again, that was not true. Both Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau were in Vancouver.</P>
<P>56. There can be no lawful excuse for Ms. Lau's failure to attend her examination for discovery on September 27, 2018. She avoided her obligation to attend a discovery by attempting to deliberately mislead Ms. Wei about her ability to attend.</P>
<P>57. Ms. Lau's untruthfulness is sufficient in and of itself to justify an order striking her defence. The appropriateness of that order is compounded when considered alongside her dilatory attitude to document production and her continued attempt to delay being examined for discovery after her missed appointment by repeating the fiction that she is in China and unable to travel for medical reasons.</P>
<P>58. Ms. Lau's response to civil claim should be struck and the proceeding continued against her as if no response to civil claim had been filed.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Variation of May 2017 Order due to Defendants' Non-Compliance</UNDER></TI>
<P>59. As noted, the May 2017 Order includes a Mareva injunction prohibiting the defendants from, among other things, disposing of or dealing with or diminishing the value of any of their assets whether they are in or outside British Columbia.</P>
<P>60. Paragraph 4 to the May 2017 Order sets out the following exception to the order:
<QUOTE><P>This Order does not prohibit the defendants from spending $3,500.00 each per month on ordinary living expenses and a total of $25,000.00 each on legal advice and representation. <UNDER>Before spending any money on living, business or legal expenses, the defendant must advise the plaintiff's solicitors in writing of the intended source of the funds</UNDER>. (Emphasis added.)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>61. As is evident, the order requires that the defendants advise the plaintiff's solicitors in writing of the intended source of funds for living expenses <UNDER>before</UNDER> any money is spent.</P>
<P>62. For the first several months after the issuance of the May 2017 Order, the defendants, through their counsel, advised the plaintiff's solicitors in writing of the intended source of funds before funds were spent on living expenses.</P>
<P>63. However, since approximately December of 2017 the defendants have not been providing the plaintiff's solicitors with advance notice in writing of the intended source of funds for living expenses.</P>
<P>64. The result is that Ms. Lau is not complying with the May 2017 Order, as she is spending money on living and business expenses without first advising the plaintiff's solicitors of the intended source of the funds.</P>
<P>65. As an example from prior to December 2017, a PPRS search of the BMW being driven by Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau reveals a PPSA Security Agreement registered in favour of BMW Canada Inc. on September 27, 2017. The base debtor is listed as &ldquo;Mui Queenie Chiu&rdquo;. Ms. Lau did not advise the plaintiff's solicitors before spending money in September 2017 of the intended source of funds for the expenses in acquiring their BMW, or before paying for the insurance renewal in the fall of 2018.</P>
<P>66. As a consequence of Ms. Lau's continued non-compliance with paragraph 4 of the May 2017 Order, Ms. Wei seeks an order varying her monthly living expenses from $3,500 to $1,000 until such time as she provides a full accounting of her monthly living expenses from December 2017 to the present date and identifies the source of the funds for those living expenses. Ms. Wei also seeks as part of the order that Ms. Wei be required to produce to the plaintiff's solicitors all documents related to the purchase or lease of the BMW vehicle registered in her name.</P>
<P>67. Ms. Wei seeks this order pursuant to paragraph 8 of the May 2017 Order, which permits anyone affected by the order to apply to the Court at any time to vary it.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Ms. Lau is in Contempt of Court</UNDER></TI>
<P>68. Ms. Lau's failure to attend her scheduled examination for discovery and her noncompliance with paragraph 4 of the May 2017 Order both constitute contempt of court.</P>
<P>69. Pursuant to Rule 22-8(4) of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, a person who is guilty of refusing, without lawful excuse, to attend at the time and place appointed for his or her examination for discovery is subject to the court's power to punish contempt of court.</P>
<P>70. On an application for contempt, the applicant must prove three elements, being a clear order, actual knowledge of the order, and evidence of wilful noncompliance.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Carey v. Laiken</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 17</CITE><PARANUM>30&ndash;35</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>XY, LLC v. Canadian Topsires Selection Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 2629</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Unifor Local Union No. VCTA v. Sunlover Holding Co.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 922</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>71. All of the elements of contempt are met in this case.</P>
<P>72. With respect to Ms. Lau's refusal to attend her scheduled examination for discovery, Ms. Wei properly served her appointment to examine Ms. Lau in accordance with the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules.</EM> Further, the correspondence between counsel reveals that Ms. Lau was aware of the appointment on September 27, 2018, as she provided information to her counsel to attempt to justify her refusal to attend. The correspondence between counsel also reveals that Ms. Lau's refusal to attend her examination was wilful and deliberate, as she provided her counsel with false information about her whereabouts and ability to attend the examination over a period of several days. Ms. Lau's failure to attend her examination was in contempt of court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Unifor Local Union No. VCTA v. Sunlover Holding Co.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 922</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>73. With respect to Ms. Lau's failure to comply with paragraph 4 of the May 2017 Order, the evidence once again establishes that all three elements of a contempt finding are present. First, the order is dear that Ms. Lau must notify the plaintiff's solicitors of the intended source of funds <UNDER>before</UNDER> spending any money on living, business or legal expenses. Second, it is clear that Ms. Lau had knowledge of the order, as Ms. Lau, through her counsel, previously provided the plaintiff's solicitors with information concerning the intended source of funds before it was spent by Ms. Lau on living expenses. Third, Ms. Lau's failure to provide the plaintiff's solicitors with the court ordered information before spending money is wilful conduct in contravention of the May 2017 Order.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>XY, LLC v. Canadian Topsires Selection Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 2629</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>74. The court has flexibility in crafting the appropriate remedy for contempt. Rule 22-8(1) provides that the court may impose a fine or imprisonment or both. Rule 22-8(3) provides that instead of or in addition to making an order of committal or imposing a fine, the court may order a person to give security for the person's good behaviour.</P>
<P>75. As a sanction for Ms. Lau's contempt of court, Ms. Wei seeks an order that Ms. Lau be required to post $30,000 as security for her good behaviour within two weeks of the date of the order. The $30,000 reflects the approximate amount of Ms. Wei's permitted monthly living expenses during the past ten months that she has been failing to provide the plaintiff's solicitors with the information required under the May 2017 Order.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Production of Additional Documents and Affidavit of Documents</UNDER></TI>
<P>76. Ms. Wei has demanded production of additional documents from the defendants. In particular, Ms. Wei has demanded production of all the defendants' bank and financial records from the period June 1, 2015 to present, including all bank records from the institutions listed in their Asset Lists provided on June 21, 2017.</P>
<P>77. The requested documents are capable of being used to prove or disprove material facts at issue in the proceeding. In particular, the documents are relevant to Ms. Wei's tracing claims against the defendants, and are sought from the time that Ms. Wei first advanced funds to Ms. Chiu to the present date. The documents are producible and should have been listed in the defendants' list of documents.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Han v. Cho</SOC><CITE>2008 BCSC 1207</CITE><PARANUM>6-7</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>78. Ms. Wei seeks a further order pursuant to Rule 7-1(8) that Ms. Lau (in the event that her response to civil claim is not struck) deliver an affidavit verifying her list of documents.</P>
<P>79. The court may order a party to deliver an affidavit verifying their list of documents when, in the absence of adequate explanation, relevant documents have been omitted from the list of documents. Such an order may also be made when a party has shown a dilatory and casual attitude to production of documents giving the other party reasonable cause to suspect that either deliberately or by wilful indifference relevant documents may be hidden from them.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gardner v. Viridis Energy Inc.</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 1816</CITE><PARANUM>52</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Copithorne v. Benoit</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 130</CITE><PARANUM>10&ndash;12</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>80. Where a party has, for whatever reason, omitted to list significant documents, an order for an affidavit of documents ought to be made.
<P1><EM>Copithorne</EM> at para. 11</P1></P>
<P>81. It is apparent that the defendants have failed or refused to list documents that are relevant to this proceeding. A key component of the plaintiff's claim is that the defendants received the proceeds of the fraud perpetrated on the plaintiff and converted them to their own use. The defendants' financial and banking records, including the banking records from the institutions listed in the defendants' asset lists, are clearly documents that should have been produced.</P>
<P>82. Moreover, the defendants' failure to serve a list of documents until after being ordered to do so by the court approximately ten months after the close of pleadings highlights the defendants' dilatory and casual attitude to document production.</P>
<P>83. Ms. Lau (in the event that her response to civil claim is not struck) should be ordered to swear and deliver affidavits verifying their list of documents.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
