<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>Name of applicant: the Plaintiff, Rong Wei</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>To: Allan Chiu and Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwun Queenie Chiu</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>And to: Their Solicitor</BOLD></P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge or master at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia on 20/Dec/2018 at 9:45 am for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. A declaration that Allan Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Chiu</BOLD>&rdquo;) is in contempt of court for contravening the order of Madam Justice Humphries, made May 18, 2017 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Mareva Order</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. An order that Chiu post security with the court in the amount of $447,964.78, or such other amount as the court may direct, within seven days of the date of this order, which security is to be held pending a final resolution in this matter or a direction consented to by the parties.</P>
<P>3. The Plaintiff's costs of this application be assessed as special costs fixed at a lump sum of $7,500 payable within seven days of this order and in any event of the cause by the Chiu.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Introduction</EM></TI>
<P>4. The Plaintiff applies for an order that Chiu is in contempt of court for breaching the order of Madam Justice Humphries pronounced on May 18, 2017 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Mareva Order</BOLD>&rdquo;). In short, based on records received through enforcement proceedings taken in Hong Kong in respect of the Mareva Order, the Plaintiff has learned that Chiu, since the date of the Mareva Order, has withdrawn a total of $447,964.78 from his personal account in Hong Kong. As a sanction for this contempt, the Plaintiff seeks an order requiring that Chiu give security in the amount improperly withdrawn.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Underlying Claim</EM></TI>
<P>5. The substance of the Plaintiff's claim against the Defendants is summarized in the Plaintiffs first affidavit, which was relied on in obtaining the Mareva Order:
<P1>(a) the Plaintiff provided over USD $1.1 million to the Defendants, Chiu and his wife Queenie Lau, for them to make certain investments on the Plaintiff's behalf (paragraph 64);</P1>
<P1>(b) the Defendants induced the Plaintiff to provide these funds based on representations that, among other things, these funds would be used by Chiu to purchase shares for the Plaintiff, Chiu had considerable experience in investing as a result of a high level position with Goldman Sachs, and Chiu owned properties around the world (paragraphs 64, 66 and 5);</P1>
<P1>(c) the Plaintiff understood that any shares purchased using the funds she provided to the Defendants would be held on her behalf and in trust for her (paragraph 65);</P1>
<P1>(d) the Plaintiff subsequently learned, through investigative efforts, that the representations made to her by the Defendants were false (paragraphs 90 to 93); and</P1>
<P1>(e) despite repeated demands, with the exceptions of USD $34,000, the Defendants have failed to return to the Plaintiff the funds she provided to them (paragraphs 70 to 78).</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Mareva Order</EM></TI>
<P>6. On May 18, 2017, the Plaintiff obtained the Mareva Order, the terms of which, among other things, provided that:
<P1>(a) the Defendants not in any way dispose of or deal with or diminish the value of any of their assets whether they are in or outside British Columbia whether in their own names or not and whether solely or jointly owned (paragraph 1(b)); and</P1>
<P1>(b) the Defendants provide the Plaintiff's solicitor with a list (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Defendants' Asset Lists</BOLD>&rdquo;) verified by affidavit setting out all of their assets as of the date of the Mareva Order (paragraph 17).</P1></P>
<P>7. The Mareva Order was emailed to each of the Defendants on May 19, 2017.</P>
<P>8. On May 20, 2017 Chiu messaged Eliza Wei the following:
<QUOTE><P>Hi Eliza, I just opened that email yesterday... I hope you could withdraw the freezing order from the court. If the freezing order continues being in effect, my account is frozen, my families and friends couldn't lend me money to pay back to you, nor could I transfer the money to you ...</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>9. On May 25, 2017, Plaintiff's counsel was first contacted by Mr. Riley, the Defendants' former counsel, who advised that he was in the process of being retained by the Defendants.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Defendants' Asset Lists</EM></TI>
<P>10. On or around June 21, 2017, the Defendants, through counsel, provided the Defendants' Asset Lists to Plaintiff's counsel.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Hong Kong Order</EM></TI>
<P>11. On August 18, 2017, further to efforts to have the Mareva Order recognized and enforced in Hong Kong, the Plaintiff obtained an <EM>ex parte</EM> injunction and preservation order and <EM>ex parte</EM> disclosure order (the &ldquo;<EM>Hong Kong Order</EM>&rdquo;), which provided, among other things, that the Mareva Order be enforced in Hong Kong and the Defendants not remove, dispose of or deal with their assets. The Hong Kong Order further provided that Bank of China and Standard Chartered produce records in respect of the Defendants' accounts, including Chiu's account at Bank of China in Hong Kong (the &ldquo;<BOLD>BOC Account</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Hong Kong Banking Records</EM></TI>
<P>12. The Plaintiff's Hong Kong solicitors subsequently received banking records from Bank of China and Standard Chartered in respect of the accounts maintained by the Defendants. The records indicate that from May 20, 2017 onward Chiu withdrew the following amounts from the BOC Account: $1,663,221.18 in HKD, $2900.00 in CAD, and $123,545.73 in USD, for a total amount of CAD $447,964.78 based on the Bank of Canada foreign exchange rate posted on December 4, 2018.</P>
<P>13. With the exception of $10,500 (Canadian) withdrawn by Chiu from the BOC Account, these withdrawals are in addition to, and not explained by, the exemptions allowed for the legal retainers and monthly personal expenses of the Defendants under the Mareva Order.</P>
<P>14. By letter dated September 15, 2017 counsel for the Plaintiff requested an explanation of the foregoing transactions in light of the Mareva Order and the Defendants' Asset Lists.</P>
<P>15. To date an explanation has not been provided by the Defendants.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>16. On an application for a finding of civil contempt of a court order, the applicant must prove three elements:
<P1>(a) the existence of the court order;</P1>
<P1>(b) the alleged contemnor knew of the order and its terms; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the alleged contemnor intentionally disobeyed one or more terms of the order.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>CE International Resources Holdings LLC v. Yeap Soon Sit</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 186</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. The applicant bears the onus of proving the elements of contempt beyond a reasonable doubt.
<P1><BOLD><EM>CE International Resources</EM> at para. 24.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. The last element of contempt requires proof of deliberate conduct that has the effect of contravening the court order, but it is not necessary for the applicant to prove an intent to bring the court into disrepute or to interfere with the lawful process of the court.
<P1><BOLD><EM>CE International Resources</EM> at para. 25.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>North Vancouver (District) v. Sorrenti</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 316</CITE><PARANUM>11 and 14</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Further, intention may be inferred from the circumstances.
<P1><BOLD><EM>North Vancouver (District)</EM> at paras. 13-14.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>CE International Resources</EM> at para. 25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. The evidence in this case establishes beyond a reasonable doubt that Chiu knew of the Mareva Order and intentionally disobeyed its terms.</P>
<P>21. The Plaintiff's application for the Mareva Order was served on each of the Defendants on May 16, 2017, pursuant to the short leave and alternative service orders of Master Scarth, and the order itself was emailed to each of them on May 19, 2017. Chiu acknowledged both receiving the Mareva Order and that it operated to freeze his accounts, on May 20, 2017 (in Hong Kong). The Mareva Order was clearly brought to the attention of, and its significance appreciated by, Chiu as of May 20, 2017.</P>
<P>22. The banking records disclosed pursuant to the Hong Kong Order make clear that Chiu intentionally disobeyed the Mareva Order in withdrawing funds from the BOC Account.</P>
<P>23. As a result, Chiu should be found in contempt of court for his breach of the Mareva Order.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Appropriate Sanction for Contempt of Court</EM></TI>
<P>24. Upon finding a party in contempt of a court order, the court has the power to impose a fine; make an order of committal; or order that the party guilty of contempt give security for the person's good behaviour.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, R. 22-8(1) and (3).</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>XY, LLC v. Canadian Topsires Selection Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 2629</CITE><PARANUM>22&ndash;24</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. In determining the punishment for contempt, the court will consider the following factors, among others:
<P1>(a) the need to deter the contemnor;</P1>
<P1>(b) the successful party's ability to realize the judgment; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the extent to which the breach was intended.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>CE International</EM> Resources at para. 44.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. The Plaintiff submits that, in the circumstances of this case, it would be appropriate for the court to grant an order requiring that Chiu post as security with the court the amounts withdrawn by him in breach of the Mareva Order, and that such security be paid within seven days. Such an order would ensure that Chiu does not benefit from his contempt, and therefore act as a deterrent, serve as a proportional sanction given the nature of the breaches and provide a measure of protection to the Plaintiff and her ability to recover on an eventual judgment.</P>
<P>27. Deterrence is a particularly important factor in determining the appropriate sanction for Chiu's contempt, as Chiu has shown a continua! disregard for the court process throughout this proceeding. Most recently, Chiu swore an affidavit admitting that he lied to his former counsel, Kieran Siddall, that his wife was in China and unable to attend her scheduled examination for discovery on September 27, 2018. Ms. Lau was not in fact in China, but was in Vancouver, where both she and Chiu were observed by a private investigator in the days leading up to Ms. Lau's examination for discovery, as well as on the scheduled date itself. Chiu subsequently lied to his counsel that he was also in China and no longer resided in Vancouver.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Costs</UNDER></TI>
<P>28. A person found in contempt of court is normally ordered to pay special costs, because a breach of a court order is <EM>prima facie</EM> conduct deserving of rebuke. Moreover, a person who obtains a court order is entitled to have that order complied with. Special costs operate as an indemnity to the party forced to bring an application to remedy the other party's contempt.
<P1><BOLD><EM>CE International Resources</EM> at para. 50; and</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>North Vancouver (District)</EM> at para. 20.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. The Plaintiff respectfully submits that it would be appropriate in this case for the court to award special costs to the Plaintiff, payable forthwith and in any event of the cause assessed at $7,500.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
