<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>5:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. The Defendants accept and adopt the test as described by the plaintiffs at paragrap hs 16-17 of the Notice of Application.</P>
<P>2. Allan Chiu does not deny the existence of the court order. That said, the applicant has failed to prove that Allan Chiu intentionally disobeyed one or more terms of the order.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Absence of intention to disobey one or more terms of the order</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>3. The three part test is conjunctive and necessitates the applicant satisfy all three elements. At issue here is the third element. The applicant has not proven that the &ldquo;... alleged contemnor intentionally disobeyed one or more of the terms of the order.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>CE International Resources Holdings LLC v. Sit</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 186</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>4. The third element of the test requires &ldquo;... proof of deliberate conduct that has the effect of contravening the court order.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>CE International Resources Holdings LLC v. Sit</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 186</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>5. In assessing what is necessary for civil contempt, the British Columbia Court of Appeal has stated:
<QUOTE><P>... the conduct constituting disobedience of the court order must have been intentional, as opposed to accidental or unintentional, and with the fact that intention <EM>may</EM> be inferred from the circumstances... &lsquo;all that is necessary is proof of deliberate conduct that has the effect of contravening the order; an intent to bring the Court into disrepute or to interfere with the due course of justice or with the lawful process of the Court is not an essential element of civil contempt.&rsquo; (emphasis in the original)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>North Vancouver (District) v. Sorrenti</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 314</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF>., citing <CASEREF><SOC>Topgrow Greeenhouses Ltd. v. Houweling</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 355</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>6. Justice Fisher in <EM>CE International Resources</EM> stated that positive proof that disobedience was accidental or unintentional results in an unlikely conviction of contempt as stated::
<QUOTE><P>... the petitioner must show both conduct which was in breach of an order and that the conduct was intentional&mdash;although as has been seen, intention may be inferred from the circumstances of a given case. If the circumstances support such an inference, then in practical terms, the defendant is likely to be convicted in the absence of positive proof that his or her disobedience of the order was in fact accidental or unintentional.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>CE International Resources Holdings LLC v. Sit</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 186</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>7. Deliberate as an adjective is defined as &ldquo;[i]ntentional; premeditated; fully considered.&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Black's Law Dictionary</EM> (10th ed. 2014)</P1></P>
<P>8. Intentional as an adjective is defined as: &ldquo;[d]one with the aim of carrying out the act.&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Black's Law Dictionary</EM> (10th ed. 2014)</P1></P>
<P>9. In response to paragraph 22 of the Notice of Application, Mr. Chiu did not &ldquo;intentionally disobey&rdquo; the Mareva Order as declared by the plaintiff. Rather, in the span of four days between May 17, 2017 at 8:15am and May 20, 2017 at 6:04 am, he received a number of legal documents while in Hong Kong. Mr. Chiu did not recognize the sender and it wasn't until the second e-mail that he determined he required legal counsel. He attempted to retain counsel but, as it was the weekend, was unable to do so and did not receive legal advice until May 25, 2017 at approximately 6am HKT.</P>
<P>10. Intentional and deliberate acts necessitate premeditation and being fully considered. Mr. Chiu could not consider his actions.</P>
<P>11. Further, Mr. Chiu's actions and an assessment of the facts demonstrate that Mr. Chiu did not intentionally or deliberately dispose of assets as:
<P1>(a) the process of transferring funds from the CIBC account to Hong Kong was initiated well in advance of any notice of the impending lawsuit brought by the plaintiff;</P1>
<P1>(b) the actions of Mr. Chiu were a response to funds being deposited by his wife in the midst of marital strife and not related to disposing assets from British Columbia;</P1>
<P1>(c) specifically, the actions of Mr. Chiu were a response to threats to his and his families personal well-being as a result of gambling debts amassed in the year prior May 2017;</P1>
<P1>(d) Mr. Chiu clearly did not understand the terms of the order, which is evidenced by his e-mail to his counsel in which he advised that a &ldquo;response deadline&rdquo; of the court order existed 7 days after the Order was granted, or May 25, 2018. The Order does not contain a response deadline of 7 days. Rather, at paragraph 17 of the Order, the defendants are ordered to produce an asset list within 7 days. There is no other reference to a 7 day response in the Mareva Order and, as is clear at paragraph 8, anyone can apply to vary or discharge the order;</P1>
<P1>(e) The foregoing absence of intention is confirmed by the actions of Mr. Chiu after June 9, 2017 when funds were deposited into his accounts in Hong Kong. It belies logic for an individual who it is argued had the intention to dispose of funds to deposit funds into an account that was subject to a Mareva Order; and</P1>
<P1>(f) this is especially true as, following discussion with legal counsel, the withdrawals from the account were made for the purposes of adhering to the Mareva Order with respect to living expenses.</P1></P>
<P>12. Further, and in any event, the Defendant had not received notice of the order.</P>
<P>13. With respect to paragraph 27 of the Notice of Application, the defendant denies that this is a circumstance where there has been continual disregard for the court process. In reference to the lie made by Allan Chiu to former counsel, Mr. Chiu clarified and confirmed on cross-examination on the affidavits, that he was concerned for his wife's well-being. His wife's brother had been diagnosed with Stage 4 lung cancer, had a mother with failing health, and was dealing with her own health issues. He lied to shield his wife from the perceived stresses of an Examination for Discovery with good intentions and not continual disregard.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
