<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, Allan Chiu, presently with no permanent address but with an address for service in this matter of 700 - 595 Burrard Street, Vancouver British Columbia, SWEAR THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am the husband of the Co-Defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau, and am a personally named defendant in these proceedings and, as such, have personal knowledge of the facts and matters set out herein to this Affidavit, except where the same are stated to be on information and belief and, as to those matters, I verily believe them to be true.</P>
<P>2. I have been primarily responsible for communicating with legal counsel regarding issues related to this file. I recall being advised that an Examination for Discovery was scheduled for September 27, 2018 for my wife, Ms. Lau, to attend.</P>
<P>3. I was advised, and verily believe it to be true, that my wife's biological brother, Kwan Ying Lau, was diagnosed with stage 4 lung cancer.</P>
<P>4. I was advised, and verily believe it to be true, that my wife's biological mother was diagnosed with gall bladder problems which required frequent hospital visits, including hospitalization in or about February, 2018 for approximately 4 weeks, which required surgery to place stents in her bile duct. My mother in law's health continues to deteriorate. We were advised in or about July 2018 that she required another surgery. On or about October 25, 2018, her mother underwent another operation to remove stents and remove her gall bladder.</P>
<P>5. I was advised, and verily believe it to be true, that my wife was diagnosed with Thalessimia and a serious anemic condition which has worsened over the last 18 months.</P>
<P>6. In or about August, 2018 when I was first advised of the scheduled Examination for Discovery of my wife, I observed that my wife was under tremendous stress related to her own health and related to the health of her family members. I observed a loss of appetite, rapid loss of weight, memory loss and lapses, and sleep loss. I was concerned for her own well -being and her mental state.</P>
<P>7. As a result of those observations, I decided not to inform my wife of the scheduled Examination for Discovery of September 27, 2018. I also decided to misinform our previous counsel, Kieran Siddall, that my wife and I were in China and unable to travel for medical reasons related to her blood disorder. I also misinformed our previous co unsel that both my wife and I would be unavailable to attend an Examination for Discovery until December.</P>
<P>8. I am aware that my decision not to inform my wife of the Examination for Discovery scheduled September 27, 2018 and to misinform my counsel that we were in China was foolish. However, I made the decision not to advise her of the obligation with the best intentions of assisting my wife through a difficult period.</P>
<P>9. I am able to attend an Examination for Discovery between the dates of December 18, 2018 to December 20, 2018 and will attend whether ordered, or in response to an Appointment to Examine for Discovery.</P>
<P>10. I swear this affidavit in response to the Notice of Application of the plaintiff in the above referenced action regarding orders for contempt of court, to strike out my Response to Civil Claim, to attend discovery, provide document disclosure, and related orders pertaining to costs.</P>
