<P>95. In further response to paragraph 55 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, the Plaintiff's statement about me learning of the house sale and pressuring her to give more money is false. It was all along the Plaintiffs plan, since December 2015, to sell her Las Vegas properties and use the sale proceeds to diversify into the European market through the BVI company to hide her assets from CRA and Chinese tax authorities.</P>
<P>96. In response to paragraph 56 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, the Plaintiff told me in early August 2016 that she would give me another USD$200,000 to hold for her and when the timing is right, the funds are to be used to invest in the right opportunity in the UK. It was also around this time that the Plaintiff and I were planning a trip to Europe to evaluate market conditions and property investment opportunities. Again, the source of funds from the plaintiff was unknown and, as previously advised by the plaintiff, the funds came from illegal underground banks sent by her husband Huai Xin Li, from China and Hong Kong. At the time, it became clear to me as to why the plaintiff wants me to hold funds for her, because the source of the funds were questionable and she did not want to attract the attention of tax authorities. I agreed to help due to my relationship with the plaintiff and my affection for her.</P>
<P>97. In response to paragraph 57 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, after the Plaintiff told me that she had deposited USD$200,000 into Mrs. Chiu's account, she asked me to prepare another unofficial agreement regarding our proposed investment capital together in the UK. At the time, the Plaintiff and I were deeply in love so I did anything she asked of me. Neither of us specified exactly what investments would be purchased in the UK. The Plaintiff and I together were going to make investment decisions after we had visited Europe.</P>
<P>98. In response to paragraph 59 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. I did not provide to the Plaintiff the summary which forms Exhibit S to the Wei #1 Affidavit. I had not seen this document prior to reading the Wei #1 Affidavit.</P>
<P>99. In response to paragraph 60 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I did not recommend NTB to the Plaintiff as a good investment. The Plaintiff and I had many discussions about possible investments, but I do not recall NTB being one of them.</P>
<P>100. In response to paragraph 61 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I did not sell any NTB shares to the Plaintiff. At that time in October 2016, I asked the Plaintiff for a loan to settle some personal debt.</P>
<P>101. In response to paragraph 62 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I repeat that I made no commitment to purchase any shares in NTB for the Plaintiff. At that time in October 2016, I asked the Plaintiff for a loan to settle some personal debt of about US$250,000. The Plaintiff loaned me that amount without any conditions.</P>
<P>102. In response to paragraph 64 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. The only relationship between the Plaintiff and Mrs. C hiu was that of a social acquaintance without any business relationship. Whereas, the relationship between me and the Plaintiff was an intimate one which also included daily discussions about trading stocks in the Plaintiff's trading accounts and at times explored other investment opportunities with funds of the Plaintiff held by me at her direction.</P>
<P>103. In further response to paragraph 64 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, from June 2015 to April 2017, I helped the Plaintiff trade stocks in both her CIBC Investors' Ed ge account (US Portfolio) and her Essence International Hong Kong trading account (Hong Kong Portfolio). In 2016 alone, I helped the Plaintiff earn a profit of over USD$300,000 in her Hong Kong Portfolio alone.</P>
<P>104. I have been helping the Plaintiff in trading and making money without any compensation since July 3, 2016. I got up every trading morning at 6:30am to help trade US stocks for the Plaintiff without any compensation out of my love and affection for her and because I was in a serious, intimate relationship with her and we had complete trust in each other when it came to money matters.</P>
<P>105. In response to paragraph 65 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, after the Plaintiff and I began our intimate relationship, it became clear that the Plaintiff's motive was for me to hold funds for her to avoid tax implications, as her investment instructions became less clear. The only clear investment decisions were the daily trading activities that I made for the plaintiff regarding trading in her CIBC Investors' Edge account (US Portfolio) as well as her Hong Kong Essence International trading accounts (Hong Kong Portfolio). Although we had many discussions and verbal agreements as to how and where the Plaintiff wished to invest, she would change her mind often and revoke or ch ange her instructions to me. Any money the plaintiff gave to me was held by me such that the plaintiff could avoid tax implications and to respond to directions of the Plaintiff with respect to investments or other uses, such as travelling expenses.</P>
<P>106. In response to paragraph 66 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, the Plaintiff and I often talked about property markets around the world, but I did not tell her that I or Mrs. Chiu owned properties in Singapore, San Francisco, London or elsewhere around the world. Neither I nor Mrs. Chiu owned any real property during the time between meeting the Plaintiff in 2015 and the present.</P>
<P>107. In response to paragraph 67 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, the Plaintiff did not pay me or Mrs. Chiu USD$44,000 for commissions or management fees in the period from June 2015 to October 2016. In the course of our relationship which was during that period of time and extended beyond it to May, 2017, the plaintiff loaned me money and she also gave me money to hold on her behalf. Some of those funds were us ed with her consent for my personal use as well as to pay for our joint entertainment and travelling expenses. As stated in paragraph 103 above, I helped the Plaintiff in trading and making money without any compensation since July 3, 2016.</P>
<P>108. In response to paragraph 68 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, in June 2016, I went to Singapore with the Plaintiff at her request and at her expense to set up a BVI company and to spend vacation time together with the Plaintiff who complained that her exhusband had rarely travelled with her.</P>
<P><BOLD>109.</BOLD> In further response to paragraph 68 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, in September 2016, at the Plaintiff's request, the Plaintiff and I travelled together to Europe for vacation as well as to explore business and investment opportunities. On that trip, I spent lavishly at the Plaintiff's request because she told me that her ex-husband treated her badly, that she rarely travelled and that she had not really lived before. The Plaintiff told me that she wanted to live it up with me. During that trip and the earlier one to Singapore, expenses were never an issue, the Plaintiff and I talked about and it did not matter who paid for what, because we saw a future together. I spent on the joint expenses of myself and the Plaintiff around USD$40,000 during our Singapore trip and over USD$100,000 during our trip to Europe. With consent from the plaintiff, those monies came from funds I was holding for the plaintiff. Where I used credit card to pay expenses, I paid the credit card bills from funds held by me on the plaintiff's behalf.</P>
<P>110. In response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, the Plaintiff and I were not only &ldquo;at times involved in a romantic way&rdquo;. I was very much involved in almost every aspect of the Plaintiff's daily life as her partner since our intimate relationship began in early 2016. At the Plaintiff's request, I would help her in almost every aspect of her daily life, dealing with issues big or small including issues pertaining to her children.</P>
<P>111. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have accompanied the Plaintiff to appointments with her doctor.</P>
<P>112. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of WeChat message exchange of December 6, 2016 concerning my accompanying the Plaintiff to her medical appointment.</P>
<P>113. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have accompanied the Plaintiff to appointments with her son's school principal. Her son is Lan Meng (David) Li, he attend St Georges School.</P>
<P>114. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of WeChat message exchange of October 25, 2016 concerning my accompanying the Plaintiff to a meeting with her son's school principal.</P>
<P>115. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have accompanied the Plaintiff to appointments with her daughter's UBC counsellor to discuss her daughter's first year course selection. Daughter's name is Lan Xin (Catherine) Li, she is a student at UBC.</P>
<P>116. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G1a to G1c&rdquo;</BOLD> are WeChat messages from plaintiff requesting my help.</P>
<P>117. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I witnessed the Plaintiff's signature on a field trip medical form document permitting her son to attend a school organized trip to Europe.</P>
<P>118. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of WeChat message exchange of October 23, 2016 concerning the Plaintiff's request that I witness her signature.</P>
<P>119. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have accompanied the Plaintiff to a fund-raising meeting at her son's school.</P>
<P>120. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of an email message exchange of October 24, 2016 concerning my accompanying the Plaintiff to the fund-raising meeting.</P>
<P>121. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have accompanied the Plaintiff to meetings with her accountants and have helped her deal with tax planning and income tax returns.</P>
<P>122. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of WeChat message exchange of August 24, 2016 concerning a reassessment by CRA of the Plaintiff's 2014 tax return. The Plaintiff asked me to assist her with the CRA reassessment and I met with her and her accountants, BDO Dunwoody, on numerous occasions in April 2016 and with her and her accountant, Lily Chen, on numerous occasions in March 2017.</P>
<P>123. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have assisted the Plaintiff with management of her Las Vegas rental properties and dealing with Frances Cox, the Plaintiff's real estate agent in Las Vegas.</P>
<P>124. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of an email message exchange of between May 27 and June 2, 2016 between me, the Plaintiff and Frances Cox concerning the Plaintiff's Las Vegas properties.</P>
<P>125. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I was the Plaintiff's designated point of contact for communications with her home alarm system and I held the pass code for the Plaintiff's home alarm system.</P>
<P>126. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;L&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of WeChat message exchange of November 17, 2016 concerning my access to the Plaintiff's alarm system.</P>
<P>127. In further response to paragraph 69 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, during the period from early 2016 to March 2017, the Plaintiff and I were in love and planning our future together.</P>
<P>128. In response to paragraph 70 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, in October 2016, after the Plaintiff and I had returned to Vancouver from our trip to Europe, I asked the Plaintiff for a personal loan. At that time, I also told the Plaintiff that I had used some of the funds I was holding for her for other purposes, including expenses. In response, the Plaintiff told me that she considered the funds I had used to be a gift. She further stated she did not expect me to pay her back, but if I had the ability to pay her back, the money would be payable only when I was able to do so. The Plaintiff also told me that she was agreeable to permitting you to use the funds you held on her behalf out of love and affection, because I was helping her to earn good returns in her trading accounts and because our finances would soon be merged anyway as we were then planning to move in together. Specifically, she said I could forget the money spent because it was already spent. We even explored the idea of moving to London UK and settling there. The Plaintiff and I agreed to the terms of a conditional loan by which I would repay to her the sums borrowed when I was able to do so and also the loan could be offset by the profits that I helped her earn in her trading accounts.</P>
<P>129. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;M&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of WeChat message exchange of August 8, 2016 where the Plaintiff states (in Chinese text) that it is time we went hunting for a house in London as the GB Pound Sterling had fallen.</P>
<P>130. In response to paragraph 71 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, in November, 2016, the Plaintiff suspected that there may be a reconciliation between me and Mrs. Chiu from whom I had separated. As a result, the Plaintiff became extremely jealous and she sent me an email talking about some investments that did not exist but the Plaintiff claimed that I was holding for her. At the time, it was clear that the plaintiff had reneged on her verbal consent that the money I held on her behalf and I had used with her consent was a gift and the agreement that I could pay her when I was able to.</P>
<P>131. In further response to paragraph 71 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I told the Plaintiff in a mid-November 2016 meeting that I was, at that time, unable to repay her any money and that I needed time to raise some money. The Plaintiff was very upset during that meeting and drew up by hand a form of Promissory Note for me to sign.</P>
<P>132. In response to paragraph 72 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. I told the Plaintiff none of the things she has sworn I told her. I told her only that Mrs. Chiu was planning to leave me because of my relationship with the Plaintiff. I did not loan Mrs. Chiu money for a fashion business. Mrs. Chiu does not have a fashi on business or any business at all. My daughter does not and did not attend a private school in the United Kingdom.</P>
<P>133. In response to paragraph 73 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I did not sign the Promissory Note which the Plaintiff presented to me at the mid-November 2016 meeting. The signature on Exhibit V to the Wei #1 Affidavit, is not my signature.</P>
<P>134. In further response to paragraph 73 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, although Exhibit V to the Wei #1 Affidavit describes a house and property in Singapore, I do not now n or have I ever owned a property of that description. Further, I did not tell the Plaintiff that I owned such a property.</P>
<P>135. The Plaintiff and I had several more quarrels during November 2016, all of which revolved around the Plaintiff's concern that I was reconciling with Mrs. Chiu. After many discussions on the topic, the Plaintiff and I resumed our personal relationship and we resumed life as a couple as before.</P>
<P>136. The Plaintiff and I met almost every day and went for lunches, dinners, movies and long hikes on the weekends as well as other activities which normal couples do. I helped the Plaintiff book her Christmas family vacation in Hawaii with her children. The Plaintiff wanted me to join her on that vacation but with her children there, it was not convenient. The Plaintiff told me that due to her divorce agreement with her ex-husband the Plaintiff is prohibited from dating until their son, the younger of the Plaintiff's two children, is enrolled in university.</P>
<P>137. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;N&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit is a copy of WeChat message exchange of November 6, 2016 where the Plaintiff invited me to join her in Maui for Christmas 2016 and messages from December 26, 2016 while on holidays.</P>
<P>138. Although I was often in and around the Plaintiff's house and her children knew me, the Plaintiff told me that I had to keep a low profile in front of her children to prevent her ex-husband from finding out about our relationship.</P>
<P>139. In response to paragraph 74 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintif f is false. The Plaintiff did not demand repayment of the loan she had made to me. I told her my wife was considering a divorce.</P>
<P>140. In further response to paragraph 74 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, during the period March 29&ndash;31, 2017, my relationship with the Plaintiff continued as normal with meals and outings taken together. I continued to take and give trading instructions to the Plaintiff.</P>
<P>141. Attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;O&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit are copies of WeChat message exchanges of March 29, 30 and 31, 2017 made between me and the Plaintiff.</P>
<P>142. In response to paragraph 75 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. I was not suspicious of the Plaintiff recording our conversation on March 28, 2017 and neither did I ask her if she was recording it. At that time, the Plaintiff and I were still in a loving relationship as well as continuing to trade stocks together and corresponding via WeChat as a couple.</P>
<P>143. In response to paragraph 76 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. In the days following March 28, 2016, the Plaintiff and I were still carrying on our relationship and meeting for meals and other activities. We did not have a meeting at that time about repayment of the personal loan and I did not ask the Plaintiff to bring any documents or banking records.</P>
<P>144. In response to paragraph 77 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I met with the Plaintiff on April 6, 2017 and, relying on her previous instructions that I could repay funds when I was able to, I made a partial repayment of USD$14,000 to be applied against the Plaintiff's personal loan to me and the Plaintiff gave me a receipt for the payment.</P>
<P>145. In further response to paragraph 77 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;P&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit a copy of a receipt for USD$14,000 signed by the Plaintiff and dated April 6, 2017.</P>
<P>146. In further response to paragraph 77 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I did not steal the Plaintiff's iPhone as she has stated. In fact, I was the first person she called to help her find it. The Plaintiff called me about 2 hours after our meeting of April 6, 2017 and I helped her return to the Starbuck's restaurant where we had met and I helped her look for her phone without success. I suggested that she file a lost phone report with her service provider.</P>
<P>147. In response to paragraph 78 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, it was not on April 9, 2017 but rather on April 25, 2017 that I met with the Plaintiff to give her another payment of USD$20,000 in cash to be applied against the personal loan. I did not ask the Plaintiff to sign a loan agreement at that meeting.</P>
<P>148. In further response to paragraph 78 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have attached hereto and marked <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;Q&rdquo;</BOLD> to my Affidavit a copy of a receipt for USD$20,000 signed by the Plaintiff and dated April 25, 2017.</P>
<P>149. In further response to paragraph 78 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I was in regular, daily contact with the Plaintiff after April 25, 2017 to discuss a repayment schedule. The Plaintiff ceased contact with me in early May 2017. On May 3, 2017, the Plaintiff and I spoke and, at that time, the Plaintiff was still asking me about stocks and potential investments. She specifically asked how to diversify the Hong Kong Portfolio into several smaller accounts in preparation for the implementation of Common Reporting System (&ldquo;CRS&rdquo;) and the potential resulting taxation consequences for the Plaintiff anticipated in July 2017.</P>
<P>150. In response to paragraph 79 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have not taken any steps to hide or dissipate my assets.</P>
<P>151. In response to paragraph 80 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. I did not recommend a BVI account for the Plaintiff and I do not have any BVI or Offshore company accounts myself. The Plaintiff has knowledge about BVI companies from her ex-husband who the Plaintiff told me is hiding a lot of assets under a BVI company as well as in offshore companies in other jurisdictions. The Plaintiff herself formed a BVI company while we were in Singapore together in June 2016. In or about April 2017, the Plaintiff told me that, in an effort to hide her assets from CRA and the Chinese tax authorities, she was considering buying a new identity and a new passport from a small island nation such as Seychelles or Dominican Republic and that the cost would be about USD$750,000. The Plaintiff told me that this is the latest trend and method used by Mainland Chinese nationals to hide their assets from CRS that will be introduced in 2017 by most countries in the world including Canada and China.</P>
<P>152. In response to paragraph 81 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I communicated with the Plaintiff regularly on a daily basis and she was aware of my whereabouts and travel plans at all times. In early May 2017, I told the Plaintiff that I would repay her USD$70,000 on May 16, 2017, but she did not even give me a chance to do that because she filed the Notice of Civil Claim to commence this Action on May 12, 2017.</P>
<P>153. In response to paragraph 82 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I received a WeChat message from the Plaintiff on May 11, 2017 (Pacific Standard Time) while I was in Hong Kong. The plaintiff asked me to call her, which I did.</P>
<P>154. In response to paragraphs 84&ndash;86 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I had a telephone conversation with the Plaintiff on May 12, 2017 while I was in Hong Kong and I told he r that I planned to repay her the personal loan but that I needed more time to do so. She was very emotional because she thought I was reconciling with Mrs. Chiu. This was a recurring pattern in our relationship. The Plaintiff would be easy going and agr eeable when she felt secure in our relationship but whenever she felt that there was possibility of a reconciliation between me and Mrs. Chiu, she would take a completely different tone and would renege on her verbal agreement regarding our personal loan. I did not tell the Plaintiff in our telephone conversation of May 12, 2017 that I had already travelled to Hong Kong with Mrs Chiu, because I did not want to upset her.</P>
<P>155. In further response to paragraph 86 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, the Plaintiff was well aware of my plans to travel to Hong Kong in early May 2017 and she had planned to join me there in mid-May if she could arrange for her ex-husband to travel to Vancouver to stay with her children. In the event that her ex-husband was not available at that time, the Plaintiff and I had discussed the opportunity to meet in Hong Kong in June 2017 when her son would be visiting family in China.</P>
<P>156. In response to paragraph 87 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. From the start of our relationship in 2015, I told the Plaintiff that I had owned and operated a company in Singapore with the name Stoneset Equities Asia Pte. Ltd. and that that company was no longer in existence. The Singapore company was not a subsidiary, parent or sister company to an Alberta company which operated under the name, &ldquo;Stoneset Equities&rdquo; and I was never an employee of that Alberta company or any Alberta company of a similar name.</P>
<P>157. In response to paragraph 88 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I was not aware that the P laintiff had engaged a private investigator to research my past while the Plaintiff and I were still carrying on an intimate relationship as described elsewhere in this Affidavit.</P>
<P>158. In response to paragraphs 89&ndash;93 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I was not aware that the Plaintiff had engaged others to conduct research into my past.</P>
<P>159. In further response to paragraph 90 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I never claimed to the Plaintiff or to any other person that I had the credentials, qualifications or work experience listed in that paragraph.</P>
<P>160. In further response to paragraph 91 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I do not now nor have I ever owned property in Hong Kong.</P>
<P>161. In further response to paragraph 93 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, I have no knowledge of the items listed there except that, per paragraph 93b, I do not own any property in Singapore.</P>
<P>162. In response to paragraph 94 of the Wei #1 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. I have never owned property in Singapore directly or indirectly and I have never held any interest in or position in a BVI company and neither did I tell the Plaintiff any such thing.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>AFFIDAVIT #2 OF RONG (ELIZA) WEI</UNDER></TI>
<P>163. I have read the Affidavit #2 of the Plaintiff sworn herein 16 May 2017 (the &ldquo;Wei #2 Affidavit&rdquo;).</P>
<P>164. In response to paragraph 5 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. The Plaintiff and I never discussed ownership of ray residence in Vancouver but the fact is that I rented my residence. I have not owned property anywhere in the world since 2015.</P>
<P>165. In response to paragraph 7 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, the Birney Property was, prior to August 2018, the residence of myself and Mrs. Chiu. Mrs. Chiu and I were separated temporarily after she found out the plaintiff and I were having an affair but I never told the Plaintiff that I did not know the whereabouts of Mrs. Chiu.</P>
<P>166. In response to paragraph 8 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, the Plaintiff could have contacted Mrs. Chiu via her cell phone or via the WeChat texting app.</P>
<P>167. In response to paragraph 9 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, I had no plans to meet with the Plaintiff on May 14, 2017 but, as stated above, I did speak by telephone with the Plaintiff on May 12, 2017.</P>
<P>168. In response to paragraph 10 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, I told the Plaintiff on May 12, 2017 that I intended to pay her USD$70,000 in the week of May 16, 2017 to be applied against the personal loan she had made to me.</P>
<P>169. In response to paragraph 11 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, it is the Plaintiff who was deceiving me by continuing in a loving and intimate relationship with me while, at the same time, hiring private investigators and others to investigate my past.</P>
<P>170. In response to paragraph 12 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, on May 12, 2017, the Plaintiff knew, from our conversation of the same date, that I was not at home that day.</P>
<P>171. In response to paragraph 13 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, the Plaintiff knew from our conversation of the previous day that I was not planning on being home on May 13, 2017. As the Exhibits to this Affidavit show, the Plaintiff and I were, for many months, in daily contact by email, text message and telephone and the Plaintiff could have contacted me by those methods on May 13, 2017.</P>
<P>172. In response to paragraphs 14 and 15 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, the Plaintiff was well aware of my plans to travel to Hong Kong in early May 2017 and she knew on May 14, 2017 that I had already travelled to Hong Kong on May 10, 2017. The Plaintiff and I had made plans to meet up in Hong Kong later in June 2017.</P>
<P>173. The plaintiff's efforts to serve me with documents at my home when she knew I had already travelled to Hong Kong are a blatant effort by the Plaintiff to mislead the Court that I had gone into hiding.</P>
<P>174. In response to paragraphs 17&ndash;22 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, the Plaintiff had various means to contact me or Mrs. Chiu by email, text message and telephone but chose not to do so.</P>
<P>175. In response to paragraph 23 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, I normally used credit cards when I travelled together with the Plaintiff but sometimes had to use cash in places where credit cards were not accepted. I did not and do not travel with large amounts of cash.</P>
<P>176. In response to paragraphs 24 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, this statement by the Plaintiff is false. I do not keep cash in a safe deposit box and neither did I tell the Plaintiff any of the things alleged in paragraph 24 of the Wei #2 Affidavit.</P>
<P>177. In response to paragraphs 25&ndash;27 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, I did not prepare or present to the Plaintiff an investment summary and I do not have a TD Bank account.</P>
<P>178. In response to paragraphs 28&ndash;30 of the Wei #2 Affidavit, I do not have a Scotiabank account.</P></BLOCK2>
