<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, Allan Chiu, presently with no permanent address but with an address for service in this matter of 700 - 595 Burrard Street, Vancouver British Columbia, SWEAR THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am the husband of the Co-Defendant, Mui Kwan Queenie Lau, and am a personally named defendant in these proceedings and, as such, have personal knowledge of the facts and matters set out herein to this Affidavit, except where the same are stated to be on information and belief and, as to those matters, I verily believe them to be true.</P>
<P>2. By the spring of 2017, my wife having been aware that I was involved in an intimate relationship with the plaintiff for approximately one year could no longer tolerate the relationship.</P>
<P>3. As a result, my wife informed me, in or around March, 2017, that she was considering a separation. Further, my wife advised me that the she was going to transfer all funds that were in her CIBC account that were related to the plaintiff to my accounts in Singapore and Hong Kong.</P>
<P>4. As a result, I received a total of four transactions from my wife's account in Canada into my bank accounts:
<P1>(a) On April 10, 2017, $50,000USD was deposited to my Standard Chartered account in Singapore;</P1>
<P1>(b) On April 12, 2017, $120,000USD was deposited to my Standard Chartered account in Singapore;</P1>
<P1>(c) On May 14, 2017, $175,000USD was deposited to my Bank of China (HK) account in Hong Kong; and</P1>
<P1>(d) On May 16, 2017, $100,000USD was deposited to my Bank of China (HK) account in Hong Kong.</P1></P>
<P>5. On May 10, 2018, I travelled with my wife to Hong Kong for the purpose of saving our marriage. I was aware that my wife was considering a separation. At times, the relationship was tense. At other times, we were working things out and the relationship appeared positive.</P>
<P>6. Soon after my arrival in Hong Kong, I made four transfers from the Standard Chartered Account in Singapore to my Bank of China (HK) account, the particulars are contained in this my affidavit at paragraph 11 as follows:
<P1>(a) On May 16, 2017, I transferred $10,000USD;</P1>
<P1>(b) On May 16, 2017, I transferred $60,000USD;</P1>
<P1>(c) On May 17, 2017, I transferred $70,000USD; and</P1>
<P1>(d) On May 23, 2017, I transferred $29,000USD.</P1></P>
<P>7. I needed the funds to be transferred from Singapore to Hong Kong to settle perso nal debts and pay expenses. I have a gambling problem. When I refer to &ldquo;personal debts&rdquo; within this affidavit it refers to the following circumstances:
<P1>(a) starting in approximately the fall of 2016, I accumulated and amassed debt from unsanctioned gambling;</P1>
<P1>(b) I was actively gambling on horse races, card games, and dice games;</P1>
<P1>(c) I was loaned funds from &ldquo;loan sharks&rdquo; to support my gambling problem;</P1>
<P1>(d) the loans came with threats of physical violence to me and family members if they were not repaid; and</P1>
<P1>(e) over the course of 2016-2017, my debt was approximately $2,000,000HKD and was growing as a result of high interest charges that the &ldquo;loans sharks&rdquo; applied to the loan.</P1></P>
<P>8. Shortly after my arrival in Hong Kong, I received phone calls and had in-person discussions with the &ldquo;loan sharks&rdquo;. They threatened me and advised that I had to pay my outstanding debt or they would cause physical harm to me and my family.</P>
<P>9. To secure the personal safety of my family and myself, I attended to satisfying the loan which included using funds in my Bank of China (HK) account.</P>
<P>10. I include below a chart referencing the Bank of China (Hong Kong) Ltd. Bank in my name with account number XXXXXXXXXX between the dates of May 12, 2017 and August 31, 2017 as contained in Affidavit #3 of Tina Le&mdash;December 5, 2018&mdash;Exhibit G&mdash;Pages 39-40. The date and time of the transactions in the document titled &ldquo;C.I.F. System A/C Financial History Transaction List&rdquo; are times in Hong Kong. The dates and times contained in the chart below were completed for me by staff at the office of my legal counsel and I verily believe the calculation of the dates and times to be correct.</P>
<P>11. The explanation contained under the head &ldquo;the circumstances of the transaction&rdquo; are a combination of facts that I recall, facts that I have been ab le to recall on review of financial records, and where stated, are believed to be true.</P>
