<P>16. On May 17, 2017 at 8:15am HKT, which was May 16, 2017 at 5:15pm PST, an e-mail was delivered to my e-mail account at allan@allanchiuconsulting.asia from Gail Major. The e-mail is attached as Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; to the 3<SUP>rd</SUP> affidavit of Tina Le dated December 5, 2018 at pages 2-3.</P>
<P>17. I am unable to recall the specific time or time of day I viewed the e-mail from Gail Major. However, I recall seeing the name Gail Major and that her name was unfamiliar to me. Even without opening the e-mail, I saw attachments were included in the e-mail. As such, I did not open the e-mail. I did not open the e-mail of Gail Major dated May 16, 2017 until approximately 2 weeks after receipt.</P>
<P>18. On May 20, 2017 at 6:04am HKT, which was May 19, 2017 at 3:04pm PST, I received another e-mail from Gail Major. In the subject line to the e-mail, I saw the words &ldquo;order&rdquo;. I realized I should talk to legal counsel. I attended to searching for legal counsel in Ca nada. I recall opening this e-mail either immediately prior to my phone call with Jef Poulsen or while on the telephone with Jef Poulsen. I do not recall the specific time. I did not open the attachment immediately. The e-mail is attached as Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo; to the 3<SUP>rd</SUP> affidavit of Tina Le dated December 5, 2018 at page 5.</P>
<P>19. On May 20, 2017 at around 8 am HKT, I was able to reach Jef Poulsen at Poulsen Law. Mr. Poulsen advised me that it was around 5:00 pm on a Friday in Vancouver, Mr. Poulsen advised me he was leaving the office. He requested that I forward to him the documents I received.</P>
<P>20. On May 20, 2017, between 8:21 am and 8:29 am HKT, I forwarded the e-mail of Gail Major dated May 19, 2017 at 3:04pm PST to Mr. Poulsen. I forwarded the e-mail twice as I had received a &ldquo;bounce-back&rdquo; and I believed the first e-mail had been rejected. Attached and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to my affidavit is a copy of the e-mails to Mr. Poulsen from May 19, 2017 to May 23, 2017.</P>
<P>21. At some point on May 20, 2017 HKT, I opened the attachment in the Gail Major e-mail dated May 19, 2017 at 3:04pm PST containing the Mareva Order. I read the Mareva Order and the reference to a freezing order. I did not understand all of the terms contained in the Mareva Order.</P>
<P>22. The following morning, on May 21, 2017 at 10:05 am HKT, which was May 20, 2017 at 7:05pm PST, I delivered a message to the plaintiff to offer funds and in exchange requested she remove the freezing order.</P>
<P>23. On May 23, 2017 at 9:27 am PST, which was May 24, 2017 at 12:27am, I e-mailed Mr. Poulsen as I had not heard from him to inform him that my wife and I wished to retain him for the purposes of applying for an extension to file a response. I wrote in my e-mail that we had a &ldquo;... pressing response deadline of the court order on May 25 (7 days from Thursday, May 18)&rdquo;. I did not understand that I could apply to discharge or vary the order at the time I delivered the e-mail to Mr. Poulsen.</P>
<P>24. On May 23, 2017 at 2:30 pm PST, which was May 24, 2017 at 5:30am, I received an e-mail from Jef Poulsen. He advised that he needed to obtain copies of the Application and Affidavits that were filed with respect to the Order. I was not aware prior to receiving this e-mail from Mr. Poulsen that the documents he requested were contained in the first e-mail from Gail Major dated May 16, 2017 at 5:15pm PST.</P>
<P>25. On May 25, 2017 at approximately 6:00 am HKT, I talked to Mr. Poulsen and Mr. Riley by telephone with my wife present with me in Hong Kong.</P>
<P>26. During my discussions with legal counsel, I came to understand that my accounts outside of British Columbia were subject to the Mareva Order and not to be used in contravention of the order.</P>
<P>27. As delineated above, after learning the effect of the Mareva Order, I only used funds contained in the account pursuant to the exception contained in the order contained at paragraph 4 which prohibiting my wife and I from spending more than $3,500 each per month on ordinary living expenses.</P>
<P>28. I deposited funds into the account on June 9, 2017 and subsequently withdrew the funds for livin g expenses. The withdrawals subsequent to June 9, 2017 were reported to the Plaintiff as evidenced at paragraph 5 to the 3<SUP>rd</SUP> affidavit of Tina Le dated December 5, 2018.</P>
<P>29. I had no intention to dispose of or hide assets. I withdrew the funds deposited by my wife to satisfy personal debts and pay for living expenses while in Hong Kong.</P>
<P>30. I swear this affidavit in response to the Notice of Application of the plaintiff in the above referenced action dated December 5, 2018 regarding orders for contempt of court.</P>
