<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</TI>
<P>Name(s) of Applicant(s): Allan Chiu and Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu</P>
<P>To: Rong Wei</P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant(s) to the presiding master at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, BC on December 18, 2018 at 9: 45 am for the order(s) set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDER(S) SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. The Order of Mr. Justice Grauer pronounced on December 4, 2018 be varied or amended such that Paragraph 4 of the order now read:
<QUOTE><P>Ms. Lau shall deliver an Amended List of Documents that lists all of the documents that are or have been in her possession or control that could, if available, be used to prove or disprove a material fact, as well as all other documents Ms. Lau intends to refer to at trial (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Amended List of Documents</BOLD>&rdquo;) no later than January 25, 2019.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. This application relates to a request for the court to use its discretion pursuant to Rule 22 -4, or otherwise, to vary or amend the order of Justice Grauer as being unable to receive documents from third parties necessary to comply with the order.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Litigation History</EM></TI>
<P>2. The Plaintiffs claim, to which the Defendants deny, is summarized in the affidavit of Rong Wei, relied on in obtaining a Mareva Order. The Plaintiff stated and claims:
<P1>(a) the Plaintiff provided over USD $1.1 million to the Defendants, Chiu and his wife Queene Lau, for them to make certain investments on the Plaintiff's behalf (paragraph 64);</P1>
<P1>(b) the Defendants induced the Plaintiff to provide these funds based on representations that, among other things, these funds would be used by Chiu to purchase shares for the Plainitff, Chiu had considerable experience in investing as a result of a high level position with Goldman Sachs, and Chiu owned properties around the world (paragraphs 64, 66, and 5);</P1>
<P1>(c) the Plaintiff understood that any shares purchased using the funds she provided to the Defendants would be held on her behalf and in trust for her (paragraph 65);</P1>
<P1>(d) the Plaintiff subsequently learned, through investigative efforts, that the representations made to her by the Defendants were false (paragraphs 90 to 93); and</P1>
<P1>(e) despite repeated demands, with the exceptions of USD $34,000, the Defendants have failed to return to the Plaintiff the funds she provided to them (paragraphs 70 to 78).</P1>
<P1><EM>Aff # 1 of R. Wei</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>3. On December 4, 2018, on application by the Plaintiff, among the Orders sought by the Plaintiff were the following orders related to document production:
<QUOTE><P>4. By consent, Ms. Lau shall deliver an Amended List of Documents that lists all of the documents that are or have been in her possession or control that could, if available, be used to prove or disprove a material fact, as well as all other documents Ms. Lau intends to refer to at trial (the &ldquo;Amended List of Documents&rdquo;) within 14 days of the order of this Court.</P>
<P>5. By consent, Ms. Lau shall include in the Amended List of Documents the documents and classes of documents set out at Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; to the plaintiff's notice of application filed November 21, 2018.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Aff. #1 of S. Culver</EM>, Ex. XX</P1></P>
<P>4. Schedule A referenced in the order and attached to the Notice of Application filed on November 21, 2018 reads:
<QUOTE><P>1. Copies of all bank and financial records in the defendants' own names, in the names of aliases, or in the names of other entities over which either of the defendants exercises control from the period June 1, 2015 to present, including, without limiting the generality of the foregoing, all bank records from the institutions listed in Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; to Mr. Chiu's June 21, 2017 affidavit and Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; to Ms. Chiu's June 21, 2017 affidavit.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Notice of Application of the Plaintiff</EM>, November 21, 2018</P1></P>
<P>5. On December 7, 2018, counsel for the defendant began to deliver correspondence to financial institutions in Canada and Hong Kong to produce records. A request for documentation was additionally delivered to BMW Leasing.
<P1><EM>Aff. #1 of S. Culver</EM>, Ex. &ldquo;A to F&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>6. On December 12, 2018, on receipt of correspondence from plaintiff counsel containing specific contacts within the financial institutions, counsel for the defendants delivered subsequent letters demanding document production to those contacts.
<P1><EM>Aff. #1 of S. Culver</EM>, Ex. &ldquo;G-H&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>7. Through no fault of the defendants, a number of documents anticipated to be listed in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; have not yet been provided.</P>
<P>8. Trial for this matter is scheduled for 7 days beginning March 4, 2019.</P>
<P>9. The Amended List of Documents lists the following documents. The Amended List of Documents was delivered to plaintiff counsel by way of e -mail on December 17, 2018 at 8:07 pm:
<QUOTE><P>1. CIBC Investor Series Account Statements for account number XXXXXXXXXX from June 1, 2015 to October 31, 2018 (the last statement generated);</P>
<P>2. CIBC Mastercard account statements for account number ending 1123 from January 1, 2015 to December 10, 2018;</P>
<P>3. CIBC US Visa account statements for account number ending 2211 from October 7, 2015 to December 3, 2018;</P>
<P>4. CIBC Account statements for account number XXXXXXXXXX from June 1, 2015 to December 12, 2018;</P>
<P>5. CIBC Account statements for account number XXXXXXXXXX from June 1, 2015 to December 12, 2018;</P>
<P>6. CIBC Account Statements for account number XXXXXXXXXX from June 1, 2015 to December 12, 2018;</P>
<P>7. Hudson Bay Mastercard account statements for account number ending in 5977 from November 25, 2017 to October 24, 2018;</P>
<P>8. CostcoPlatinum Mastercard account statements for account number ending 8739 from November 22, 2017 to November 21, 2018;</P>
<P>9. Bank of Montreal Everyday Banking Account statements for account XXXXXXXXXX from September 18, 2017 to December 7, 2018;</P>
<P>10. BMW Financial Services lease agreement dated September 19, 2017.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>10. The relevant rules are reproduced below:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>22-4</N><TI>Extending or shortening time</TI>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>The court may extend or shorten any period of time provided for in these Supreme Court Civil Rules or in an order of the court, even though the application for the extension or the order granting the extension is made after the period of time has expired.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM></BOLD>, BC Reg 168/2009, Rules 22-4.</P1></P>
<P>11. The court has inherent jurisdiction to do all that is &ldquo;necessary to do justice between the parties.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia (Director of Civil Forfeiture v. John Doe</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 940</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF> [&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>John Doe</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;]</P1></P>
<P>12. The rule for extending time is permissive in nature and broad and scope. The interests of justice is the overriding question in considering whether or not a court should exercise its discretion under the Rule.
<P1><BOLD><EM>John Doe</EM>,</BOLD> para. 23</P1></P></BLOCK2>
