<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P>Name of applicant: Rong (Eliza) Wei</P>
<P>TO: Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu and Allan Chiu</P>
<P>AND TO: Their Solicitors</P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge or master at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia on February 19, 2019, at 9:45 a.m. for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Against Mui Kwan Queenie Lau</TI>
<P>1. A declaration that Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Ms. Lau</BOLD>&rdquo;) is in contempt of court, with penalty hearing to follow, by reason of one or more of the following:
<P1>a. breaching paragraphs 1 and 4 of the order of Madam Justice Humphries dated May 18, 2017 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Mareva Order</BOLD>&rdquo;), in May 2017, October 2017, November 2017, December 2017, January 2017, February 2018, March 2018, May 2018, June 2018, July 2018, August 2018, September 2018, October 2018, November 2018;</P1>
<P1>b. breaching paragraph 4 of the Mareva Order, as varied by paragraph 8 the order of Mr. Justice Grauer dated December 4, 2018 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>December 2018 Order</BOLD>), in December 2018;</P1>
<P1>c. for refusing or neglecting to attend without lawful excuse at the time and place appointed for her examination for discovery on September 27, 2018, December 19, 2018, and January 18, 2019; and</P1>
<P1>d. breaching paragraph 4 of the Mareva Order by failing since in or about December 2017 to advise the plaintiff of her sources of spending.</P1></P>
<P>2. An order that the response to civil claim of Ms. Lau filed on August 30, 2017, be struck out and the proceeding continue as if no response to civil claim had been filed.</P>
<P>3. An order that special costs of this application be payable by Ms. Lau forthwith in any event of the cause.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Against Allan Chiu</TI>
<P>4. Within 7 days of the date of this order, or such other time as this Honourable Court order permits, Allan Chiu (&ldquo;<BOLD>Mr. Chiu</BOLD>&rdquo;) produce to the Applicant the documents and classes of documents set out at <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this notice of application.</P>
<P>5. Costs of the application.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Overview of Application</UNDER></TI>
<P>6. This case concerns the actions of Mr. Chiu and his wife Ms. Lau, who between 2015 and 2016 received from the plaintiff, Rong (Eliza) Wei (&ldquo;<BOLD>Ms. Wei</BOLD>&rdquo;), approximately USD$1.1 million to invest on her behalf.</P>
<P>7. Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau did not invest the funds they received from Ms. Wei and did not provide Ms. Wei a return on her investment. Instead, Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau converted Ms. Wei's funds to their own uses. Despite repeated demands, Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau have failed to return to Ms. Wei all but USD$34,000 of the funds that she provided to them.</P>
<P>8. Ms. Wei brings this application seeking an order that Ms. Lau be found in contempt for her breach of the terms of the Mareva Order and her willful refusal to attend her examination for discovery and an order striking Ms. Lau's response to civil claim. Ms. Wei also seeks an order for the disclosure of material documents from Mr. Chiu.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Procedural History</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ms. Wei Obtains Mareva Order</EM></TI>
<P>9. Ms. Wei filed her notice of civil claim on May 12, 2017, claiming the sum of approximately $1.5 million on account of the amounts provided by Ms. Wei to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau. Ms. Wei also sought interim and permanent injunctive relief restraining the defendants from disposing of their assets, as well as equitable relief, including tracing orders and orders that the defendants hold any real and personal property as constructive trustees.</P>
<P>10. Humphries J. granted the Mareva Order on short notice to the defendants, prohibiting the defendants from disposing of their assets.</P>
<P>11. Paragraph 4 of the Mareva Order imposed the following restrictions on the defendants' spending:
<QUOTE><P>This Order does not prohibit the defendants from <UNDER>spending $3,500.00 each per month on ordinary living expenses</UNDER> and a total of $25,000.00 each on legal advice and representation. <UNDER>Before spending any money on living, business or legal expenses, the defendant must advise the plaintiff's solicitors in writing of the intended source of the funds</UNDER>. (Emphasis added.)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. The Mareva Order was emailed to each of the defendants on May 19, 2017.</P>
<P>13. The Mareva Order required the defendants to provide Ms. Wei's solicitor with an Asset List within seven days setting out all of the defendants' assets as of the date of the Mareva Order.</P>
<P>14. On December 4, 2018, Grauer J. varied the Mareva Order, with the consent of the defendants, to reduce the amount that Ms. Lau is permitted to spend each month on ordinary living expenses to $1,000 per month.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Defendants' Delay in Providing Document Discovery</EM></TI>
<P>15. Ms. Wei served her list of documents on October 23, 2017. Ms. Wei served an amended list of documents on November 9, 2017, listing additional documents.</P>
<P>16. Ms. Wei scheduled examinations for discovery of Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau in November 2017. Those examinations could not proceed, as the defendants had yet to deliver their list of documents, despite several requests. They were adjourned by agreement.</P>
<P>17. On May 29, 2018, Ms. Wei filed an application seeking an order that the defendants deliver a list of documents.</P>
<P>18. On June 6, 2018, Master Vos ordered that the defendants deliver a list of documents within 21 days.</P>
<P>19. On July 3, 2018, the defendants delivered a list of documents. Despite Ms. Wei requesting copies of the documents on July 5, 2018, the documents were not delivered until August.</P>
<P>20. By letter dated October 10, 2018, Ms. Wei made demand of the defendants pursuant to sub-rules 7-1(10) to (12) of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> that the defendants' list of documents be amended to include additional documents, including the documents set out at <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this notice of application. Counsel for Ms. Wei left requests for the same at Mr. Chiu's examination for discovery on January 22, 2019.</P>
<P>21. On December 4, 2018, Grauer J. ordered Ms. Lau to produce bank and financial records from the accounts that the outlined in her Asset List.</P>
<P>22. Those records were delivered to Ms. Wei on December 17, 2018, and January 17, 2019.</P>
<P>23. Ms. Wei has yet to receive production of the bank and financial records of Mr. Chiu.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ms. Lau Fails to Attend Scheduled Examination for Discovery on September 27, 2018</EM></TI>
<P>24. On September 19, 2018, Ms. Wei served an appointment to examine for discovery Ms. Lau on September 27, 2018, at the offices of her then counsel and attached conduct money.</P>
<P>25. On September 24, 2018, then counsel for the defendants advised that he was instructed that Ms. Lau was in China and unable to travel for medical reasons. Counsel for the defendants explained that he understood that Ms. Lau had a blood disorder, and it was hoped it would resolve sufficiently by December so that she would be able to travel then. Counsel for the defendants requested that the examination of Ms. Lau be rescheduled to December, as Ms. Lau was unable to attend the scheduled discovery on September 27, 2018.</P>
<P>26. On September 26, 2018, counsel for the defendants sent an email to counsel for Ms. Wei reiterating that Ms. Lau was not available for the reasons previously expressed.</P>
<P>27. Ms. Lau did not attend at her scheduled examination for discovery on September 27. A certificate of non-attendance was issued.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ms. Lau was not in China on the Date of her Examination</EM></TI>
<P>28. The reason proffered by Ms. Lau's then-counsel on her behalf for her inability to attend her scheduled examination for discovery on September 27 was that she was in China and unable to travel to Vancouver for medical conditions. That was not true.</P>
<P>29. On September 24, the day Ms. Lau's counsel advised Ms. Wei's counsel that Ms. Lau was in China and unable to travel for medical reasons, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were observed by John Hilpert, a private investigator retained by Ms. Wei, at the McArthurGlen outlet mall in Richmond, British Columbia in a dark BMW vehicle.</P>
<P>30. During the afternoon of September 26, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were observed again by Mr. Hilpert at numerous locations in Vancouver, including playing tennis on the UBC campus, driving their BMW, walking a dog at a park and picking up their daughter at the Lansdowne Skytrain station. Mr. Hilpert observed that the BMW had an expired insurance sticker.</P>
<P>31. On September 27, the day of her scheduled examination, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were observed again by Mr. Hilpert at several locations in Vancouver.</P>
<P>32. On September 28, Ms. Lau and Mr. Chiu were again observed by Mr. Hilpert at several locations in Vancouver, including attending the CIBC branch located at 4489 West 10<SUP>th</SUP> Avenue, playing tennis on the UBC campus and going to the McArthurGlen outlet mall in Richmond.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Further Attempts to Schedule Discoveries of the Defendants</EM></TI>
<P>33. As a result of those events, among others, Ms. Wei brought the application heard by Grauer J. on December 4, 2018. In response to that application, and the application for an order that Lau's response to civil to claim be struck, Ms. Lau swore an affidavit on December 4, 2018, in which she stated, at para. 11:
<QUOTE><P>I am able to attend an examination for discovery between the dates of December 18, 2018 to December 20, 2018 and will attend whether ordered, or in response to an appointment to examine for discovery.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>34. On December 11, 2018, Ms. Wei served an appointment to examine for discovery of Ms. Lau returnable on December 19, 2018. Ms. Lau did not attend at her scheduled examination for discovery on December 19, 2018. A certificate of non-attendance was issued. The following day, December 20, 2018, Lau's counsel delivered to Ms. Wei's counsel a doctor's note dated December 19, 2018, stating, in full:
<QUOTE><P>This is to confirm that Ms. Chiu is unable to attend her court appearance today for medical reasons. She will be unable to attend for the next four weeks for medical reasons.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>35. On January 4, 2019, Ms. Wei served an appointment to examine for discovery Ms. Lau on January 18, 2019 (being four weeks from the doctor's note of December 19, 2018).</P>
<P>36. Ms. Lau did not attend her scheduled examination for discovery on January 18. A certificate of non-attendance was issued. Late in the afternoon on January 17, 2019, Ms. Lau's lawyer delivered to Ms. Wei's lawyer a further doctor's note of that day stating, in full:
<QUOTE><P>Unable to attend court on 18<SUP>th</SUP> January due to sickness. Will remain unfit for court until the end of February 2019.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>37. The trial date is March 4, 2019.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Spending of Funds Contrary to the Mareva Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>38. The banking records produced in December 2018 pursuant to the order of Grauer J. revealed significant and consistent spending by Ms. Lau in excess of what the Mareva Order (both originally and as varied by Grauer J.) permits.</P>
<P>39. On September 7, 2017, Ms. Lau swore an affidavit in which she deposed:
<QUOTE><P>I only found out that the plaintiff had obtained a world-wide Mareva injunction against me and the first defendant (Allan Chiu) on or around May 25, 2017, i.e. after the first defendant's conference call with the lawyers in Canada.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>40. Accordingly, at least by May 25, 2017, Ms. Lau had knowledge of the Mareva Order. A few days later, on May 29, 2017, USD$154,000 was withdrawn from her CIBC US dollar account #XXXXXXXXXX at 5796 University Boulevard, Vancouver.</P>
<P>41. On January 9, 2019, Mr. Chiu was found in contempt of court for intentionally disobeying the Mareva Order by withdrawing amounts in breach of the Mareva Order after being served with a copy thereof.</P>
<P>42. Ms. Lau has breached the Mareva Order by spending in excess of the monthly amount permitted ($3,500 per month from May 2017 to November 2018, and $1,000 per month as of December 4, 2018) in at least May 2017, October 2017, November 2017, December 2017, January 2017, February 2018, March 2018, May 2018, June 2018, July 2018, August 2018, September 2018, October 2018, November 2018, and December 2018. That spending is outlined in the table appended as <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Striking Ms. Chiu's Response to Civil Claim for Failure to Attend Examination</UNDER></TI>
<P>43. A party of record has an obligation to make him or herself available for an examination for discovery: Rule 7-2(1).</P>
<P>44. Where a defendant, contrary to the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> and without lawful excuse, neglects to attend at the time and place appointed for his or her examination for discovery, the court may strike out the response to civil claim and order the proceeding to continue against that person as if no response to civil claim had been filed: Rule 22-7(2) and (5).</P>
<P>45. Where the evidence is clear that a defendant has engaged in obstructive conduct, the court will be more willing to apply the sanction of striking the defence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Han v. Cho</SOC><CITE>2008 BCSC 1621</CITE><PARANUM>19&ndash;21</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Kalcsa v. Read Media Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 248</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>636023 B.C. Ltd. v. A-Millenia Construction Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2005 BCSC 1563</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>46. The facts of this case merit an order that Ms. Lau's response to civil claim be struck.</P>
<P>47. Ms. Lau's response to civil claim should be struck and the proceeding continued against her as if no response to civil claim had been filed.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Ms. Lau is in Contempt of Court</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Failure to Attend</EM></TI>
<P>48. Ms. Lau's failure to attend her scheduled examination for discovery and her non-compliance with paragraph 4 of the Mareva Order both constitute contempt of court.</P>
<P>49. Pursuant to Rule 22-8(4) of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, a person who is guilty of refusing, without lawful excuse, to attend at the time and place appointed for his or her examination for discovery is subject to the court's power to punish contempt of court.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Mareva Order</EM></TI>
<P>50. The Mareva Order limits the amounts Ms. Lau may spend on ordinary living expenses and requires that the defendants advise Ms. Wei's solicitors in writing of the intended source of funds for living expenses <UNDER>before</UNDER> any money is spent.</P>
<P>51. The financial records produced pursuant to the December 2018 Order, show that Ms. Lau has regularly spent more than the amounts permitted by the Mareva Order and the December 2018 Order. Ms. Lau spent more than $3,500 on ordinary living expenses in May 2017, October 2017, November 2017, December 2017, January 2017, February 2018, March 2018, May 2018, June 2018, July 2018, August 2018, September 2018, October 2018, November 2018, and in excess of $1,000 in December 2018.</P>
<P>52. Expenditures made in these months include:
<P1>a. the transfer of USD$154,000 from her CIBC US Dollar Account XXXXXXXXXX on May 29, 2017;</P1>
<P1>b. monthly payments of $1,260.12&ndash;$1,289.59 to lease and insure a 2017 BMW X4 M40i, which lease Ms. Lau entered on September 9, 2017, after the Mareva Order;</P1>
<P1>c. purchases of $1,192.80 at Holt Renfrew on May 6, 2018 (as charged to her Hudson Bay Mastercard); and</P1>
<P1>d. purchases of $3,090.21 at Holt Renfrew, SSense, JCrew and Uniqlo in the month of June 2018 (as charged to her Hudson Bay MasterCard and Costco Platinum MasterCard).</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Analysis</EM></TI>
<P>53. On an application for contempt, the applicant must prove three elements, being a clear order, actual knowledge of the order, and evidence of wilful noncompliance.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Carey v. Laiken</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 17</CITE><PARANUM>30&ndash;35</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>XY, LLC v. Canadian Topsires Selection Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 2629</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Unifor Local Union No. VCTA v. Sunlover Holding Co.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 922</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>54. Moreover, Ms. Lau has failed, contrary to the Mareva Order, to provide Ms. Wei's solicitors with advance notice in writing of the intended source of funds for living expenses since approximately December of 2017.</P>
<P>55. All of the elements of contempt are met in this case.</P>
<P>56. With respect to Ms. Lau's failure to comply with paragraph 4 of the Mareva Order, the evidence establishes that all three elements of a contempt finding are present. First, the order is clear that Ms. Lau must notify Ms. Wei's solicitors of the intended source of funds <UNDER>before</UNDER> spending any money on living, business or legal expenses and must spent within the limits that it sets. Second, it is clear that Ms. Lau had knowledge of the order, as Ms. Lau swore to such knowledge in her past affidavit and, through her counsel, previously provided Ms. Wei's solicitors with information concerning Ms. Lau's spending on living expenses. Third, Ms. Lau's failure to provide Ms. Wei's solicitors with the court ordered information before spending money and her excess of the limits set is willful conduct in contravention of the Mareva Order.
<P1><BOLD><EM>XY, LLC</EM></BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. With respect to Ms. Lau's refusal to attend her scheduled examination for discovery, Ms. Wei properly served her appointments to examine Ms. Lau in accordance with the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>. While the defendants' evidence is that Mr. Chui hid the scheduling of the first examination from Ms. Lau, the examinations since have been scheduled on notice to her or on dates of her suggestion. The reasons she has provided for failing to attend, including the doctor's notes provided excusing her due to &ldquo;sickness&rdquo;, are inadequate. That is particularly the case where she swore an affidavit stating that she would attend and where the most recent note claims that she is unable to attend until, effectively, the trial date. Those reasons being inadequate, Ms. Lau should be found to have willfully and deliberately failed to attend on at least two occasions, and she should be found in contempt of court for doing so.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Unifor Local Union No. VCTA</EM>;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Dhillon v. Parmar</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 1115</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Stovicek Estate v. Napier International Technologies Inc.</SOC><CITE>[1996] B.C.J. No. 1460</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Special Costs</UNDER></TI>
<P>58. A person found in contempt is normally ordered to pay special costs because a breach of a court order is <EM>prima facie</EM> conduct deserving of rebuke. Special costs otherwise operate to indemnify the party forced to bring an application to remedy the other party's contempt.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>North Vancouver (District) v. Sorrenti</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 316</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Production of Additional Documents</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>59.</BOLD> Ms. Wei has demanded production of additional documents from the defendants. In particular, Ms. Wei has demanded production of all the defendants' bank and financial records from the period of June 1, 2015, to present.</P>
<P>60. Ms. Lau produced an Amended List of Documents addressing that demand pursuant to the December 2018 Order. Mr. Chiu has yet to do the same.</P>
<P><BOLD>61.</BOLD> The requested documents are capable of being used to prove or disprove material facts at issue in the proceeding. In particular, the documents are relevant to Ms. Wei's tracing claims against the defendants and are sought from the time that Ms. Wei first advanced funds to the present date. The documents are producible and should have been listed in the defendants' list of documents.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Han v. Cho</SOC><CITE>2008 BCSC 1207</CITE><PARANUM>6-7</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
