<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Ms. Lau was not in China</EM></TI>
<P>11. On September 27, 2018, Ms. Lau was scheduled to attend an appointment for an examination for discovery. Her counsel, at the time, had been advised by Mr Chiu that Ms. Lau had a blood disorder and was in China. That information was communicated to Mr Dennis, and it was not entirely accurate. It was true that Ms. Lau had a blood disorder. However, it was not true that she was in China, and Mr Chiu made that false claim because he was concerned about Ms. Lau's health and the stress that she would be subjected to in the examination for discovery.</P>
<P>12. Mr Chiu has admitted that it was his idea and he mistakenly did so in order to subject Ms. Lau to further stress that would aggregate her medical conditions. It was a mistake and factored into Mr Chiu being found in contempt of court.</P>
<P>13. Mr Chiu, out of consideration for Ms. Lau's health, never advised her of the September 27, 2018 examination for discovery, and, as a result Ms. Lau was unaware of her obligation to attend on that date.
