<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>5:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. The applicant has failed to prove that Ms. Lau intentionally disobeyed one or more terms of the order.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Absence of intention to disobey one or more terms of the order</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>2. The three part test is conjunctive and necessitates the applicant satisfy all three elements. At issue here is the third element. The applicant has not proven that the &ldquo;... alleged contemnor intentionally disobeyed one or more of the terms of the order.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>CE International Resources Holdings LLC v. Sit</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 186</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>3. The third element of the test requires &ldquo;... proof of <BOLD><UNDER>deliberate</UNDER></BOLD> conduct that has the effect of contravening the court order.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>CE International Resources Holdings LLC v. Sit</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 186</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>4. In assessing what is necessary for civil contempt, the British Columbia Court of Appeal has stated:
<QUOTE><P>... the conduct constituting disobedience of the court order must have been intentional, as opposed to accidental or unintentional, and with the fact that intention <EM>may</EM> be inferred from the circumstances...&lsquo;all that is necessary is proof of deliberate conduct that has the effect of contravening the order; an intent to bring the Court into disrepute or to interfere with the due course of justice or with the lawful process of the Court is not an essential element of civil contempt.&rsquo; (emphasis in the original)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>North Vancouver (District) v. Sorrenti</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 314</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF>., citing <CASEREF><SOC>Topgrow Greeenhouses Ltd. v. Houweling</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 355</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>5. Justice Fisher in <EM>CE International Resources</EM> stated that positive proof that disobedience was accidental or unintentional results in an unlikely conviction of contempt as stated::
<QUOTE><P>... the petitioner must show both conduct which was in breach of an order and that the conduct was intentional&mdash;although as has been seen, intention may be inferred from the circumstances of a given case. If the circumstances support such an inference, then in practical terms, t he defendant is likely to be convicted in the absence of positive proof that his or her disobedience of the order was in fact accidental or unintentional.</P>
<P><BOLD>Read par 24&mdash;(1) existence of the order&mdash;conceded (2) knew of the order and its terms&mdash;he did not (3) intentionally disobeyed requires proof of deliberate conduct&mdash;there is no such proof in this case</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Read par 25 &rarr; must be able to determine exactly what he is supposed to do &rarr; Mr Chiu was not able to do so as evidenced by believing there was a 7 day deadline to respond and texting the plaintiff advising her that he could no longer borrow money or pay her back</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>In an effort to understand the order he immediately makes efforts to retain Canadian counsel &rarr; that demonstrates good faith on his part to understand and be in compliance</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>CE International Resources Holdings LLC v. Sit</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 186</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>6. Deliberate as an adjective is defined as &ldquo;[i]ntentional; premeditated; fully considered.&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Black's Law Dictionary</EM> (10th ed. 2014)</P1></P>
<P>7. Intentional as an adjective is defined as: &ldquo;[d]one with the aim of carrying out the act.&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Black's Law Dictionary</EM> (10th ed. 2014)</P1></P>
<P>8. In response to the allegations that Ms. Lau intentionally missed dates for examinations for discovery, the medical evidence demonstrates that Ms. Lau was too ill to attend and Mr Dennis was provided with prompt responses and medical documentation. As such, Ms. Lau did not &ldquo;intentionally disobey&rdquo; the obligation to attend.</P>
<P>9. Intentional and deliberate acts necessitate premeditation and being fully considered. The applicant has failed to meet those requirements. The suggestion that Ms. Lau has been continually disregarding the court process is not substantiated. While it is true that Ms. Lau missed the September 27, 2018 examination for discovery, she has provided the explanation that she was unaware of the date and Mr Chiu took responsibility for that falsehood and confirmed he did not tell Ms. Lau of the obligation to attend on that date, because he was concerned for her well-being. Ms. Lau was either entirely unaware of the initial discovery scheduled for September 27, 2017 as a result of Mr. Chiu's decision to protect her from the stress of the discovery amidst health issues and her brother's failing health.</P>
<P>10. The information Mr. Chiu gave was false and he clarified and confirmed that during cross&mdash;examination that he was concerned about his wife's well-being and thought the discovery process would be too stressful for her.</P>
<P>11. His intentions in preventing his wife from going through more stress were good, but the manner that he went about it was wrong, and he understands that and has accepted full responsibility.</P>
<P>12. The allegations made in relation to breaching the Order are unfounded as the financial documentation and explanations provided by Ms. Lau account for the entirety of the alleged impugned transactions.</P>
<P>13. Additionally, Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; relied on is complete with errors making the evidence impossible to reconcile. First, an approximate $6,000 error in Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; of the Notice of Application to have Ms. Lau found in contempt of court with respect to the total amount spent on November 2017 Second, for a number of purported transactions alleged to demonstrate the defendants have exceeded the limits under the order, the transactions were consented to by the Plaintiff. Third, a number of purported transactions reported as withdrawals from the account are actually deposits into the account. Specifically, we reference each of the Scotiabank Personal Line of Credit payments or deposits which were incorrectly reported as withdrawals which include:
<P1>(a) September 2017: deposits totalling $1,600 (page 367 of Chan Affidavit #1);</P1>
<P1>(b) October 2017: deposit totalling $300 (page 369 of Chan Affidavit #1);</P1>
<P1>(c) December 2017: deposit totalling $3 13.00 (page 371 of Chan Affidavit #1); The errors continue throughout the Scotiabank Personal Line of Credit records.</P1></P>
<P>14. Further, there are discrepancies contained in all credit card accounts as payments to the account are considered an example of spending without a corresponding transfer from an account.</P>
<P>15. The applicant is seeking an extraordinary remedy with quasi-criminal implications for Ms. Lau. Accordingly, the respondent has carefully reviewed each transaction and have provided complete explanations for each one.</P>
<P>16. Given the seriousness of breaching a court order, the test to be applied on this application is one of <EM>beyond a reasonable a reasonable doubt</EM>. A review of the medical records reveal that Ms. Lau is quite ill and is scheduled for surgery on February 22, 2019, which provides a reasonable explanation for the delay in having an examination for discovery. Moreover, the financial records demonstrate there has not been a breach of the Order.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
