<FREEFORM>
<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>Name of applicant:</BOLD> Allan Chiu and Mui Kwan Queenie Chiu (&ldquo;the Defendants&rdquo;)</P>
<P><BOLD>To:</BOLD> Rong Wei</P>
<P><BOLD>TAKE NOTICE</BOLD> that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding master at The Law Courts, 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia, V6Z 2E1, on <BOLD>Thursday, February 14, 2019</BOLD>, at 9:45 a.m. for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. An Order that the Mareva Order issued by the Honourable Madam Justice Humphries in the Supreme Court of British Columbia dated May 18, 2017 be discharged;</P>
<P>2. Alternatively, an Order that paragraph 4 of the Mareva Order issued by the Honourable Madam Justice Humphries in the Supreme Court of British Columbia dated May 18, 2017 be varied to exclude a limit on the amount that may be paid for legal advice and represent ation;</P>
<P>3. An Order granting the Defendants liberty to apply for damages or special costs at a later date;</P>
<P>4. An Order that the Plaintiff pay the Defendants costs of this application, in any event of the cause.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. This action concerns claims by the Plaintiff for funds allegedly provided between 2015-2016 in the amount of $1.1 million USD.</P>
<P>2. The Plaintiff alleges she was induced to provide the funds to the Defendants based on misrepresentations that include, among others, that the funds would be us ed to purchase shares for the Plaintiff, and that Mr. Chiu had considerable experience investment experience.</P>
<P>3. The Defendants deny the Plaintiff's alleged claims in their entirety, and maintains a number of defences against those claims.</P>
<P>4. On May 18, 2017, an application for a Mareva injunction was brought <EM>ex parte</EM> by the Plaintiff and the order granted by Madam Justice Humphries (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Mareva Order</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>5. The Mareva Order required, among other things, the Defendants to each make and serve an affidavit of assets disclosing each of the Defendants' respective assets and holdings and it restricted legal fees in the matter to a total of $25,000 per defendant.</P>
<P>6. The Plaintiffs obtained a worldwide <EM>Mareva</EM> injunction against each of the Defendants in Hong Kong on August 18, 2017.</P>
<P>7. On December 20, 2018, a Notice of Application brought by the Plaintiff wherein Mr. Chiu was determined to be held in contempt of the order with the penalty phase yet to be heard.</P>
<P>8. In seeking the Mareva order, the Plaintiff relied on the following affidavits:
<P1>(a) Affidavit #1 of Rong Wei made May 12, 2017 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Wei #1</BOLD>&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(b) Affidavit #1 of John Hilpert made May 12, 2017 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Hilpert #1</BOLD>&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(c) Affidavit #2 of Rong Wei made May 16, 2017 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Wei #2</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1></P>
<P>9. The affidavits relied on for the purpose of seeking the Mareva Order con tain numerous statements of fact that are untrue and which constitute a material misrepresentation, each of which is addressed below.</P>
<P>10. In response to the affidavits, Mr. Chiu deposed Affidavit #2 made December 12, 2018 (<BOLD>&ldquo;Chiu #2&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>11. The Plaintiff stated in their Notice of Application seeking the Mareva Order that through investigative measures that representations purportedly made by the Defendants were false.</P>
<P>12. As delineated below with reference to the paragraph in the Notice of Application particularizing the purported misrepresentation, the Defendant denies that the representations were made.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Attendance at the University of British Columbia and Brown University&mdash;(Para 21(a) and (b))</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>13. Ms. Wei deposed that the Defendants stated that Mr. Chiu had attended Brown University and the University of British Columbia. At paragraphs 7 through 9 of Hilpert #1, Mr. Hilpert deposed that each university was contacted and were unable to confirm Mr. Chiu's attendance.
<P1>Wei #1 at para. 5(b); Hilbert #1 at paras. 10&ndash;12.</P1></P>
<P>14. Mr. Chiu did not attend and never told Ms. Wei that he had attended either institution. Brown University was discussed solely for the purpose of determining potential universities for the plaintiff's son.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 6</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Employment at Goldman Sachs&mdash;(Para 21(c))</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>15. Ms. Wei deposed that the Defendant had stated he had experience in investing as a result of high level positions with Goldman Sachs and specifically that he had retired working as the Department Head of the Asia Pacific Institutional Buying Side of Goldm an Sachs' Hong Kong Office. At paragraphs 9 through 10 of Hilpert #1, Mr. Hilpert deposed that he was unable to confirm that anyone named Allan Chiu had worked for or been associated with Goldman Sachs.
<P1>Wei #1 at para. 5(b); Hilbert #1 at paras. 10&ndash;12.</P1></P>
<P>16. Mr. Chiu told the Plaintiff, and the Plaintiff knows it to be true, that Mr, Chiu ran his own business while living in Singapore prior to his retirement in 2010. Further, he only advised the plaintiff that he knew individuals were employed in the Goldman Sachs office.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 7</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Stoneset Equities and Temasek Private Holdings&mdash;Para (21(d) and (e))</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>17. Ms. Wei deposed that Mr. Chiu had informed her that he had lived in Calgary, Alberta and was employed with Temasek Private Holdings Ltd. Mr. Hilpert deposed that he was unable to find a connection.
<P1>Wei #1 at paras. 13-14; Hilbert #1 at paras. 10&ndash;12.</P1></P>
<P>18. Mr. Chiu lived in Calgary but never was employed with Temasek Private Holdings Ltd. nor did Mr. Chiu advise Ms. Wei that he had been. At all times, he had advised and Ms. Wei knew that Mr. Chiu was retired since 2010.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 8</P1></P>
<P>19. That said, Mr. Hilpert provided that he &ldquo;understood&rdquo; that &ldquo;Stoneset Asia Equities&rdquo;, which we assume was meant to be &ldquo;Stoneset Equities Asia Pte. Ltd.&rdquo; (&ldquo;<BOLD>Stoneset Asia</BOLD>&rdquo;), was part of a group of Stoneset companies, which we assume meant there was an affiliation with &ldquo;Stoneset Equity Development Corp.&rdquo; (&ldquo;<BOLD>Stoneset Alberta</BOLD>&rdquo;). Mr. Hilpert refers to an unknown and unidentified private equity trade informant known as &ldquo;P.S.&rdquo; who reportedly had access to personal information to assist in identifying Mr. Chiu. The nature of that access is not defined nor is it provided. P.S. reportedly advised that Mr. Chiu had been involved, in an unknown capacity, in a major equities scandal in Calgary around 2011 involving a real estate scheme which proved to be a Ponzi scheme. Mr. Hilpert did not particularize the nature of the &ldquo;major equities&rdquo; scandal or real estate scheme that proved to be a Ponzi scheme, nor did he refer to evidence of the Ponzi scheme.
<P1>Hilbert #1 at paras. 15&ndash;20.</P1></P>
<P>20. Ms. Wei and Mr. Hilpert's speculative statements have no basis in fact. While Mr. Chiu operated Stoneset Asia until his retirement in 2010, the company was unrelated to Stoneset Alberta except that Mr. Chiu organized, for a fee, seminars for Stoneset Alberta in Asia. Mr. Chiu never worked for Stoneset Alberta in Calgary.
<P1>Chiu #2 at paras. 10-11</P1></P>
<P>21. Mr. Chiu was never involved in an equities scandal, real estate investment scheme, or Ponzi scheme with the Alberta company. Mr. Chiu ne ver invested nor induced others to invest in Stoneset Alberta. Further, no evidence was provided to demonstrate that Stoneset Alberta was ever investigated or charged in relation to a major equities scandal or Ponzi scheme.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 10&ndash;14</P1></P>
<P>22. Mr. Chiu does not know of anyone with the initials P.S. generally or specifically within the private equity trade or investment community in Alberta. As such, the purported source of the information is unreliable.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 15.</P1></P>
<P>23. Further, on a review of the Consolidated Financial Statements for the years ended December 31, 2010 and 2009 for Stoneset Alberta, as accessed from SEDAR, we note the following statements:
<P1>(a) Stoneset Alberta was created by an amalgamation on February 16, 2010 between Aqueous Capital Corp. and Stoneset Equities Ltd. (page 5);</P1>
<P1>(b) The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company, and its subsidiaries, Stoneset Development Corporation, the general partner of Stoneset Del Lago Limited Partnership (&ldquo;SVDL LP&rdquo;), SVDL LP, Stoneset One Mortgage Corporation, Stoneset Development (Saskatchewan) Corporation, Stoneset Development (Invermere) Corporation and Stonesetgreen B.C. Development Corp (page 6).</P1>
<P1>Affidavit #2 of S. Culver at Exhibit G</P1></P>
<P>24. The above referenced document is a public document and has remained public at all material times in this matter. It was not presented to the Court and was not included in the affidavit of John Hilpert. The financial statements directly contrast his &ldquo;...understanding that [Stoneset Asia] is part of the Stoneset group of companies.&rdquo; Stoneset Asia is not noted by Stoneset Alberta as being a subsidiary. As Mr. Chiu clarified, it never was.</P>
<P>25. Mr. Hilpert deposed the following:
<QUOTE><P>I also conducted a search of Alberta Investors Protection's website and found an article entitled &ldquo;Calgary Investigation reveals Alberta Investors protection;&rdquo; which referred to Stoneset Equities. <BOLD>I cannot recall if the article was posted directly on Alberta Investors Protection's website or whether the website had a link to the article, but I printed out a copy of the article.</BOLD> Attached as Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo; to this affidavit is a copy of the article I printed out entitled &ldquo;Calgary Investigation reveals Alberta Investors protection; (sic)&rdquo; (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Hilbert #1 at para. 30.</P1></P>
<P>26. Alberta Investors Protection (&ldquo;<BOLD>AIP</BOLD>&rdquo;) is not a regulated website. The websites disclaimer identifies that it was formed to disseminate information with &ldquo;minimal restrictions as investors have been threatened with lawsuits for simply pursuing their rights. As such this website presents and open forum to seek out as much information as possible for the purpose of seeking the truth.&rdquo; Content on the site may be posted anonymously and is not tracked to the source. As such, the information contained on the site is inherently unreliable.</P>
<P>27. The article at Exhibit B of Mr. Hilpert's affidavit notes the source and posting of this site was done by a Ron Reinhold. Ron Reinhold operates a website called Rainbow Investigations at rainbowinvestigations.com. On searching the website, the article cited by Mr. Hilpert is found with distinct differences. First, at Exhibit B, we note that the font is different as between the content of the story on the top half of the page and the &ldquo;table of real estate trusts that have had trouble in Alberta&rdquo;. Second, and more importantly, the original document does not include the word &ldquo;[Asia]&rdquo; after Stoneset Equities. The word &ldquo;[Asia]&rdquo; is added after Stoneset Equities in Exhibit B. The addition of the word &ldquo;[Asia]&rdquo; is the only difference between Exhibit B and the original document.
<P1>Hilbert #1 at para. 30 and Culver at paras. 1&ndash;7</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>United Kingdom Properties in the Name of Mut Kwan Queenie Lan&mdash;(Para 21(f))</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>28. The Plaintiff deposed that Mr. Chiu advised her that Mrs. Chiu owned a townhouse in London's W8 district.
<P1>Wei #1 at para. 66.</P1></P>
<P>29. At all material times, neither Mr. Chiu nor Mrs. Chiu owned property anywhere in the world. This explains why the investigators were unable to find property owned by the Defendants. Further, Mr. Chiu did not advise the Plaintif f that either he or Mrs. Chiu owned property anywhere in the world.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 106.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Royal Bank&mdash;(Para. 21(g))</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>30. Mr. Hilpert deposed that he had sourced outstanding debt and a debt inquiry from the Royal Bank against Allan Chiu and adds that the Royal Bank has written of the debt as bad debt in 2014.
<P1>Hilbert #1 at para. 30.</P1></P>
<P>31. Mr. Hilpert does not include an exhibit with respect to his findings. Mr. Chiu is not aware of demands, claims, or litigation against himself anywhere by the Royal Bank of Canada.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 20.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Ocean Drive Property&mdash;(Para. 22)</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>32. Ms. Wei deposed that Mr. Chiu advised her that he had properties around the world and specifically a house and apartment in Singapore. The address for the home purportedly owned by Mr. Chiu is XXXXXXXXXX Further, Ms. Wei purports that Mr. Chiu signed a promissory note which reads &ldquo;I will use my house (located at XXXXXXXXXX as my pledge to gurantee (sic) the repayment.&rdquo; This fact that Mr. Chiu executed the promissory note is additionally relied on at paragraph 15 of the Not ice of Application.
<P1>Wei #1 at paras. 66, 73 and Exhibit V.</P1></P>
<P>33. Mr. Chiu never owned property in Singapore at XXXXXXXXXX Further, he did not tell the Plaintiff he owned the property. He did not sign the Promissory Note.
<P1>Chiu #2 at para. 20.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>British Virgin Islands Accounts&mdash;(Para. 23 &amp; 26&ndash;29)</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>34. In the Notice of Application, under the header of &ldquo;Dissipation of Assets&rdquo;, the Plaintiff asserts as fact at paragraphs 23 and 27 that Mr. Chiu &ldquo;...told [Wei] that for tax purposes he had used a number of companies put &ldquo;layers between himself and the properties he owned&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Notice of Application at para. 23</EM></P1></P>
<P>35. Further, in the Notice of Application, the fact relied on is that it was Mr. Chiu that recommended to the Plaintiff that she open a bank account in the BVI to hold her investments. Further, the Notice of Application relies on the purported statements of the Mr. Chiu regarding the &ldquo;layers between property owned by Mr. Chiu&rdquo; and the alleged recommendation by Mr. Chiu that the plaintiff use BVI accounts to hold investments which led to a &ldquo;real concern that [the Defendants] may transfer or hide assets...&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Notice of Application at para. 26&ndash;29</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>36. The Plaintiff deposed that at times on or around May 16, 2016 the Plaintiff was reluctant to invest in the UK and that subsequently funds were delivered after May 16, 2016 for the purpose of Mr. Chiu purchasing shares in the UK market on her behalf.
<P1>Chiu #2 at paras. 49, 53.</P1></P>
<P>37. Ms. Wei incorporated Century Lane Investment Ltd. in the British Virgin Islands on or about June 22, 2016.
<P1>Chiu #2 at paras. 91-92, and Exhibit D</P1></P>
<P>38. Ms. Wei deposed the following:
<QUOTE><P>At one point Mr. Chiu recommended that I open an account in the British Virgin Islands to hold all of my investments. I believe he may also have accounts there, or in other offshore locations.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Wei #1 at para. 80</P1></P>
<P>39. Ms. Wei subsequently clarifies in the affidavit that she retained the private investigator &ldquo;I-OnAsia Ltd.&rdquo; in or about the fall of 2016. It was then, on receiving information from the private investigator, that she asked Mr. Chiu about the Ocean Drive Property. She deposes that it was at that point that Mr. Chiu told her he had used lots of layers between himself and properties he owned and advised her she should own companies in the BVI.
<P1>Wei #1 at para. 88</P1></P>
<P>40. We are unable to reconcile how it came to be that Ms. Wei incorporated her business in the BVI on the recommendation or suggestion of Mr. Chiu in June 22, 2016 before she claims she received information from Mr. Chiu in the fall of 2016 advising her to own a BVI company.</P>
<P>41. In any event, Mr. Chiu does not have accounts or incorporated companies in the BVI and did not recommend BVI accounts. Rather, it was the Plaintiff who incorporated in the BVI on or about June 22, 2016 and delivered a text message on or about November 11, 2016 via WeChat requesting an appointment be set up to use the BVI account.
<P1>Chiu #1 at paras. 77, 83&ndash;85, 91, 95, 108, 151, Exhibit C</P1></P>
<P>42. Further, it is the Plaintiff's actions that warrant censure. The Plaintiff delivered messages to Mr. Chiu confirming that she was using underground banks in China to transfer funds out of China. It became clear to Mr. Chiu in early August 2016 that the use of the underground banks was because the source of the funds was questionable and the plaintiff was intending to avoid the attention of tax authorities. Further, the Plaintiff advised of her intention to transfer undeclared assets from China into a BVI Company.
<P1>Chi #1 at paras. 73, 87-88, 91, 96, Exhibit C1, D</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Allan Chiu Consulting&mdash;(Hilbert Affidavit&mdash;Paras.25&ndash;28)</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>43. Mr. Hilpert deposed that Mr. Chiu held himself out as operating a business under the name Allan Chiu Consulting. Adding further, that he had discovered a website that had been operational and owned by Mr. Chiu with a URL of allanchiuconsulting.asia that was active until March 2016, a Hong Kong PO Box business address for Allan Chiu Consulting, and an address and phone number in Calgary that confirmed the URL was registered to Allan Chiu.
<P1>Hilbert #1 at paras. 25&ndash;28.</P1></P>
<P>44. No exhibits were provided to demonstrate the source of the facts contained in the above paragraph. Allan Chiu has used an e-mail address of allan@allanchiuconsulting.asia since approximately 2009. However, no website has operated using the name or URL of allanchiuconsulting.asia and no Post Office Box in Hong Kong has ever been used, as alleged, under the name of &ldquo;Allan Chiu Consulting&rdquo;. Allan Chiu has never operated or held himself to operate a business under the name of Allan Chiu Consulting.
<P1>Chiu #2 at paras. 16&ndash;19</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. The court has an inherent discretionary jurisdiction to set aside or vary its own Orders.</P>
<P>2. In the <EM>ex parte</EM> application material non-disclosure occurred or, alternatively, material misrepresentations were made in seeking the Order such that the Order should be discharged, or alternatively, varied.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Material Non-Disclosure or Material Misrepresentation</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>3. Material non-disclosure arises where a party in an <EM>ex parte</EM> application fails to disclose a fact which may affect the outcome of the application. In a hearing to set aside a Mareva order, the court is to first consider whether there was material non-disclosure and, if not, is to proceed to a hearing <EM>de novo</EM> on the merits.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Northwestpharmacy.com Inc. v. Yates</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>4. Persons making an application <EM>ex parte</EM> must use the utmost good faith and, if they do not, they cannot keep the results of their application. Recently stated as an obligation that the applicant must be &ldquo;profoundly fair&rdquo; and disclose all important aspects of the evidence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lazard Bros. &amp; Co. v. Banque Industrielle de Moscou</SOC><CITE>[1932] 1 K.B. 617</CITE><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[1933] AC 289</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>102 LJKB 191</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; and <CASEREF><SOC>Northwestpharmacy.com Inc. v. Yates</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>5. Where a court finds material non-disclosure, it likely will, set aside the Mareva order. That said, the court retains discretion to consider whether the injunction should stand in light of additional evidence on the set-aside application.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Save-A-Lot Holdings Corp. v. Christensen</SOC><CITE>2019 BCSC</CITE><PARANUM>4</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>6. With respect to material misrepresentation, the British Columbia Court of Appeal has clarified that where there has been a material misrepresentation on the application for <EM>ex parte</EM> order, then the order should be set aside.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kraupner v. Ruby</SOC><YEAR>1957</YEAR><CITE>21 W.W.R. 145</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>7 D.L.R. (2d) 383</CITE><PARANUM>32</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> citing <CASEREF><SOC>Lazard Bros. &amp; Co. v. Banque Industrielle de Moscou</SOC><CITE>[1932] 1 K.B. 617</CITE><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[1933] AC 289</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>102 LJKB 191</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>7. The principles surrounding full and frank and true disclosure and material misrepresentation were further particularized in <CASEREF><SOC>Bennet Estate v. Islamic Republic of Iran</SOC></CASEREF> where the Ontario Superior Court of Justice said:
<QUOTE><P>(i) Material facts are those of which the court must be made aware in arriving at a decision, non-disclosure of which may have affected the court's approach to the motion, made the decision doubtful, or affected the outcome of the motion; ...</P>
<P><BOLD>(iii) In making full and frank disclosure of the relevant facts, the plaintiff must include facts which may explain the defendant's position, if known to the plaintiff.</BOLD> The onus on the plaintiff to make full and complete disclosure is not discharged by disclosing only what is the most limited basis of information that may be relevant. Full disclosure may and often will require a plaintiff to advise the court of matters of both fact and of law which form the position of the other side;</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P><BOLD>(vi) If a finding is made of material misrepresentation or material no n-disclosure the court is not stripped of all of its discretion but, generally speaking, the <EM>ex parte</EM> order will be set aside.</BOLD></P>
<P>(emphasis added)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Continental Casualty Co. v. Symons</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 2021</CITE><PARANUM>34</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>8. In British Columbia, the Court of Appeal addressed the approach for Mareva Orders in Canada noting that the approach differs from other jurisdictions as a &ldquo;flexible&rdquo; or &ldquo;relaxed&rdquo; approach. Under this approach, an applicant is required to establish a <EM>prima facie</EM> case and subsequently the focus of the application shifts to a balance of convenience.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kepis &amp; Pobe Financial Group Inc. v. Timins Corporation</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 420</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>9. Following an exhaustive review of the law, Justice D. Smith provided the following summary:
<QUOTE><P>In sum, British Columbia has forged a flexible approach to applications for Mareva injunctions from the more stringent rules -based approach in Aetna. Under this approach, &ldquo;[t]he fundamental question in each case is whether the granting of an injunction is just and equitable in all the circumstances of the case&rdquo;: <CASEREF><SOC>Mooney v. Orr No. 2</SOC></CASEREF> at para. 43. The legal test requires an applicant to establish:</P>
<P>(1) the threshold issue of a strong prima facie or good arguable case; and</P>
<P>(2) in balancing the interests of the parties, to consider all the relevant factors, including
<P1>(i) the existence of exigible assets by the defendant both inside and outside the jurisdiction, and</P1>
<P1>(ii) whether there is evidence of a real risk of disposal or dissipation of those assets that would impede the enforcement of any favourable judgment to the plaintiff.</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Kepis &amp; Pobe Financial Group Inc.</EM>, at para. 18.</P1></P>
<P>10. At issue in this situation is whether the Plaintiff adequately satisfied the first part of the legal test above. The question that warrants asking is whether, had the Court received all of the relevant information, would the Plaintiff have demonstrated a strong <EM>prima facie</EM> case?</P>
<P>11. In <EM>Mooney</EM>, the principles that underlie whether a strong <EM>prima facie</EM> case described challenges to the Court, whether on a contested application or an <EM>ex parte</EM> application as follows:
<P1>(a) it is difficult to summarize all relevant evidence given the limitations in time in presenting the case (paragraph 30);</P1>
<P1>(b) a conclusion on the strength of the case is made without findings as to credibility</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mooney v. Orr</SOC><CITE>[1994] B.C.J. No. 2652</CITE><PARANUM>31-32</PARANUM><COURTJUR>&ldquo;B.C.S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>12. Further, in <EM>Mooney</EM>, the Court proceeded to accept the following test:
<QUOTE><P><EM>In these circumstances, I consider the right course is to adopt the test of a good arguable case, in the sense of a case which is more than barely capable of serious argument, and yet not necessarily one which the judge believes to have a better than 50% chance of success</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mooney v. Orr</SOC><CITE>[1994] B.C.J. No. 2652</CITE><PARANUM>31-32</PARANUM><COURTJUR>&ldquo;B.C.S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> citing <CASEREF><SOC>Ninemia Maritime Corp. v. Trave Schiffahrtsgessedschaft mbH</SOC><CITE>[1984] 1 All E.R. 398</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 404</PAGENUM><COURTJUR>&ldquo;C.A.&rdquo;</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Variance to the Mareva Order</EM></TI>
<P>13. Alternatively, should the court refuse to discharge the Mareva Order, the Mareva Order should be varied to exclude a limit on the amount that may be paid for legal advice and representation.</P>
<P>14. Where the assets of defendants are frozen are shown not to be proprietary to the plaintiff, the defendants should be permitted to use those assets to obtain legal counsel as:
<QUOTE><P>[i]t would be shocking if a litigant could prevent an opponent in a lawsuit from defending himself by foreclosing his ability to retain counsel.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bot Construction (Ontario) Ltd. v. Dumoulin</SOC><CITE>[2008] O.J. No. 1861</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>90 O.R. (3d) 680</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>&ldquo;O.S.C.J.&rdquo;</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>15. The footnote to the model order reads:
<QUOTE><P>This Order is not intended to limit a defendant in obtaining legal advice. Whether an amount is fixed or reasonable, and the ultimate amount if it is fixed, should depend on the entire context of the case and the evidence: e.g., a more complex case may require higher legal fees.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>16. Further, where a &ldquo;white knight&rdquo; has been found to pay for legal fees, it should be of no consequence to the plaintiff as the funds do not detract from the funds on hand which is the concern of any Mareva injunction.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hans v. Volvo Trucks North America Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 1123</CITE><PARANUM>140</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
