<BLOCK1><TI>APPLICATION RESPONSE</TI>
<P><BOLD>Application response of:</BOLD> The Plaintiff, Rong Wei, (the &ldquo;Application Respondent&rdquo;)</P>
<P>THIS IS A RESPONSE TO the notice of application of the Defendants filed February 12, 2019.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS CONSENTED TO</TI>
<P>The application respondent consents to the granting of no orders set out in Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>ORDERS OPPOSED</TI>
<P>The application respondent opposes the granting of the orders set out in paragraphs 1&ndash;4 of Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>ORDERS ON WHICH NO POSITION IS TAKEN</TI>
<P>The application respondent takes no position on the granting of no orders set out in Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>4:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Introduction</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The defendants have contemptuously breached the Mareva order that they now seek to set aside or vary, 21 months after its issuance. That is all the justification the Court requires for dismissing the application. The defendants dissipated assets (in the amount of hundreds of thousands of dollars) in defiance of a court order forbidding them from doing so. The defendants should not be given the ability to dissipate the remainder of the plaintiff's money in their hands.</P>
<P>2. The defendants admit to the receipt of substantial sums from the plaintiff. Mr. Chiu admitted on examination for discovery that he received funds from the plaintiff to invest on the plaintiff's behalf. He admitted that, at his direction, the plaintiff paid those funds to the defendant Queenie Lau and that the funds were deposited into a bank account belonging to Ms. Lau. He admitted that he owes money to the plaintiff. And he admitted that funds received from the plaintiff now are in his bank account in Hong Kong.</P>
<P>3. The evidence admitted to more than demonstrates a good arguable case. The defendants' spending of funds in breach of the Mareva order&mdash;for which Mr. Chiu already has been found in contempt of court and in relation to which an application to have Ms. Lau found in contempt of court is scheduled for hearing next Tuesday&mdash;shows a substantial risk of dissipation. If, as is the case, the defendants have dissipated assets with (and despite) a Mareva order in place, the court can and should have no hesitation in concluding that the balance of convenience favours maintaining the Mareva order.</P>
<P>4. Accordingly, the defendants' application to discharge or vary the May 18, 2017 Mareva order (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Mareva Order</BOLD>&rdquo;) should be refused for any or all of the following reasons:
<P1>(a) In accordance with settled law, the Court should decline to hear an application by the defendants unless and until the defendants purge their contempt. Both Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau have failed to comply with the Mareva Order. Mr. Chiu already has been found in contempt for contravening the Mareva Order, and Ms. Lau has a contempt hearing on February 19 based on spending in excess of what the Mareva Order permits.
<QUOTE><P>There is a well-settled rule that the court will not entertain an application by a person who is in contempt of court until he or she has purged him or herself of that contempt. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hadkinson v. Hadkinson</SOC><CITE>[1952] 2 All E.R. 567</CITE></CASEREF>, Lord Denning traced the origin of the rule in Chancery back to an ordinance of Lord Bacon in the year 1618, which laid down that &ldquo;they that are in contempt... are not to be heard [<EM>sic</EM>] neither in that suit, nor any other, except the court of special grace suspend the contempt&rdquo;.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bettinson v. Bettinson</SOC><CITE>[1965] 1 All E.R. 102</CITE><COURTJUR>Ch. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, per Plowman J.</P1>
<P1>(b) The defendants' repeated breaches of the Mareva Order, by spending in excess of what the order of this court permitted, demonstrates a high risk of dissipation which justifies maintaining the Mareva Order; hundreds of thousands of dollars that were in the bank accounts of the defendants when this court granted the Mareva Order have vanished since.
<QUOTE><P>[T]he key requirement for any Mareva injunction ... is that it shall accord with the rationale upon which Mareva relief has been based in the past. That rationale, legitimate purpose and fundamental principle I have already stated, namely, that no court should permit a defendant to take action designed to frustrate subsequent orders of the court.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Derby &amp; Co. Ltd. v. Weldon (Nos. 3 and 4)</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 W.L.R. 412, 422</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>(c) The defendants belatedly, 21 months after the order was made, and only weeks before the current trial date, offer contradictory evidence, but that does not amount to non-disclosure; the application for the Mareva Order was on notice to the defendants (pursuant to an order for short leave and substitutional service); counsel drew to the attention of the experienced chambers judge that there was evidence from one side only.
<QUOTE><P>In these circumstances I conclude that this was not really a without notice application. Although the notice given was very short, notice was given, short leave was granted and, as I have indicated earlier, Eilat's counsel made submissions on the substantive application.</P>
<P><UNDER>In light of this. Eilat's submissions on Skeena's alleged failure to make full and frank disclosure, arguments that are more suited to cases where an order has been obtained truly without notice, have much less significance</UNDER>. I will, in any event, address those points shortly.</P>
<P>[Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Skeena Resources Limited v Eilat Exploration Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 616</CITE><PARANUM>71-72</PARANUM></CASEREF>, per BlokJ.</P1>
<P1>(d) In any event, the hearing now is <EM>de novo</EM> and the evidence, including admissions made by the first defendant Allan Chiu on examination for discovery, more than meets the standard for the granting of a Mareva order: (1) the plaintiff has deposed that she entrusted funds to the defendants to invest on the plaintiff's behalf; (2) the defendants admit in their Response to Civil Claim the receipt of over $1 million from the plaintiff; (3) Mr. Chiu admits the funds were entrusted to him to invest on the plaintiff's behalf (save for US $200,000 which he claims was a loan); (4) Mr. Chiu admits that he owes money to the plaintiff; (5) Mr. Chiu admits that funds received from the plaintiff not already spent (some evidently to repay his gambling debts to loan sharks) now are in his bank account in Hong Kong; and (6) bank records of the defendants show that funds from the plaintiff were spent by the defendants on their own account, confirming the allegation of the plaintiff.
<QUOTE><P>The application is a hearing <EM>de novo</EM>. The court may consider new or additional material that is put forward as well as the evidence on the original application.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>In conclusion, the defendants' attempt to assert prejudice as a basis to set aside the <EM>Mareva</EM> Order overlooks their own conduct, their acknowledgment that money is owed and past due to the plaintiffs, and is defeated by their <EM>laches</EM>. The balance of convenience continues to weigh heavily in favour of the plaintiffs. The plaintiffs have established on this <EM>de novo</EM> application that the defendants are engaged in an effort to frustrate payment of monies justly owing to them.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Otal v Azure Foods Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1655</CITE><PARANUM>2 and 107</PARANUM></CASEREF>, per Walker J.</P1>
<P1>(e) The defendants' evidence falls short of what is required to justify a variation of the Mareva Order; the defendants by their own breaches of the order already have had access to hundreds of thousands of dollars, for which they need to account fully and with specificity before this court should permit further access to the frozen funds. Moreover, there is a higher test that the defendants must meet when they seek to access funds that the plaintiff says belong to her. The evidence of the defendants does not satisfy their legal burden.
<QUOTE><P>[A] defendant seeking the release (from the effect of a freezing injunction) of assets over which the plaintiff claims a proprietary interest must meet a different and more demanding test.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Simon Fraser University v. Saidi</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 2287</CITE><PARANUM>5</PARANUM></CASEREF> <EM>per</EM> Holmes J. (as she then was)</P1>
<P1>(f) Finally, even if the court were to discharge or vary the Mareva Order, the court should grant a preservation order over the funds in Mr. Chiu's Hong Kong bank account and order those funds to be paid into court, pursuant to Rule 10-1(1) and (2).
<QUOTE><P>The point of the proposed appeal is to cover the possibility that this court may set aside the <EM>Mareva</EM> injunction. While many issues on a preservation order are the same ones addressed on a <EM>Mareva</EM> injunction, it is possible that the <EM>Mareva</EM> injunction could be set aside for reasons that do not touch the availability of a preservation order. In that circumstance, Kepis &amp; Pobe wishes this court to have the capacity to reinstate a preservation order in lieu of a <EM>Mareva</EM> injunction.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kepis &amp; Pobe Financial Group v. Timis</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 293</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>, per Saunders J.A. (In Chambers)</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Mareva Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. This case concerns the actions of Mr. Chiu and his wife Queenie Lau, who between 2015 and 2016 received from the plaintiff, Rong (Eliza) Wei, approximately USD$1.1 million to invest on her behalf. As stated above, it is admitted that funds were received from the plaintiff for that purpose and that money is owed to the plaintiff.
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Eliza Wei, paras. 16-17, 28-29, 39-40, 53-54, 57-58 and 62-63;</P1>
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Catherine Flores, Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; (Transcript of Examination for Discovery of Allan Chiu), Q395&ndash;400, p. 61; Q408&ndash;411, p. 83; Q464-465, p. 95; Q480&ndash;488, pp. 98-99; Q492, p. 99; Q494-495, pp. 100-101; Q498&ndash;500, p. 101; Q516&ndash;526, pp. 105-106; Q585-586, p. 120; Q594&ndash;597, p. 121; Q632, pp. 127-128; Q636-637, p. 128; Q659&ndash;665, pp. 132-133; Q670-671, p. 134; Q683, p. 137; Q687-688, p. 138; Q691-692, p. 139)</P1></P>
<P>6. Ms. Wei filed her Notice of Civil Claim on May 12, 2017 claiming the sum of approximately $1.5 million on account of the principal amounts provided by Ms. Wei to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau. On May 18, 2017, Humphries J. granted the Mareva Order, the terms of which provided that the defendants not in any way dispose of or deal with or diminish the value of any of their assets whether they are in or outside British Columbia whether in their own names or not and whether solely or jointly owned. Paragraph 4 of the Mareva Order imposed the following restrictions on the defendants' spending:
<QUOTE><P>This Order does not prohibit the defendants from spending $3,500.00 each per month on ordinary living expenses and a total of $25,000.00 each on legal advice and representation. Before spending any money on living, business or legal expenses, the defendant must advise the plaintiff's solicitors in writing of the intended source of the funds.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>7. On December 4, 2018, Mr. Justice Grauer varied the Mareva Order with the consent of the defendants, to reduce the amount that Ms. Lau is permitted to spend each month on ordinary living expenses to $1,000 per month.</P>
<P>8. The Mareva Order was not made <EM>ex parte</EM>, but rather was made on short notice pursuant to an order of Master Scarth made on May 16, 2017. The defendants were served with the application materials on May 16, 2017, which consisted of the Notice of Application for a Mareva injunction, two affidavits sworn by the plaintiff and one affidavit sworn by John Hilpert, a private investigator hired by the plaintiff.</P>
<P>9. Notwithstanding that the application was not <EM>ex parte</EM>, the plaintiff brought a number of additional considerations to the court's attention during the hearing of the application, including the following:
<P1>(a) The application relied mainly on evidence from the Plaintiff herself, and that the nature of the representations made by the Defendants, and the basis on which they received funds from her, was not corroborated by another witness.</P1>
<P1>(b) There was no evidence as to the whereabouts of the defendant Ms. Lau or that she could no longer be found at her residence. Accordingly, the court could not draw an inference that Ms. Lau had recently gone into hiding.</P1>
<P1>(c) Paragraphs 17&ndash;21 of Mr. Hilpert's affidavit contain hearsay evidence provided to Mr. Hilpert by a confidential informant that was not named. The evidence supported the order sought even if paragraphs 17&ndash;21 of Mr. Hilpert's affidavit were not relied upon.</P1>
<P1>(d) The plaintiff's first affidavit referred to information provided to her by private investigators in Asia. Her evidence of what those private investigators told her (at paragraphs 90 and 93 of her first affidavit) might be viewed as double hearsay (but was not relied on for its truth).</P1></P>
<P>10. On August 18, 2017, further to efforts to have the Mareva Order recognized and enforced in Hong Kong, the Plaintiff obtained an <EM>ex parte</EM> injunction and preservation order and <EM>ex parte</EM> disclosure order (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Hong Kong Order</BOLD>&rdquo;), which provided, among other things, that the Mareva Order be enforced in Hong Kong and the Defendants not remove, dispose of or deal with their assets.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Defendants' Non-Compliance with the Mareva Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. On January 9, 2019, Madam Justice Baker found Mr. Chiu in contempt of court for contravening the Mareva Order. The sentencing portion of the application has not yet been heard. Mr. Chiu has not purged his contempt.</P>
<P>12. The defendants were served with the Mareva Order on May 20, 2017 (Hong Kong time) and shortly thereafter contacted counsel in Vancouver. Between May 20 to May 24, Mr. Chiu withdrew approximately HKD $1,678,959 from his HKD Account with Bank of China (the &ldquo;<BOLD>HKD Account</BOLD>&rdquo;) and USD $90,000 from his USD Account with Bank of China (the &ldquo;<BOLD>USD Account</BOLD>&rdquo;), totalling more than CAD $400,000 based on the Bank of Canada foreign exchange rate posted on February 12, 2019.</P>
<P>13. In the subsequent weeks and months, Mr. Chiu withdrew additional amounts from his USD Account and HKD Account in excess of the monthly living allowances under the Mareva Order. A summary of Mr. Chiu's withdrawals from May 20&mdash;August 4, 2017 is attached as <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this Application Response.</P>
<P>14. On February 5, 2019, Ms. Wei filed a Notice of Application for an order that Ms. Lau be found in contempt of court for contravening paragraphs 1 and 4 of the Mareva Order. The application is scheduled for Tuesday, February 19, 2019.</P>
<P>15. The evidence filed in support of that application demonstrates that on May 29, 2017, after being served with the Mareva Orcler, USD$154,000 was withdrawn from Ms. Lau's CIBC US dollar account #XXXXXXXXXX at 5796 University Boulevard, Vancouver. The evidence also demonstrates that Ms. Lau has breached the Mareva Order by spending in excess of the monthly amount permitted ($3,500 per month from May 2017 to November 2018, and $1,000 per month as of December 4, 2018) in at least May 2017, October 2017, November 2017, December 2017, January 2017, February 2018, March 2018, May 2018, June 2018, July 2018, August 2018, September 2018, October 2018, November 2018, and December 2018. That spending is outlined in the table appended as <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> to this Notice of Application.</P>
<P>16. Expenditures made in those months include:
<P1>(a) monthly payments of $1,260.12-$1,289.59 to lease and insure a 2017 BMW X4 M40i, which lease Ms. Lau entered on September 9, 2017, after the Mareva Order;</P1>
<P1>(b) purchases of $1,192.80 at Holt Renfrew on May 6, 2018 (as charged to her Hudson Bay Mastercard);</P1>
<P1>(c) purchases of $3,090.21 at Holt Renfrew, SSense, JCrew and Uniqlo in the month of June 2018 (as charged to her Hudson Bay MasterCard and Costco Platinum MasterCard).</P1></P>
<P>17. Ms. Wei's application also seeks an order that Ms. Lau be found in contempt of court for failing to attend her scheduled examination for discovery.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>5:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Court Ought Not Consider the Application until Defendants Purge their Contempt</UNDER></TI>
<P>18. As a general rule, courts will not hear further applications by persons in breach of a court order unless there is a convincing explanation given of the impossibility of compliance with the court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kwong v. Kwong</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 679</CITE><PARANUM>18&ndash;24</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>19. Contempt of court is an issue between a party and the court. It is not concerned with the merits of the dispute between parties to litigation, but rather strikes at the heart of the administration of justice. Court orders must be respected, even orders that the defendants consider were improperly or improvidently granted. The law is clear that an order of the court must be obeyed until it is reversed or varied.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Larkin v. Glase</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 321</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Sabourin and Sun Group of Companies v. Laiken</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 530</CITE><PARANUM>47</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>20. In <EM>Larkin</EM>, Mr. Justice Chiasson noted that there is clear authority for the Court of Appeal to refuse to hear an appeal where the order under appeal has not been obeyed. The refusal to hear an appeal is based on the policy of the court to protect the administration of justice by avoiding circumstances where the court could be held in disrepute by assisting a party who has exhibited disdain for the judicial process.
<P1><EM>Larkin</EM> at paras. 30&ndash;34</P1></P>
<P>21. Those principles&mdash;and the underlying rationale supporting them&mdash;apply similarly to applications brought by parties in breach of court orders in the Supreme Court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>XY, LLC v. Canadian Topsires Selection Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 2284</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>22. Mr. Chiu was recently found in contempt of court for breaching the Mareva Order and has not purged his contempt. Ms. Lau is similarly in breach of the Mareva Order and has a contempt motion scheduled for February 19, 2019. The court should decline to hear an application by the defendants until they have purged their contempt.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>There is No Basis to Set Aside the Mareva Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>23. An application to set aside a Mareva injunction is a hearing <EM>de novo</EM>. The court may consider new or additional material that is put forward as well as the evidence on the original application.
<P1><EM>Otal</EM> at para. 2</P1></P>
<P>24. Where a defendant asserts that a plaintiff has failed to disclose to the court material information, a plaintiff will not be held to have failed in its duty to make full and frank disclosure on the basis of &ldquo;mere imperfections in an affidavit or because inconsequential facts&rdquo; were not disclosed. In order for misrepresentations or omissions to result in an order being set aside, they &ldquo;must be relevant and material to the discretion to be exercised by the Court&rdquo;. A material fact is one that &ldquo;may or might affect the outcome of an application&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R&amp;D Arts inc. v. Feld</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 1896</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>25. An applicant on an <EM>ex parte</EM> chambers application is expected to present the factual matrix as it was able to see it, with the evidence available to it at the time.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Global Chinese Press Inc. v. Zhang</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 874</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>26. The legal principles pertaining to &ldquo;full and frank&rdquo; disclosure that apply on <EM>ex parte</EM> applications for a Mareva injunction have much less significance where the application is brought on short notice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Skeena Resources Limited v Eilat Exploration Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 616</CITE><PARANUM>71-72</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>27. The plaintiff's application for a Mareva injunction was brought on notice to the defendants. The defendants' arguments that the plaintiff failed to make full and frank disclosure in an <EM>ex parte</EM> application are thus irrelevant.</P>
<P>28. But even if the defendants' motion is considered on its merits, the defendants have not met their burden of establishing that the plaintiff did not make full and frank disclosure.</P>
<P>29. The defendants do not appear to be asserting that the plaintiff made any misrepresentations or omissions during the hearing. The defendants did not attend the hearing and have not included a transcript of the hearing in the record. The defendants have rather focused on the evidence filed in support of the application and effectively argue that the affiants, the plaintiff and Mr. Hilpert, omitted certain facts.</P>
<P>30. Most of the &ldquo;facts&rdquo; that the defendants suggest were omitted were effectively the defendant Mr. Chiu's evidence that he did not make certain representations attributed to him by the plaintiff. Those cannot be &ldquo;misrepresentations&rdquo; or &ldquo;omissions&rdquo; in the context of an application for a Mareva injunction. The plaintiff asserts the representations were made; the defendant denies making them. Those are contested facts that will be adjudicated at trial.</P>
<P>31. The plaintiff, during submissions, drew to the attention of the court that the evidence filed in support of the application for a Mareva Order was the evidence of one side only.</P>
<P>32. The defendants also refer to several passages from Mr. Hilpert's affidavit that were on information and belief from unnamed informants. Once again, the plaintiff brought those matters to the court's attention during the hearing and explained why the identity of the informants was not disclosed.</P>
<P>33. The defendants have failed to articulate how any of the alleged &ldquo;misrepresentations&rdquo; from the hearing were material in the sense that they may have affected the outcome of the application. (And it is difficult to conceive how they could do so without the transcript of the hearing and the decision of Humphries J.).</P>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ms. Wei has a Strong Prima Facie Case</EM></TI>
<P>34. When the issue of granting the Mareva Order is considered <EM>de novo</EM> in light of the current evidence, the justification for continuing the Mareva Order is compelling.</P>
<P>35. Ms. Wei has provided evidence demonstrating that she provided significant funds to the defendants, and that those funds or any investments purchased by them were to be held in trust for Ms. Wei. With the exception of USD$34,000, the defendants have failed to repay the principal amounts advanced by Ms. Wei and have failed to transfer to Ms. Wei any investments held by them in trust for Ms. Wei.</P>
<P>36. The defendants admit in their Response to Civil Claim to receiving over $1 million from the plaintiff. Mr. Chiu admits that the funds were entrusted to him to invest on the plaintiff's behalf (save for US $200,000 which he claims was a loan), and that the funds were paid to Ms. Lau. Mr. Chiu admits that funds received from the plaintiff not already spent are in his bank account in Hong Kong. Bank records produced by the defendants show that funds from the plaintiff were spent by the defendants on their own account, confirming the allegation of the plaintiff. The evidence adduced by Ms. Wei on this application clearly establishes that she has a strong prima facie case.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Risk of Dissipation and Balance of Convenience</EM></TI>
<P>37. The court may infer risk of asset dissipation from the circumstances and the defendant's pattern of prior behaviour, especially where those circumstances and prior behaviour involve fraud or misrepresentation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>East Guardian v. Mazur</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 6403</CITE><PARANUM>67-68</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>38. There is a significant risk of dissipation in this case. Mr. Chiu already has been found in contempt of court for withdrawing funds in breach of the Mareva Order. Ms. Lau is similarly in breach of the Mareva Order, with a contempt hearing set for February 19, 2019.</P>
<P>39. Mr. Chiu has also sworn an affidavit admitting he lied to his former counsel, Kieran Siddall, that Ms. Lau was in China and unable to attend her scheduled examination for discovery on September 27, 2018. Ms. Lau was not in fact in China, but was in Vancouver, where both she and Mr. Chiu were observed by a private investigator in the days leading up to Ms. Lau's examination for discovery, as well as on the scheduled date itself. Mr. Chiu subsequently lied to his counsel that he was also in China and no longer resided in Vancouver.</P>
<P>40. The defendants' continual disregard for court orders and the court process demonstrate a genuine risk that they will do whatever they can to further dissipate or dispose of whatever funds or assets they currently have.</P>
<P>41. The balance of convenience in this case clearly favours Ms. Wei.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>There is No Basis to Vary the Mareva Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>42. The alternative relief sought by the defendants is to vary the Mareva Order to exclude a limit on the amount that may be paid for legal advice and representation.</P>
<P>43. The plaintiff in this case seeks both personal and proprietary relief. Ms. Wei is asserting a proprietary claim to funds and assets owned by the defendants as part of her claims for breach of trust, unjust enrichment and fraud. Ms. Wei seeks a declaration of constructive trust and seeks to follow the funds as well as trace into any substitute assets that may have been acquired by the defendants. That includes any funds held in Mr. Chiu's Bank of China account in Hong Kong, which Mr. Chiu suggested contained&mdash;and still contains&mdash;the plaintiffs' funds.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Foskett v. McKeown</SOC><CITE>[2001] 1 A.C. 102</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2000] 3 All ER 97</CITE><PAGENUM>at 119-120</PAGENUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>44. Where a defendant seeks to vary a Mareva order to access funds falling with a proprietary claim by the plaintiff, the defendant must meet a different and more demanding test.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Simon Fraser University v. Saidi</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 2287</CITE><PARANUM>5</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>45. The test was set out in the following terms by Mr. Justice Goepel in <CASEREF><SOC>Right Business Limited v. Affluent Public Limited</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 1541</CITE></CASEREF>:
<P1>(a) Has the defendant established on the evidence that he has no other assets available to pay his expenses other than those frozen by the injunction?</P1>
<P1>(b) If so, has the defendant shown on the evidence that there are assets caught by the injunction that are from a source other than the plaintiff, i.e. assets that are subject to a Mareva injunction, but not a proprietary claim?</P1>
<P1>(c) The defendant is entitled to the use of non-proprietary assets frozen by the Mareva injunction to pay his reasonable living expenses, debts and legal costs. Those assets must be exhausted before the defendant is entitled to look to the assets subject to the proprietary claim.</P1>
<P1>(d) If the defendant has met the previous three tests and still requires funds for legitimate living expenses and to fund his defence, the court must balance the competing interests of the plaintiff in not permitting the defendant to use the plaintiff's money for his own purposes and of the defendant in ensuring that he has a proper opportunity to present his defence before assets in his name are removed from him without a trial. In weighing the interests of the parties, it is relevant for the court to consider the strength of the plaintiff's case, as well as the extent to which the defendant has put forward an arguable case to rebut the plaintiff's claim</P1></P>
<P>46. The evidence of the defendants does not meet the test necessary to vary the Mareva Order. The defendants have not provided evidence of the intended source of funds to pay their legal fees. The defendants have also failed to account for the hundreds of thousands of dollars withdrawn from Mr. Chiu's Bank of China account in breach of the Mareva Order.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Order Sought</UNDER></TI>
<P>47. The plaintiff seeks an order that the defendants' application be dismissed, with costs payable to the plaintiff in any event of the cause.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
