<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P>Name of applicant: Rong (Eliza) Wei</P>
<P>TO: Mui Kwan Queenie Lau also known as Mut Kwan Queenie Chiu and Allan Chiu</P>
<P>AND TO: Their Solicitors</P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge at the courthouse at 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver, British Columbia on February 14, 2019, at 9:45 a.m. for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. An order for the preservation of all funds held in Account Nos. XXXXXXXXXX and XXXXXXXXXX at Bank of China (Hong Kong) Limited (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Funds</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. An order that the defendant Allan Chiu forthwith pay the Funds into court.</P>
<P>3. Costs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. This case concerns the actions of Allan Chiu and his wife Queenie Lau, who between 2015 and 2016 received from the plaintiff, Rong (Eliza) Wei, approximately USD$1.1 million to invest on her behalf.</P>
<P>2. Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau did not invest the funds they received from Ms. Wei and did not provide Ms. Wei a return on her investment. Instead, Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau converted Ms. Wei's funds to their own uses. Despite repeated demands, Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau have failed to return to Ms. Wei all but USD$34,000 of the funds that she provided to them.</P>
<P>3. On May 18, 2017, Madam Justice Humphries granted a Mareva injunction against the defendants (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Mareva Order</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. On June 21, 2017, Mr. Chiu swore an affidavit verifying his assets in accordance with the Mareva Order (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Chiu Asset List</BOLD>&rdquo;). Mr. Chiu swore that that he held two accounts with Bank of China in Hong Kong. Mr. Chiu swore that he held HKD2,212.88 in Account No. XXXXXXXXXX (the &ldquo;<BOLD>HKD Account</BOLD>&rdquo;) and USD362,934.60 in Account No. XXXXXXXXXX (the &ldquo;<BOLD>USD Account</BOLD>&rdquo;) as of the date of the Mareva Order.</P>
<P>5. On January 22, 2019, Mr. Chiu was examined for discovery. Mr. Chiu gave evidence that he believed over USD400,000 received from Ms. Wei and deposited into Ms. Lau's account were transferred by Ms. Lau to Mr. Chiu's accounts at Bank of China in 2017.</P>
<P>6. Although Mr. Chiu subsequently withdrew large portions of Ms. Wei's funds from his accounts in Hong Kong (for which he has been found in contempt), there appears to be approximately $108,000 of Ms. Wei's funds remaining as of August 18, 2017 (the latest date for which Ms. Wei has evidence from Mr. Chiu).</P>
<P>7. Ms. Wei brings this application pursuant to Rule 10-1 of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> to preserve those funds by having the funds paid into court pending trial, currently scheduled to commence on March 4, 2019.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Mareva Order</UNDER></TI>
<P>8. Ms. Wei filed her Notice of Civil Claim on May 12, 2017 claiming the sum of approximately $1.5 million on account of the principal amounts provided by Ms. Wei to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau. Ms. Wei also sought interim and permanent injunctive relief restraining the defendants from disposing of their assets, as well as equitable relief, including tracing orders and orders that the defendants hold any real and personal property as constructive trustees.</P>
<P>9. On May 18, 2017, Humphries J. granted the Mareva Order, the terms of which provided that the Defendants not in any way dispose of or deal with or diminish the value of any of their assets whether they are in or outside British Columbia whether in their own names or not and whether solely or jointly owned.</P>
<P>10. On August 18, 2017, further to efforts to have the Mareva Order recognized and enforced in Hong Kong, the Plaintiff obtained an <EM>ex parte</EM> injunction and preservation order and <EM>ex parte</EM> disclosure order (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Hong Kong Order</BOLD>&rdquo;), which provided, among other things, that the Mareva Order be enforced in Hong Kong and the Defendants not remove, dispose of or deal with their assets.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Contempt Motion</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. On December 5, 2018, Ms. Wei filed an application for an order that Mr. Chiu be held in contempt of court for contravening the Mareva Order by withdrawing funds from his account at Bank of China after being served with the Mareva Order.</P>
<P>12. Mr. Chiu made an affidavit in response to Ms. Wei's Notice of Application on December 12, 2018. Mr. Chiu gave the following evidence:
<P1>(a) By the spring of 2017, Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau were having marital difficulties. In or around March 2017, Ms. Lau advised Mr. Chiu that she was going to transfer all funds that were held in her CIBC account that were related to the plaintiff to Mr. Chiu's accounts in Singapore and Hong Kong (paras. 2-3);</P1>
<P1>(b) As a result, in April and May 2017, Mr. Chiu received four transfers totalling USD445,000 from Ms. Lau's CIBC accounts into his accounts in Singapore and Hong Kong (para. 4);</P1>
<P1>(c) On May 10, 2017, Mr. Chiu travelled to Hong Kong with Ms. Lau (para. 5);</P1>
<P1>(d) Between May 16&ndash;23, 2017, Mr. Chiu transferred USD169,000 from his Standard Chartered Account in Singapore to his HKD Account (para. 6);</P1>
<P1>(e) Mr. Chiu needed to transfer the funds from Singapore to Hong Kong to settle gambling debts with loan sharks (para. 7);</P1>
<P1>(f) Between May 19, 2017 to July 31, 2017, the balance in Mr. Chiu's USD Account decreased by approximately USD300,000, going from USD362,934.60 (as set out in the Chiu Asset List) to USD67,483.60 (paras. 10-11); and</P1>
<P1>(g) Between May 19, 2017 to August 10, 2017, the balance in Mr. Chiu's HKD Account went from HKD2,212.88 (as set out in the Chiu Asset List) to HKD76,099.89. The amounts in the HKD Account included several transfers of funds from Mr. Chiu's USD Account (paras. 12-13).</P1></P>
<P>13. On January 9, 2019, Madam Justice Baker held Mr. Chiu in contempt for contravening the Mareva Order. The sentencing portion of the application has not yet been heard.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Examination for Discovery of Mr. Chiu</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. On January 22, 2019, Mr. Chiu was examined for discovery by counsel for Ms. Wei. During his examination, Mr. Chiu gave the following evidence that is material to this application:
<P1>(a) Mr. Chiu does not have any assets that are not listed in the Chiu Asset List (Q74, p. 12).</P1>
<P1>(b) Mr. Chiu owes Ms. Wei money (Q333&ndash;336, p, 67).</P1>
<P1>(c) Ms. Wei made several transfers of funds to Ms. Lau at Mr. Chiu's direction deposited into an account held by Ms. Lau at CIBC, of which more than USD400,000 was probably transferred to his Bank of China account in Hong Kong (Q395&ndash;400, p. 61; Q408&ndash;411, p. 83; Q464-465, p. 95; Q480&ndash;488, pp. 98-99; Q492, p. 99; Q494-495, pp. 100-101; Q498&ndash;500, p. 101; Q516&ndash;526, pp. 105-106; Q585-586, p. 120; Q594&ndash;597, p. 121; Q632, pp. 127-128; Q636-637, p. 128; Q659&ndash;665, pp. 132-133; Q670-671, p. 134; Q683, p. 137; Q687-688, p. 138; Q691-692, p. 139).</P1></P>
<P>15. Ms. Wei does not have evidence of the current balances in Mr. Chiu's Bank of China accounts, as Mr. Chiu has not produced his bank records indicating the present balances in his accounts. Ms. Wei is seeking production of up-to-date banking records from Mr. Chiu in an application scheduled for February 19, 2019. However, based on an affidavit sworn by Mr. Chiu in Hong Kong on September 7, 2017, Mr. Chiu, as of August 18, 2017, appears to have had HDK118,000 in his HKD Account and USD67,000 in his USD Account. Those amounts translate to approximately $108,000, based on the Bank of Canada daily exchange rates for February 12, 2019. Ms. Wei is asserting a proprietary claim to those funds as part of her claim for breach of trust.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>16. The court may grant a preservation order pursuant to Rule 10-1 of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, s. 39 of the <EM>Law and Equity Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 253 and its inherent jurisdiction.</P>
<P>17. Rule 10-1 provides in relevant part:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>The court may make an order for the detention, custody or preservation of any property that is the subject matter of a proceeding or as to which a question may arise and, for the purpose of enabling an order under this rule to be carried out, the court may authorize a person to enter on any land or building.</SSECP></SSEC>
<SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>If the right of a party to a specific fund is in dispute in a proceeding, the court may order the fund to be paid into court or otherwise secured.</SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>18. The test for a preservation order requires the court to consider the following:
<P1>a. The plaintiff has a proprietary interest in the property that is the subject of the application;</P1>
<P1>b. The plaintiff reasonably believes the property is imperiled;</P1>
<P1>c. There is a substantial question to be tried as to the applicant's entitlement to all the property; and</P1>
<P1>d. The balance of convenience favours granting a preservation order.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McKnight v. Hutchison</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 36</CITE><PARANUM>146</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Drozdzik v. O'Nions</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1181</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>19. Alternate phrasings of the test adopted in some cases are no different in substance.
<CASEREF><SOC>Tran v. 2506448 Ontario Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1163</CITE><PARANUM>44&ndash;51</PARANUM></CASEREF></P>
<P>20. With respect to Rule 10-1(2), a specific fund is one to which the plaintiff shows fact that, if proven at trial, would give it a right of property in the fund. The property claims must be &ldquo;sufficiently ascertainable&rdquo;. The property claims can be to a beneficial interest in the fund.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kongrecki v. Rafael</SOC><YEAR>1993</YEAR><CITE>81 B.C.L.R. (2d) 387</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1993] B.C.J. No. 1631</CITE><PARANUM>17&ndash;19</PARANUM></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Kashani v. Dhalla</SOC><CITE>2002 BCSC 1353</CITE><PARANUM>47</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Kabani v. 1266442 Ontario Inc.</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 1719</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>21. Where funds are transferred or used to purchase other property, tracing is available provided the path of the specific fund is clear.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gold Star Renovations Inc. v. Vinnik</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 6575</CITE><PARANUM>21&ndash;28</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Drucker, Inc. v. Hong</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 905</CITE><PARANUM>36&ndash;39</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>22. The evidence filed in support of this application satisfies each element of the test.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Ms. Wei has a proprietary interest in the property at issue</EM></TI>
<P>23. It is clear from Mr. Chiu's evidence on examination for discovery, as well as in his previously filed affidavit evidence, that funds received by Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau from Ms. Wei were transferred from Ms. Lau's CIBC account to Mr. Chiu's accounts with Bank of China in Hong Kong. Based on Mr. Chiu's evidence, and assuming Mr. Chiu complied with the Mareva Order after August 2017, there would appear to be approximately $108,000 of Ms. Wei's funds sitting in Mr. Chiu's USD Account and HKD Account at the Bank of China in Hong Kong.</P>
<P>24. Ms. Wei is asserting a proprietary claim to those funds as part of this action, which includes claims for breach of trust, unjust enrichment and fraud for failing to hold her funds in trust and invest them on her behalf. Ms. Wei seeks a declaration of constructive trust and seeks to follow the funds as well as trace into any substitute assets that may have been acquired by the defendants.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Foskett v. McKeown</SOC><CITE>[2001] 1 A.C. 102</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2000] 3 All ER 97</CITE><PAGENUM>at 119-120</PAGENUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>25. Mr. Chiu's evidence provides a direct link between the funds transferred by Ms. Wei to Ms. Lau at his direction to the funds in his Bank of China account in Hong Kong. Ms. Wei, if successful in her claim, will be entitled to the return of her funds as a remedy for breach of trust. The first element of the test is satisfied.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Risk of Dissipation</EM></TI>
<P>26. The court may infer risk of asset dissipation from the circumstances and the defendant's pattern of prior behaviour, especially where those circumstances and prior behaviour involve fraud or misrepresentation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>East Guardian v. Mazur</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 6403</CITE><PARANUM>67-68</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>27. There is a risk of dissipation in this case. Although the funds at issue are theoretically frozen by the Mareva Order, Mr. Chiu already has been found in contempt of that order for withdrawing funds in breach of the Mareva Order. Mr. Chiu has yet to purge his contempt.</P>
<P>28. Mr. Chiu has also sworn an affidavit admitting he lied to his former counsel, Kieran Siddall, that Ms. Lau was in China and unable to attend her scheduled examination for discovery on September 27, 2018. Ms. Lau was not in fact in China, but was in Vancouver, where both she and Mr. Chiu were observed by a private investigator in the days leading up to Ms. Lau's examination for discovery, as well as on the scheduled date itself. Mr. Chiu subsequently lied to his counsel that he was also in China and no longer resided in Vancouver.</P>
<P>29. Mr. Chiu's continual disregard for court orders and the court process demonstrate a genuine risk that Mr. Chiu will do whatever he can to further dissipate or dispose of the funds currently held in the HKD Account and the USD Account.</P>
<P>30. In addition, the Defendants have applied, on one day's notice, for an order discharging the Mareva Order currently scheduled to be heard on February 14, 2019. Ms. Wei will be opposing that application. But in the event the Defendants are successful in discharging the Mareva Order, a preservation order is essential to ensuring the integrity of the Funds pending trial.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kepis &amp; Pobe Financial Group Inc. v. Timis Corporation</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 293</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM><COURTJUR>In Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>There is a Substantial Question to be Tried</EM></TI>
<P>31. This part of the test has been held to have a relatively low threshold for success. The court need not dwell too long on the evidence, nor should it measure the application by the likelihood of the applicant's eventual success at trial. The plaintiff is not required to establish a <EM>prima facie</EM> case.
<P1><EM>Kabani</EM> at para. 39; <EM>Kashani</EM> at para. 51</P1></P>
<P>32. Ms. Wei has provided evidence demonstrating that she provided significant funds to the defendants, and that those funds or any investments purchased by them were to be held in trust for Ms. Wei. With the exception of USD$34,000, the defendants have failed to re-pay the principal amounts advanced by Ms. Wei and have failed to transfer to Ms. Wei any investments held by them in trust for Ms. Wei.</P>
<P>33. Mr. Chiu, during his examination for discovery, admitted that he owes money to Ms. Wei. The evidence adduced by Ms. Wei on this application clearly establishes that there is a substantial question to be tried in this case.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Balance of Convenience Favours Granting the Order Sought</EM></TI>
<P>34. In <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Broadcasting Corp. v. CKPG Television Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>64 B.C.L.R. (2d) 96</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1992] B.C.J. No. 247</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 5</PAGENUM></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Mr. Justice Lambert set out a list of factors to be considered in assessing the balance of convenience. Lambert J.A. noted that the list is not exhaustive, and the relevant factors will vary from case to case:
<P1>(a) the adequacy of damages as a remedy for the applicant if the injunction is not granted and for the respondent if an injunction is granted;</P1>
<P1>(b) the likelihood that if damages are finally awarded they will be paid;</P1>
<P1>(c) the preservation of contested property;</P1>
<P1>(d) other factors affecting whether harm from the granting or refusal of the injunction would be irreparable;</P1>
<P1>(e) which of the parties has acted to alter the balance of their relationship and so affect the status quo;</P1>
<P1>(f) the strength of the applicant's case;</P1>
<P1>(g) any factors affecting the public interest; and</P1>
<P1>(h) any other factors affecting the balance of justice and convenience.</P1></P>
<P>35. With respect to (a) through (d), Mr. Chiu's evidence at his examination for discovery was that he has no assets other than the assets listed in the Chiu Asset List. It thus appears that Mr. Chiu has no assets of any tangible value in British Columbia, or anywhere in Canada, that would be available to satisfy a judgment. Moreover, Hong Kong is not a reciprocating jurisdiction under the <EM>Court Order Enforcement Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 78, s. 37. A preservation order in the form sought by Ms. Wei is necessary to ensure the funds in Mr. Chiu's HKD Account and USD Account with Bank of China in Hong Kong to which Ms. Wei asserts a propriety claim are preserved until trial.</P>
<P>36. With respect to (e), it is the Defendants that have altered the status quo by first transferring Ms. Wei's funds from Ms. Lau's bank account in Vancouver to Mr. Chiu's bank accounts in Singapore and Hong Kong. Mr. Chiu further altered the status quo by breaching the terms of the Mareva Order by withdrawing further funds from his accounts in Hong Kong, for which he has been found in contempt. (Ms. Wei has a pending motion to have Ms. Lau similarly found in contempt of the Mareva Order, scheduled for February 19, 2019.)</P>
<P>37. With respect to (f), the strength of Ms. Wei's case also supports the relief sought in this application. Ms. Wei provided significant funds to the defendants to invest on her behalf. The Defendants admit to receiving the funds from Ms. Wei, and Mr. Chiu admits he owes money to Ms. Wei. Ms. Wei has a strong case at trial for repayment of the sums she advanced to Mr. Chiu and Ms. Lau.</P>
<P>38. With respect to (g), it is in the public interest that the preservation order be granted. A preservation order will effectively return Ms. Wei's funds to British Columbia to be held pending trial in circumstances where Mr. Chiu admitted that those funds were transferred out of the jurisdiction into his accounts in Hong Kong in the months and weeks prior to the commencement of the action. Mr. Chiu has already been found in contempt for further dissipating those funds to pay gambling debts to loan sharks in breach of a Mareva Order. The circumstances of this case strongly support granting the order sought.</P>
<P>39. There is no prejudice to Mr. Chiu in making the order. On his evidence, the funds in his HKD Account and the USD Account contain funds originating from Ms. Wei. Moreover, those accounts are currently frozen by the Mareva Order, and Mr. Chiu should not be accessing them. Should the Defendants ultimately succeed in this action, the funds will be returned to them. It is Ms. Wei and Ms. Wei alone, who suffers prejudice if the preservation order is not granted.</P>
<P>40. The balance of convenience clearly favours Ms. Wei.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
