<BLOCK1><TI>APPLICATION RESPONSE</TI>
<P><BOLD>Application response of:</BOLD> The Application Respondents, Allan Chiu and <BOLD>Mui</BOLD> Kwan Queenie Lau (the &ldquo;Defendants&rdquo;)</P>
<P>THIS IS A RESPONSE TO the Notice of Application of the Plaintiff, Rong Wei, filed February 13, 2019.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS CONSENTED TO</TI>
<P>The Application Respondent consents to the granting of the Orders set out in the following paragraphs of Part 1 of the Notice of Application on the following terms:</P>
<P>1. The application respondent consents to the granting of no orders set out in Part 1 of the Notice of Application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>ORDERS OPPOSED</TI>
<P>1. The application respondent opposes the granting of the orders set out in paragraphs 1&ndash;3 of Part 1 of the Notice of Application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>ORDERS ON WHICH NO POSITION IS TAKEN</TI>
<P>1. The application respondent takes no position on the granting of no orders set out in Part 1 of the Notice of Application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>4:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Nature of the Plaintiff and Mr. Chiu's Relationship</EM></TI>
<P>1. The plaintiff has admitted that the plaintiff and Mr. Chiu were at times involved in a romantic way and trips to Singapore and Europe.
<P1><EM>Affidavit #1 of R. Wei</EM> at paras. 68-69</P1></P>
<P>2. The lavish spending was a joint enterprise. Mr. Chiu spent over $140,000 USD on the international trips and the source of the funds was money being held for the plaintiff with credit card payments being paid by funds held on the plaintiff's behalf with her knowledge.
<P1><EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 109.</P1></P>
<P>3. However, the plaintiff and the defendant were involved in every aspect of each other's life and at the plaintiff's request, Mr. Chiu was involved in numerous aspects of the plaintiffs life which included:
<P1>(a) as early as May 31, 2016, the plaintiff requested the defendant was assisting with her daughter's educational planning and the two were planning trips to meet each other (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at Exhibit G&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(b) in June 2016, the plaintiff and Mr. Chiu travelled to Singapore together (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 85);</P1>
<P1>(c) in October of 2016, the plaintiff requested the defendant assist with the plaintiffs son's field trip (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at Exhibit Gla&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(d) in September 2016, the plaintiff and defendant travelled to Europe together, it was after this trip to Europe where Mr. Chiu asked for a personal loan and the plaintiff advised that funds provided and used were a gift and there was no expectation to repay the funds and, further, that funds could be used out of love and affection and the funds spent could be forgotten. An agreement was made to a conditional loan to repay sums borrowed and the loan would be offset by profits earned in trading accounts (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at Paragraph 128);</P1>
<P1>(e) In November, 2016, Ms. Wei began to suspect a reconciliation between the Defendants and delivered an e-mail demanding a return on investments that did not exist. (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 130 in response to paragraph 71.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Use of Fraudulent Records</EM></TI>
<P>4. The plaintiff has fraudulent created documents and sworn them to be true for the sole purpose of attempting to demonstrate funds transferred to the defendant were related to specific investments. Of note, the fraudulent statements include:
<P1>(a) As sworn at paragraph 30, the first page of Exhibit H to Wei Affidavit #1 was not provided to the plaintiff by Mr. Chiu and Mr. Chiu had never seen this document prior to receipt of the affidavit (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 60);</P1>
<P1>(b) As sworn at paragraph 31, Exhibit 1 to the Wei Affidavit #1 was not provided to the plaintiff and Mr. Chiu had never seen this document prior to receipt of the affidavit (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 61);</P1>
<P1>(c) As sworn at paragraph 36, the first page of Exhibit K to the Wei Affidavit #1 was not provided to the plaintiff and had not been seen prior to receipt of the affidavit (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 66);</P1>
<P1>(d) As sworn at paragraph 59, Exhibit S to the Wei Affidavit #1 was not provided to the plaintiff and had not been seen prior to reading the Wei #1 affidavit (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 66);</P1>
<P1>(e) As sworn at paragraph 73, Exhibit V to the Wei Affidavit was drafted by the plaintiff and while presented to the plaintiff, it was not signed by the Defendant and the signature located on the document is not that of Mr. Chiu (<EM>Affidavit #2 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 66).</P1></P>
<P>5. In order to explain the operation of underground banking, the Plaintiff provided a Bank of Montreal statement that includes the names of unknown individuals who provided funds to the plaintiff. The unknown individuals are part of the underground banking system who move small amounts of funds to avoid the attention of Chinese authorities.
<P1><EM>Affidavit #5 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 2</P1></P>
<P>6. On February 26, 2016 and March 7, 2016, the plaintiff confirmed that she was using underground banking to deliver funds to Canada and that the funds could be delivered from underground banking to wherever it was preferred.
<P1><EM>Affidavit #5 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraphs 4-5</P1></P>
<P>7. Further, the plaintiff advised that funds from underground banking were being deposited into her mother's account in Hong Kong to which the plaintiff had access.
<P1><EM>Affidavit #5 of Allan Chiu</EM> at paragraph 6</P1></P>
<P>8. It cannot be denied is that the plaintiff has used underground funds to facilitate the delivery of funds to Canada.</P>
<P>9. Further, the plaintiff has not produced any records to demonstrate the source of funds and cannot demonstrate the funds delivered are her own and not received through illegitimate sources.</P>
<P>10. The affidavit material of Ms. Wei contains evidence that Ms. Wei provided funds to the Defendants at various times but the source of the funds is conspicuously absent.</P>
<P>11. As a consequence of the evidence related to the transfer of funds from underground banks, as admitted, the sources of the funds Ms. Wei purported to provide to the plaintiff as her own are relevant to the action. To that end, a request for production of banking records has been provided as well as an inquiry as to whether the promissory note contained at Exhibit V of Affidavit #1 of Rong Wei.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>5:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. The defendant accepts the four part test for a preservation order as described by the plaintiff at paragraph 18 of the Notice of Application.</P>
<P>2. The funds provided were provided to Mr. Chiu out of love and affection or, alternatively, as a loan that would be repaid when Mr. Chiu had the capacity to do so. The plaintiff has not led sufficient evidence to satisfy the third part of the test that there is a substantial question to be tried.</P>
<P>3. While it is accepted that the threshold for success is relatively low and that the plaintiff is not required to establish a <EM>prima facie</EM> case, the claim for funds grossly exceeds the amount of money that Mr. Chiu admitted owing to Ms. Wei.</P>
<P>4. The doctrine of unjust enrichment is an equitable concept. Even if a plaintiff establishes a <EM>prima facie</EM> claim of unjust enrichment, the court must additionally assess whether the clean hands doctrine precludes the remedies sought.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Craiggs v. Owens</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 29</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Craiggs]</P1></P>
<P>5. The clean hands doctrine was described as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The clean hands doctrine serves to deny equitable relief where the misdeeds or misconduct has &ldquo;an immediate and necessary relation to the equity sued for... it must be shown, in order to justify a refusal or relief, that there is such an &ldquo;immediate and necessary relation&rdquo; between the relief sought and the delinquent behaviour in question that it would be unjust to grant that particular relief.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Craiggs, Mayer v. Osborne Contracting Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1249</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>6. While the plaintiff has transferred funds to the Defendants, material misrepresentation and non&mdash;disclosure in attaining the Mareva order and the use of underground banking raises a reasonable suspicion that the funds she says are owed are not her own and, more importantly, are potentially received through immoral and potentially illegal sources.</P>
<P>7. Of the relevant factors delineated by Lambert J.A., in C.B.C. assessing the balance of convenience include the strength of the applicant's case, factors affecting the public's trust, and factors affecting the balance of justice and convenience.</P>
<P>8. In that regard, while the defendants admit receiving the funds and that some money is owing, the plaintiff has fraudulently created documents to significantly inflate the scope of the claim and has used a mechanism, underground banking, to deliver significant funds that are dishonest and unethical.</P>
<P>9. The defence of <EM>ex turpi causa</EM>, meaning a person cannot found a claim of action based on her own illegal or immoral acts, is a complete answer to the claims of the plaintiff.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Norberg v. Wynrib</SOC><CITE>[1992] 2 S.C.R. 266</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 79.</P1></P>
<P>10. <EM>Ex turpi causa</EM> is concerned with the enforcement of rights by the courts and the courts will not enforce what would otherwise be enforceable if the right arises out of an act committed by the person asserting the right which is sufficiently anti-social to justify the courts refusing to enforce that right.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hardy v. Motor Insurers' Bureau</SOC><CITE>[1964] 2 All E.R. 742</CITE><COURTJUR>Eng. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>11. The effect of the rule is to bar a plaintiff from recovery for loss or injury which is suffered in connection with a course of conduct that is clearly reprehensible and involves the commission of breaches of the Criminal Code of Canada.</P>
<P>12. The minimum requirement of the doctrine is:
<P1>(a) the plaintiff must be engaged in conduct clearly reprehensible, typically in breach of the <EM>Criminal Code of Canada</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(b) there must be a connection between this activity and the loss or injury;</P1>
<P1>(c) the foregoing requirements are not alone to justify application of the doctrine as the court must additionally be satisfied that the offence is sufficiently reprehensible and its connection sufficiently close to be disentitled to assistance.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mandzukv. Vierira</SOC><CITE>[1986] B.C.J. No. 332</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>29 D.L.R. (4th) 677</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>BCSC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 17.</P1></P>
<P>13. <EM>Ex turpi causa</EM> is intended to defend the integrity of the legal system and the reputation in which the court ought to be held by law-abiding members of the community. The question to ask is this: is it manifestly unacceptable to fair-minded, or right-thinking, people that a court should lend assistance to a plaintiff who has defied the law.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mandzuk v. Vierira</SOC><CITE>[1986] B.C.J. No. 332</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>29 D.L.R. (4th) 677</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>BCSC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 19.</P1></P>
<P>14. A person commits an offence who knowingly makes a false statement in writing with the intent that it should be relied on with respect to financial condition... for the purpose of procuring... her benefit the making of a promissory note. The plaintiff has fraudulently made a false statement stating that the promissory note she prepared was signed by Mr. Chiu.
<P1><EM>Criminal Code (R.S.C. 1985, c. C-46)</EM>, s. 362(1)(c)(vi)</P1></P>
<P>15. The plaintiff has made multiple references to use of underground banks and the source of those funds is relevant in order to assess the potential of a violation of money laundering by using or sending funds from China to Canada, directly or occasionally through Hong Kong, with the intent to conceal the proceeds if the proceeds were obtained or derived from the commission of a crime or an act that, if it occurred in Canada, would have constituted an enterprise crime offence or substance offence.
<P1><EM>Criminal Code</EM>, s. 462.31</P1></P></BLOCK2>
