<BLOCK1><TI>APPLICATION RESPONSE</TI>
<P>Application response of: the Plaintiff, Eliza Wei (the &ldquo;<BOLD>application respondent</BOLD>&rdquo;)</P>
<P>THIS IS A RESPONSE TO the Notice of Application of the Defendant filed April 4, 2019.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS CONSENTED TO</TI>
<P>The application respondent consents to the granting of the orders set out in the following paragraphs of Part 1 of the notice of application on the following terms: NIL.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>ORDERS OPPOSED</TI>
<P>The application respondent opposes the granting of the orders set out in paragraphs 1-2 of Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>ORDERS ON WHICH NO POSITION IS TAKEN</TI>
<P>The application respondent takes no position on the granting of the orders set out in the following paragraphs of Part 1 of the notice of application on the following terms: NIL.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>4:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Defendant's Application is a Breach of a Court Order and Ought not to be Heard</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. On March 8, 2019, Madam Justice Dillon found the defendant Queenie Lau in contempt of court for &ldquo;flagrant&rdquo; and &ldquo;serious&rdquo; breaches of a <EM>Mareva</EM> Order obtained by the plaintiff in May 2017 and for failing to attend her examination for discovery without lawful excuse</P>
<P>2. Ms. Lau's recent contempt finding is but a continuation of a pattern of disrespect for court orders and the court process generally. Dillon J. described Ms. Lau's conduct in the litigation in the following terms:
<QUOTE><P>[43] It is apparent that Lau has treated this litigation cavalierly. She has failed to produce documents in a timely manner, or at all, thus thwarting until now attempts to determine whether assets have been dissipated and so frustrating the very purpose of the <EM>Mareva</EM> order. She has failed to attend at examinations for discovery without lawful excuse. She has seriously breached the <EM>Mareva</EM> order. She has caused delay of the trial. Lau had previously been put on notice that her response could be struck for failure to attend at examination for discovery. This is a serious matter.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>3. in light of Ms. Lau's conduct and failure to produce documents (including documents previously ordered produced by Mr. Justice Grauer on December 4, 2018), Dillon J. ordered Ms. Lau to produce copies of &ldquo;all bank and financial records in her name, in the name of any alias, or in the name of other entities which Lau exercises control from the period June 1, 2015 to the present, within 30 days of the date of this order (which was made on March 8, 2019)&rdquo;. (Notably, the documents ordered produced by Dillon J. included classes of documents captured by the previous order of Grauer J. that Ms. Lau did not comply with.)</P>
<P>4. As a result of Ms. Lau's pattern of conduct in this litigation, Dillon J.&mdash;on her own motion after a two-day hearing on March 4-5, 2019&mdash;expressly ordered that no application of Ms. Lau may be heard in this Court until Ms. Lau has complied with the above document production order. Dillon J. did not create a carve-out in her order for applications to vary her order.</P>
<P>5. Ms. Lau, as is clear from the nature of the application before this Court, has not complied with Dillon J.'s order.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>5:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. This Court should not entertain Ms. Lau's application. In light of Dillon J.'s order, and the underlying circumstances that led Dillon J, to grant the order on her own motion, Ms. Lau should not be proceeding in regular chambers on less than one day's notice, but rather should be before Dillon J. Of note, Ms. Lau's counsel submitted a Request to Appear before Dillon J. on April 2, underscoring that this application is properly heard by Dillon J. Ms. Lau's application is not properly before this Court and ought to be dismissed.</P>
<P>2. Dillon J.'s order was clear and reflected her findings of Ms. Lau's conduct in this litigation. Dillon J.'s finding that Ms. Lau was in contempt of Court and her description of Ms. Lau's conduct are buttressed by Bank of Montreal bank records produced by Ms. Lau on April 4, 2019. This bank account was opened by Ms. Lau after the issuance of the <EM>Mareva</EM> Order and never disclosed to plaintiff's counsel as a source of funds for monthly living expenses, which allowed her to surreptitiously access funds from that account in breach of the Mareva Order between October 2017 and December 2018.</P>
<P>3. The bank records produced yesterday cover the period from December 8, 2018 to March 7, 2019 and show that Ms. Lau also breached the monthly spending limit (which was varied from $3,500 to $1,000 pursuant to a consent order granted by Grauer J. on December 4, 2018) in the months of January and February 2019. Most egregiously, Ms. Lau spent more than $1,000 on February 20, 2019 on a monthly lease payment for her BMW&mdash;exactly one week <UNDER>after</UNDER> swearing an affidavit in response to the Plaintiff's motion that Ms. Lau be found in contempt for spending in excess of the monthly limit and failing to provide advance notice of the source of funds.</P>
<P>4. Should this Court decide to hear Ms. Lau's application, Ms. Lau's application for an extension should be dismissed. The Plaintiff will take no position on the application for the third-party financial institutions to produce records, provided that the order stipulate that copies of ail records produced are delivered to Plaintiffs counsel within two business days.</P>
<P>5. The sole legal basis articulated by Ms. Lau for an order for an extension is the court's inherent jurisdiction. The evidence simply does not support that the Court should be exercising its discretion in favour of Ms. Lau to yet again extend a deadline for the production of bank records.</P>
<P>6. This case has clear parallels with the decision of Madam Justice Choi in <CASEREF><SOC>MOBE, Ltd. v. Loudoun</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 2667</CITE></CASEREF>. In that case, the plaintiff obtained an order that the defendants produce certain classes of documents within 14 days. The defendants brought an application to extend the time under the order by an additional 21 days.</P>
<P>7. Choi J. noted that the defendant's application was &ldquo;highly discretionary&rdquo; (para. 11) and the question was whether it was &ldquo;just and convenient&rdquo; for the court to exercise its discretion to extend the deadline for production of documents (para. 14). Choi J. denied the defendant's application, citing the length of time that the request for documents had been outstanding:
<QUOTE><P>[14] For the reasons that follow, I decline to exercise my discretion to extend the time under the order. The documents ordered were originally requested in March 2016. The defendants were well aware of the documents and the information sought at least five months prior to the granting of the order. No holiday after August 31 should have caused the defendants to be unable to fulfil the order pronounced in the time required in these circumstances.</P>
<P>[15] The defendants' reasons for the delay do not warrant the court exercising its discretion in favour of the defendants. The defendants' application for extension of time is therefore dismissed.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>8. The facts of this case are even less deserving of the court granting Ms. Lau an indulgence. Not only is she before this Court having recently been found in contempt of a court order (for which she has not purged or even apologized), the extension Ms. Lau is seeking is to produce documents first requested in early October 2018. The documents were then ordered to be listed by Grauer J. by December 18, 2018, varied on the defendant's application to January 14, 2019.</P>
<P>9. Ms. Lau, although offering vague evidence about attempts to comply with Dillon J.'s most recent order, says nothing about steps taken after receiving the document demand in October 2018 or after the orders of Grauer J. and Master Scarth (for which she is in breach).</P>
<P>10. Although Ms. Lau in her affidavit attempts to deflect blame to various third-party financial institutions for her current plight, the fault lies with her and her alone. Dillon J.'s order was made on March 8, 2019. Ms. Lau's evidence of steps taken to comply with the order are that she signed an authorization permitting the release of records to her solicitors on March 18, 2019&mdash;ten days after the granting of the order&mdash;and to having placed calls to customer service departments of several of the third-party financial institutions on &ldquo;numerous occasions&rdquo;. Ms. Lau provides little details of her efforts in that regard, only providing specifics of calls made on March 31 and April 1 at a time when it must have been clear that she would be bringing this application and needed to adduce evidence of her &ldquo;efforts&rdquo; to comply with the order. It appears that even a finding of contempt and the imposition of strict terms is not enough to motivate Ms. Lau to comply with orders of this Court.</P>
<P>11. As in <EM>MOBE, Ltd.</EM>, Ms. Lau's excuses for the delay in producing documents do not warrant the Court exercising its discretion in favour of Ms. Lau. The application for an extension of time should be dismissed.</P>
<P>12. In the event that this Court decides to grant Ms. Lau's application, the Plaintiff says that the extension should be for no longer than 14 days. The documents ordered have been outstanding for six months. There is simply no justification to grant another 30-day extension, and there is no indication in the evidence that 30 is needed by any of the financial institutions.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>6:</N><TI>MATERIAL TO BE RELIED ON</TI>
<P>1. Affidavit #3 of Catherine Flores, made April 5, 2019.</P>
<P>2. Notice of Application of the Plaintiff dated November 21, 2018.</P>
<P>3. Order Made After Application of Mr. Justice Grauer dated December 4, 2018.</P>
<P>4. Order Made After Application of Master Scarth dated December 18, 2018.</P>
<P>5. Affidavit #3 of Queenie Lau made February 13, 2019.</P>
<P>6. Reasons for Judgment of Madam Justice Dillon dated March 8, 2019.</P>
<P>7. Such further and other material as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P>The application respondent estimates that the hearing of the application will take 30 minutes.
